<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FDA Opening OTC Drug Debate  </HEADLINE>
By LAURAN NEERGAARD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Envision powerful cholesterol-lowering drugs
sitting between the cough syrup and dental floss on store shelves --
no doctor's prescription required. Just toss a box of Mevacor or
Pravachol into the shopping cart and you're off.
</P>
<P>
   Is that a safe way to ward off a heart attack? And if the
government lets those cholesterol medicines start selling without a
prescription, what's next -- over-the-counter antibiotics or blood
pressure therapy or diabetes drugs?
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration this week begins debating major
changes in how it regulates over-the-counter drugs, and the fate of
Mevacor and Pravachol could signal whether a new wave of
nonprescription drugs is headed for a store near you.
</P>
<P>
   Cholesterol patients don't have the only stake. Consider the
allergy reliever Claritin. A prominent insurance company wants
Claritin to sell without a prescription like it does in Canada,
where a month's supply is about $17 instead of the $60, plus
doctor's fees, Americans pay.
</P>
<P>
   Money aside, Blue Cross of California argues nondrowsy Claritin
is safer than today's over-the-counter antihistamines that make
people sleepy, very dangerous if they're driving.
</P>
<P>
   But manufacturer Schering-Plough Corp. -- which is aggressively
lobbying Congress for patent extensions to preserve Claritin's
profits -- opposes selling nonprescription Claritin here. Can the
FDA, citing public safety, force the switch?
</P>
<P>
   They're serious dilemmas. On one side is better consumer access.
Prices usually drop when drugs move over the counter, and experts
say only a fraction of people who could benefit from nondrowsy
allergy relievers and powerful cholesterol drugs called ''statins''
use them.
</P>
<P>
   But critics question how you'd ever know without a doctor's exam
if simmering cholesterol was improving. Insurers seldom pay for
nonprescription drugs. Plus, if FDA forces Claritin over the
counter, it likely will wind up in court.
</P>
<P>
   ''Consumers are more interested in taking care of their own
health problems as much as they can,'' says Dr. Robert Delap, FDA's
chief of nonprescription drugs. ''We recognize that, and we're
reexamining ... what our policies should be.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate goes public Wednesday and Thursday, when the FDA
holds hearings in suburban Washington for consumers and advocacy
groups to voice opinions. (FDA also will accept written comments;
check http://www.fda.gov/bbs/topics/NEWS/NEW00725.html).
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, far more drugs could be affected. What about blood
pressure medicines, or the ''morning after'' pill that women need
in a hurry to prevent pregnancy? Look ahead to vaginal
''microbicides'' that companies are rapidly developing to protect
against the AIDS virus, products many advocates argue will have to
be nonprescription to help poor women.
</P>
<P>
   But the statins and Claritin are the first FDA must decide. Next
month, FDA's independent scientific advisers will formally vote on
Mevacor and Pravachol's fate. No Claritin deadline has been set.
</P>
<P>
   The cholesterol decision is overdue, says industry consultant
Steve Francesco, noting Americans already can buy an unregulated
dietary supplement called Cholestin that contains Mevacor's active
ingredient. Plus, there are FDA-approved cholesterol-lowering
margarines.
</P>
<P>
   ''These drugs are vastly superior than some of the nutritionals
out there, and yet the nutritionals are being marketed to the
public and these drugs are not,'' contends Francesco.
</P>
<P>
   But Mevacor and Pravachol patients today must get blood tests
against a rare side effect, liver damage, that would be impossible
if they don't see a doctor, argues consumer advocate Dr. Sidney
Wolfe of Public Citizen.
</P>
<P>
   As for Claritin, the FDA worries that people use today's
nonprescription but sleep-inducing allergy relievers, such as
Benadryl, before getting behind the wheel. Worried enough to say
the nondrowsy competitors Claritin, Allegra or Zyrtec should be
nonprescription, too?
</P>
<P>
   Delap demurs, saying, ''We need to find a way to accomplish what
needs to happen for the public health. But there are some legal
issues here that I would not say I have the final word on.''
</P>
<P>
   Schering contends Claritin should remain prescription-only
because ''allergies are a complex and potentially serious disease
that requires a high level of medical care.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We're talking about ... a runny nose,'' responds Blue Cross'
Robert Seidman, who petitioned FDA to force the change.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- Lauran Neergaard covers health and medical
issues for The Associated Press in Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-27-00 0013 </TRAILER>
