<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Golisano: Chances are I won't run for governor again  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - B. Thomas Golisano, the millionaire
Rochester businessman who twice ran unsuccessfully for governor as
the candidate of New York's arm of the national Reform Party, said
Monday the odds are against a third run.
</P>
<P>
   ''The chances are I won't,'' Golisano said.
</P>
<P>
   The founder and head of Paychex, a successful payroll processing
company, put the New York Independence Party on the electoral map,
when he collected 217,490 votes of the more than 5 million cast in
the 1994 governor's race.
</P>
<P>
   While he finished third behind election winner George Pataki and
then-Gov. Mario Cuomo, Golisano's vote surpassed the 50,000-vote
threshold needed in New York to gain the Ross Perot-inspired party
an automatic spot on the state ballot for the next four years.
</P>
<P>
   Golisano did even better in the 1998 election, when he won
364,056 votes on the Independence line as Pataki won a second term.
The Golisano vote not only maintained the party's automatic spot on
the ballot for another four years, but moved it into third place on
the ballot behind the Republicans and Democrats, pushing the state
Conservative Party into fourth place.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, a party's vote for governor determines its spot on
the ballot. Higher spots are considered more advantageous.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he might not run for governor again, Golisano said
Monday, ''Why not? Maybe the question should be, 'Why should I?'''
</P>
<P>
   Golisano said in a telephone interview that he was busy
''running my company'' and was not disillusioned by his two
unsuccessful runs.
</P>
<P>
   While New York's Independence Party has been riven by leadership
battles in recent months, Golisano said he felt it remained strong
and would likely survive such internal disagreements.
</P>
<P>
   ''Leadership, just like governmental leadership, comes and
goes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Noting recent enrollment figures from the state Board of
Elections that showed the Independence Party had surpassed the
Conservative Party in actual membership, 172,471 to 171,496,
Golisano remarked, ''I'd say it was doing damn well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
