<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regional Red Cross arm declares blood supply emergency  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN KEKIS
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) - Giving blood is no big deal to Larry Koch
- he's donated 16 gallons in the past 25 years. If only the Red
Cross could clone him.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with fewer donors and increasing demand, the New York-Penn
Region of American Red Cross Blood Services has declared a blood
emergency, calling it the most drastic hospital demand-driven
shortage in a least a decade.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross said the regional blood supply was 45 percent of
what it should be as the Fourth of July holiday nears. Supplies of
nearly every blood type are low because hospital demand has
outpaced blood donations for two months. Some hospitals have even
decided to cut back on elective surgeries.
</P>
<P>
   Although summer shortages are the norm, there is the feeling
that this one is acute.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we do expect is that it dips in the summer,'' Red Cross
spokesperson Andrea Strano said Monday. ''We usually don't arrive
at that point until midsummer. But this isn't the usual summer cry
for donations. We don't know how this is going to play out through
September.''
</P>
<P>
   In the New York-Penn region, which serves 129 hospitals in 61
counties, 2,600 more units of blood were distributed in May than a
year ago. That's a 12 percent increase. And Strano said the problem
is likely to grow in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our speculation is that generations are getting older and need
more medical attention and medical procedures,'' she said. ''This
is really a trend that we're seeing the beginning of.''
</P>
<P>
   Strano said a directive from the federal government barring
people who have spent six months in Great Britain may have cost the
Red Cross 2 percent of its donors. ''That's a lot,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It's unknown how long the March ruling, a response to the
overseas mad cow disease scare, will be in place.
</P>
<P>
   Although it only takes 8-10 minutes for the actual process of
giving blood, donors end up spending about an hour because they
also have to fill out a questionnaire and take time to recover.
That's an hour that many feel they don't have.
</P>
<P>
   ''People have a busier lifestyle. It makes it more convenient to
forget that blood donations are needed,'' Strano said. ''It's been
something that's gradually occurred as society has gone from a
one-income household to everybody working. There are also lot of
activities competing for civic duty.''
</P>
<P>
   Not in Larry Koch's life.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe in the cause,'' said Koch, a 46-year-old architect
in the Syracuse area with a 6-month-old baby keeping him awake when
it's time to sleep. ''I make sure that I get down there and donate
every 56 days.
</P>
<P>
   ''I do my best to proselytize, but it hasn't worked,'' Koch
said. ''People are afraid of needles, afraid of maybe catching a
disease, although you can't catch a disease from donating. Most
people have two reasons for not giving - they're afraid of needles,
or they've tried it and had a bad experience, and that finished
them off forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Strano said blood donation centers will be open extra hours for
the next two weeks. Any healthy person age 17 or older and who
weighs at least 110 pounds may be eligible to give.
</P>
<P>
   And for those who profess a fear of needles, Koch can empathize.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not a big needle person,'' he said. ''When I was in
elementary school, I feigned being sick when they gave certain
shots, I was so terrified. I think that's part of why I give. It's
an atonement for that. You've got to challenge your fears. Once I
started giving, I never looked back.''
</P>
<P>
   For more information, prospective donors are urged to call the
Red Cross toll-free at: 1-800-272-4543.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-27-00 0016 </TRAILER>
