<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 00:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cop calls conviction in Louima case 'lynching'  </HEADLINE>
By TOM HAYS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - An ex-patrolman facing severe prison time for
his role in one of the worst police brutality scandals in city
history has lashed out at federal authorities, calling himself a
victim of a ''modern day lynching.''
</P>
<P>
   In a spiteful, defiant letter filed with pre-sentencing court
papers, Charles Schwarz claimed he is ''totally innocent'' of
charges he and another officer tortured Abner Louima with a broken
broomstick following Louima's arrest in a 1997 street disturbance.
Schwarz was to be sentenced Tuesday in Brooklyn federal court.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no excuse for what happened to Abner Louima, however,
I will not take responsibility for a criminal act that I didn't
commit, nor will I apologize for something I didn't do,'' the
defendant wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The case, Schwarz added, ''was nothing more than a modern day
lynching'' staged by ''shifty'' and ''overzealous'' prosecutors. He
also accused U.S. District Judge Eugene Nickerson of allowing the
government ''to get away with their misconduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz, 34, a former Marine, was convicted last year of
violating Louima's civil rights by restraining him while another
officer, Justin Volpe, sodomized the handcuffed Haitian immigrant
with the stick in a precinct bathroom. Volpe, in a guilty plea,
said he flew into a blind rage because he believed - mistakenly -
that the prisoner had punched him in the street.
</P>
<P>
   In a second trial this year, a jury found Schwarz and two other
officers, Thomas Bruder and Thomas Wiese, guilty of concocting a
story to try to clear Schwarz.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz faces a possible life sentence for the bathroom assault,
although the judge has authority to give him less time; Volpe
received 30 years. The judge also is to sentence Schwarz, Bruder
and Wiese for obstruction of justice, which carries a penalty of up
to five years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz has maintained at both trials - and through a ''Free
Chuck Schwarz'' campaign waged by his family, attorneys and police
union officials - that he was never in the bathroom. Taking the
witness stand at the second trial, he claimed he was searching a
patrol car at the time of the assault; Volpe testified that it was
Wiese, not Schwarz, who was the second officer.
</P>
<P>
   But two officers credited with breaking the so-called blue wall
of silence testified that they saw Schwarz leading Louima toward
the bathroom. And Louima testified his second assailant was ''the
driver'' who transported him to the station; records show Schwarz
drove the patrol car.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
