<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Civil War soldiers' graves disturbed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   GROVELAND, N.Y. (AP) - Vandals disturbed the graves of two more
Civil War-era veterans near where the skull of a Union officer
known as an ''evil genius'' was stolen.
</P>
<P>
   Five holes have appeared within the last two months in the
Williamsburgh Cemetery in Groveland 35 miles south of Rochester.
</P>
<P>
   Two holes were dug near the tombstone of Army Maj. Fitzhugh
Birney, a military lawyer. Another two holes appeared near the
grave of Navy Capt. Samuel Adams Lee. A fifth hole wasn't near a
gravestone, said Groveland town Historian Larry Turner.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston County sheriff's deputies are unsure whether anything
was taken. They are checking to see whether the incidents are
related to last week's theft of the skull of Union officer Elisha
G. Marshall's skull from Mt. Hope Cemetery in Rochester. He was a
brevet general, a temporary title, and retired as a colonel. Police
believe that desecration on the summer solstice may have been part
of a satanic ritual.
</P>
<P>
   Satanic symbols were found nearby and the solstice is a day
police watch for such activity in cemeteries.	   
</P>
<P>
   In the Groveland incident, Turner said he suspects thieves armed
with metal detectors are searching for Civil War-era relics. A
well-preserved belt buckle or sword can be worth thousands of
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ''They think they are going to dig up one of those graves and
find a bonanza and get rich,'' Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't have anything to indicate a (relationship), but you
never know,'' said Rochester police spokesman Carlos Garcia said of
the Groveland and Rochester incidents.
</P>
<P>
   Birney was the son of James Birney, an abolitionist who ran for
president on the Liberty Party line in 1840 and 1844. His maternal
grandfather was Col. William Fitzhugh, who with Col. Nathaniel
Rochester and Maj. Charles Carroll bought the land along the
Genesee River that now forms downtown Rochester.
</P>
<P>
   Lee wasn't so successful. When a ship's rigging fell on his
foot, doctors had to amputate, Turner said. Then, when recovering
in hospitals, Lee became addicted to painkillers, Turner said. In
1882, Lee died of an opium overdose.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want these guys stopped,'' Turner said. ''I put too much
work into these cemeteries to have them all messed up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
