<HEADLINE> Japan on Alert for Volcano Eruption  </HEADLINE>
By KOZO MIZOGUCHI
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Earthquakes rattled a small Japanese island in the
Pacific on Tuesday, and 2,500 people were evacuated from their
homes amid warnings of a possible volcanic eruption.
</P>
<P>
   The evacuation was ordered late Monday on Miyakejima, 120 miles
south of Tokyo, after a series of mild earthquakes suggested
volcanic activity. The area around Miyakejima is volcanic, and
Mount Oyama, a 2,686-foot volcano on the island, has had several
major eruptions this century.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists detected nearly 3,150 quakes on Miyakejima starting
late Monday. Many were too small to be felt, the Meteorological
Agency said. Two of the latest tremors on Tuesday registered a
magnitude of 4.0, the strongest so far, the Meteorological Agency
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe an eruption has possibly begun undersea already,''
said Yoshiaki Ida, a seismologist at the Coordinating Committee for
the Prediction of Volcanic Eruptions. ''Our biggest fear is that
there would be violent explosions if eruption occurs closer to
shorelines.''
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Agency said the surface of the ocean about 1 mile
off the west coast of the island had turned yellow and blue,
meaning the seabed may have erupted Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   In more possible evidence of an undersea eruption, the agency
later reported that one of its patrol ships felt a strong jolt from
below. A moment later, another vessel observed thick steam rising
from the sea's surface.
</P>
<P>
   As the undersea activity increased, Tokyo and local authorities
readied evacuation and assistance plans.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister's office set up a crisis center to evacuate
people from the island if necessary, and officials dispatched 29
ships to stand by. The local government ordered residents in the
south to seek shelter in schools on the northern side.
</P>
<P>
   The Tokyo city government was preparing to ship 800 blankets,
medicine and water to the island, city official Kazuhiro Sakurai
said. The city's fire department sent a 10-member team of rescuers
and planned to send more rescuers, equipment and heat-resistant
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial flights to Miyakejima were canceled Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Mount Oyama last erupted in 1983, spewing lava down the
mountain's southwestern flank and destroying homes. No one died
because all the residents were evacuated. An eruption in 1940
killed 11 people and injured 20.
</P>
<P>
   The island has an area of 21 square miles and is home to about
4,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Japan is one of the world's most seismically active nations. A
volcanic eruption on Miyakejima would be Japan's second this year.
</P>
<P>
   More than 13,000 people living at the foot of Mount Usu in
northern Japan were ordered to leave their homes after the volcano
coughed up steam and ash March 31 for the first time in 22 years.
Many evacuees have been allowed to return home since officials said
in May that the volcano may be drifting back to sleep.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-27-00 0040 </TRAILER>
