<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ballooning Runs Afoul in Brazil  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL ASTOR
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- As dawn breaks through the hilltop
palms, dozens of sleepy-eyed ''baloeiros'' use a welding torch to
ignite the wad of wax-soaked-cotton that will propel their hot air
balloon skyward and keep it flying for up to 10 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Then they gingerly raise the 30-foot orb, with its three baskets
of fireworks trailing below, out of the volcano-shaped hill -- a
hidden patch of jungle on Rio's otherwise drab westside. As the
balloon climbs higher, the fireworks begin firing a rat-a-tat-tat
of white sparks and smoke.
</P>
<P>
   A burst of applause follows the final explosion, then everyone
rushes to their cars: Some hoping to recover the balloon, others to
catch a second launch whispered through the baloeiro grapevine and
others, still, home to sleep. No matter where they are headed, they
go quickly to avoid the police.
</P>
<P>
   To the baloeiros, setting off balloons during Brazil's annual
June festivities honoring Saints Peter, Paul, Anthony and John is a
300-year-old tradition, brought over by the Portuguese, that needs
to be preserved.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities don't share that vision. The 1998 ''environmental
crimes'' law made the launch, transport and storage of unmanned
balloons a crime punishable by fines and even prison.
</P>
<P>
   ''These balloons are just like stray bullets because they are
unguided and can fall anywhere, on top of houses, on electric
wires, wherever. They present a hazard to aviation and every year
they destroy hundreds of hectares of forest,'' said Major Fabio
Jose Meirelles, commander of Rio's forest fire fighting brigade.
</P>
<P>
   Meirelles said balloons started about 43 percent of the forest
fires that claimed some 1,720 hectares -- 4,250 acres -- around Rio
in 1997. Fires burned only about a third of that acreage in 1999, a
year after balloons were banned.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran baloeiro Humberto Pinto, a retired police colonel,
concedes the fires are a problem but says the answer lies in better
regulation, not a total ban.
</P>
<P>
   Pinto was arrested in May while handing out fliers defending the
legalization of ballooning. He was charged under a Brazilian law
that makes it illegal to advocate criminal activity.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's ridiculous; there's no such thing as free speech here,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Baloeiros say the crackdown won't deter them and claim that
hundreds of crews working independently launched some 5,000
balloons this past Mother's Day alone.
</P>
<P>
   Like graffiti artists who spend entire nights covering subway
cars with murals just to see them buffed clean the next day,
there's more than a touch of the fanatic among baloeiros. The ban
only adds to the mystique.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them sport a T-shirts bearing the slogan ''Arte
Prohibido,'' or prohibited art, accompanied by an elegantly
rendered drawing of a balloon.
</P>
<P>
   ''The police are cracking down more and more these days. Last
weekend, I was at a launch where they even fired three shots before
we could get away,'' brags 29-year-old baloeiro Emiliano Martinelli
with a broad grin.
</P>
<P>
   Like Rio's samba groups during carnival, baloeiros often spend
thousands of dollars and several months on elaborate creations that
will be glimpsed only briefly during seasonal celebrations. The
main difference being the baloeiros' parade floats really float.
</P>
<P>
   Towering as high as 72 feet, the balloons often carry enormous
banners or, if launched at night, panels made up of hundreds of
tiny candles arranged to make a picture, usually honoring soccer
teams or saints.
</P>
<P>
   At Neneh's bar, a popular baloeiro hangout on Rio's poor
northside, enthusiasts trade stories and photographs of balloons
honoring Jesus, Charlie Chaplin, Ernest Hemingway, the late
Brazilian entertainer Chacrinha and Lady Diana.
</P>
<P>
   There's even one in the shape of the Eiffel Tower whose wide
base and pointy top would seem to defy basic balloon design sense.
</P>
<P>
   Every so often, Jandir Oliveira da Silva, 42, and his friends
take time off from their drinking to go across the street and
launch three-foot-high balloons using cigarette lighters.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will die, but ballooning will never die,'' he said. ''My
father made balloons in the dining room. This is a tradition that
passes from father to son, like music.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-27-00 0041 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000627.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 00:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Greenway officials decry Pataki's firings at agencies  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Gov. George Pataki's firing of two Hudson
Valley development agencies' leaders has compromised the groups'
independence, the ex-chairman of one agency told a legislative
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature and former Gov. Mario Cuomo set up the Hudson
Greenway Council and the Greenway Conservancy as ''public benefit
corporations,'' former Greenway Conservancy Chairman Matthew Bender
IV said.
</P>
<P>
   Their boards got the power to hire and fire so the agencies
would be buffered somewhat from the whims of gubernatorial
intervention, he argued.
</P>
<P>
   Bender on Monday recounted for two Democratic Assembly members,
Richard Brodsky of Westchester County and Susan John of Rochester,
how he was told on May 24 by Pataki's appointments secretary Thomas
Doherty to fire Greenway Conservancy Executive Director Maggie
Vinciguerra.
</P>
<P>
   ''I asked for a reason and I was told, 'The governor wants her
fired,''' Bender said.
</P>
<P>
   When he described how well Vinciguerra had performed in a
demanding job, Bender said he was told by Doherty, '''The governor
wants her job' and his job was to deliver that message to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The dismissals of Vinciguerra and his counterpart at the
affiliated Greenway Council, David Sampson, triggered a public
discussion of a matter the Republican Pataki administration has
preferred to keep private, the removals of officials inherited from
the Democratic Cuomo administration.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's spokesmen have defended the governor's action as
prompted by the need to enhance the agencies and to get more done.
</P>
<P>
   Bender, heir to a famous Albany-based legal publishing business,
compounded attention the case received by balking at removing
Sampson, being replaced by Pataki in the unpaid chairman's position
at the Conservancy and by speaking openly about the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Janeway has since been hired to replace Vinciguerra and
Carmella Mantello has taken Sampson's job. Mantello will earn
$80,000 year while Janeway will get $75,000.
</P>
<P>
   Bender said the result of the changes at the Greenway
Conservancy is that the agency is ''politicized.''
</P>
<P>
   The Conservancy and Council were set up to promote agreement
among Hudson River Valley communities for recreational, tourism and
business development programs.
</P>
<P>
   Sampson, who was executive director of the Council for a decade,
said Monday he initially thought there was not enough support on
his board of directors to carry his dismissal. But as time went on,
Sampson said, that support ''eroded'' and the former official said
he heard from several board members that they were pressured by
Pataki's office to vote for Sampson's dismissal on June 7.
</P>
<P>
   Sampson said that in at least one case, an unidentified member
of the board was threatened with loss of state funding for the
agency if Sampson wasn't fired.
</P>
<P>
   Sampson said he also heard that Pataki's appointment office was
angered at Sampson and Vinciguerra for appearing at West Point in
May at an economic development event with U.S. Housing Secretary
Andrew Cuomo, a possible Democratic candidate against Pataki in
2002.
</P>
<P>
   Bender and Sampson said they heard little, if any, complaints
about the jobs the Council and Conservancy were doing prior to the
directives in May to fire Sampson and Vinciguerra. Sampson did
concede, however, that he did not have a ''warm'' relationship with
Pataki's office. He attributed that to being a holdover from
Cuomo's administration.
</P>
<P>
   But Barnabas McHenry, chairman of the Greenway Council,
testified Monday that he knew for two years or more that the Pataki
administration was unhappy with the Council and Conservancy.
Specifically, he said there was grumbling over the pace of the two
agencies' work on projects and over their attention to economic
development.
</P>
<P>
   ''I saw those storm clouds gathering,'' McHenry said. ''What do
you do with storm clouds? You can't do much.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki spokesman Michael McKeon dismissed Monday's hearing as
political grandstanding.
</P>
<P>
   ''I took my kids to the circus yesterday so I've had enough of
clowns for the week,'' McKeon said. ''I am not going to comment on
Richard Brodsky's little spectacle.''
</P>
<P>
   Brodsky, who chairs the Assembly's environmental conservation
committee, told Bender and Sampson they did not deserve to be
dismissed by Pataki. Brodsky said the firings were a ''simple
purge'' designed by Pataki to gain tighter control of agencies the
Legislature intended to be more independent of the executive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-27-00 0041 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000627.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 00:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Settlement will open 12 miles of Moose to canoes, kayaks  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - A 12-mile stretch of the Moose River in the
Adirondack Mountains will be opened to canoes and kayaks under an
agreement touted Monday by environmentalists as a landmark for
recreational boaters in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement calls for non-motorized access to the south
branch of the river from May 1-Oct. 15 through property owned by
the Old Forge-based Adirondack League Club.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement lays out a number of rules for members of the
public using that stretch of the river, including prohibitions
against fishing, swimming or hunting; anchoring or tying up of
watercrafts; use of any motorized watercraft and overnight trips.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement was signed nine years to the month after five
canoeists were barred access to the Moose River in Herkimer County.
A sign hanging over the river on a wire notified canoeists and
kayakers that they were entering private property not open to the
public.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute touched on a longstanding debate over which of the
thousands of miles of waterways which honeycomb the Adirondacks are
open to the public even though they run through privately owned
properties.
</P>
<P>
   Former state Attorney General Robert Abrams joined the
canoeists' suit against the Adirondack League Club back in 1991 and
the three subsequent New York attorneys general continued to argue
on behalf of greater public access to the Moose River.
</P>
<P>
   The Pataki administration was also arguing on the canoeists'
behalf.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the state Court of Appeals ruled that the proper test
to determine if a waterway is navigable - and open to the public -
is whether it can be used for commercial or recreational purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, the commercial use of a waterway was the legal
standard of its navigability, but the judges said the days were
long past when it was relevant to New Yorkers whether a river could
accommodate the floating downstream of logs felled by lumberjacks.
A river or lake's recreational use is also a valid factor, the
judges ruled.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement was signed last Friday by state Supreme Court
Justice Joseph Sise in Herkimer County and distributed by lawyers
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Woodworth, counsel for the Adirondack Mountain Club, said
the settlement is the first he knows of in the country establishing
that canoe or kayak travel can make a waterway ''navigable'' in the
legal sense that it is open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   It is also the first settlement that recognizes the right of
portage, he said. That is when boaters get on land and carry canoes
or kayaks around non-navigable obstacles such as waterfalls or
rapids in the river.
</P>
<P>
   One of the five canoeists who originally prompted the
litigation, Tom Kligerman, said the agreement will also open to the
public eight miles of the Moose River, including Remsen Falls,
where it meets the Adirondack League Club property.
</P>
<P>
   ''The river is open - after 110 years of posting - the river is
open,'' Kligerman said.
</P>
<P>
   The five canoeists called Monday on the state to issue a list of
navigable waterways so it is clear to paddlers and to landowners
around those water courses which ones are open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other provisions of the agreement are ones calling for
no public access to the Moose River if water levels are too low or
when the Adirondack League Club is stocking the river with fish or
engaging in scientific studies of the waterway.
</P>
<P>
   The Adirondack League Club issued a statement Monday saying it
was happy with the agreement. It also said it would enforce the
terms of the agreement on boaters stringently.
</P>
<P>
   According to the club's recommendation, only experienced
paddlers should try to use the Big Moose due to the remoteness of
the region and the difficulty of the rapids.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
