<HEADLINE> Padres 9, Dodgers 5  </HEADLINE>
By KEN PETERS
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Bret Boone hit a two-run homer and doubled in
three more runs during an eight-run second inning against Orel
Hershiser as the San Diego Padres beat Los Angeles 9-5 Monday
night, extending the Dodgers' losing streak to five games.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres rocked Hershiser (1-5) for eight runs on six hits and
three walks in just 1 2-3 innings. The 41-year-old right-hander was
starting on one day's rest, having thrown 27 pitches during a
rain-delayed 1 1-3 innings of a 6-1 loss Saturday at St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego's victory came several hours after the Padres learned
that Tony Gwynn will undergo arthroscopic surgery Tuesday on his
degenerative left knee and could be out as briefly as a month or as
long as the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The 40-year-old Gwynn, an eight-time NL batting champion, has
had five operations on the knee.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Meadows (6-5) limited the Dodgers to Todd Hollandsworth's
sixth homer, leading off the first; Gary Sheffield's sacrifice fly
in the fifth; and Alex Cora's leadoff shot -- his first major league
homer -- in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Meadows allowed six hits in 7 1-3 innings. He walked three and
struck out five.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Nicholson and Eric Owens added RBI singles in the second,
and Ed Sprague chipped in with a sacrifice fly for the other run as
San Diego sent 12 men to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Klesko had an RBI groundout in the ninth for the final San
Diego run.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Gilbert doubled in two runs in the bottom half, making it
9-5, after Carlos Almanzar walked three straight batters.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser developed control problems this year and hasn't won in
eight starts dating to an 8-1 victory over Cincinnati in the
Dodgers home opener on April 14.
</P>
<P>
   He matched a modern major league record, hitting four batters in
a 10-3 loss to Houston on April 19. Hershiser did it in just 1 1-3
innings.
</P>
<P>
   In the second inning against San Diego, he threw one pitch five
feet over the head of catcher Todd Hundley, then, with Klesko up
next, bounced a pitch that hit Klesko on the left big toe.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Hershiser volunteered to go to the minors, making three
starts before rejoining the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
Notes: In addition to Gwynn, the Padres placed RHP Stan Spencer on
the 15-day DL with a strained right elbow. They also transferred SS
Chris Gomez to the 60-day DL, recalled RHP Will Cunnane from
Triple-A Las Vegas, and purchased the contract of OF Dusty Allen
from Las Vegas. ... Padres RHP Brian Tollberg, who made his big
league debut last Tuesday, was named the NL player of the week. He
went 2-0 with a 1.25 ERA in his two starts last week, at Arizona
and Cincinnati. ... The Dodgers activated Hundley, who had been out
with a strained rib cage, and assigned C Paul LoDuca to Triple-A
Albuquerque.
</P>
</TEXT>
