<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euro 2000 Approaches Finish  </HEADLINE>
By IAN PHILLIPS
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over the years, World Cups and European Championships have been
dominated by defense-oriented games in which players seemed more
preoccupied with avoiding mistakes than scoring goals.
</P>
<P>
   This year, fans at Euro 2000 have been treated to 77 goals and
games of the highest caliber -- Portugal 3, England 2; Spain 4,
Yugoslavia 3; Netherlands 3, France 2; Netherlands 6, Yugoslavia 1;
and France 2, Spain 1.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, it looked like Euro 2000 would be remembered for the
drunken violence of English thugs. Instead, it will go down as a
memorable meeting of players at the top of their games, such as
Portugal's Luis Figo, France's Zinedine Zidane and Dutchman Edgar
Davids.
</P>
<P>
   The three midfield maestros, undaunted by grueling seasons and
the prospect of six games in 23 days if they go all the way to the
July 2 final in Rotterdam, are getting stronger and better every
game.
</P>
<P>
   How Zidane and Figo fare in the rest of the competition -- they
face each other in Wednesday's France-Portugal semifinal in Bruges
-- could decide who will be crowned world Player of the Year.
Thursday's other semifinal is between Italy and the Netherlands in
Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
   Both games seem too close to call.
</P>
<P>
   ''What I have seen gives me great satisfaction,'' Gerhard
Aigner, chief executive of UEFA, the European soccer federation,
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The violence, he added, sent ''a kind of shudder over the
tournament for a couple of days ... but I think we in Europe can be
very proud of what the players have demonstrated on the field of
play.''
</P>
<P>
   After a weekend of drama that saw 14 goals in four games,
players started preparing for the semifinals. But they couldn't
help raving about what they'd seen so far.
</P>
<P>
   ''When Zidane is playing like that, there is no stopping him,''
French goalkeeper Fabien Barthez said Monday. ''He had a brilliant
match. The man can do anything with the ball at his feet.''
</P>
<P>
   ''AC Milan must regret ever letting him go.'' France's
Christophe Dugarry said of Davids, the Juventus midfield general.
</P>
<P>
   As for Figo, he's been on everybody's lips since his bullet goal
from outside the box stunned England, paving the way for a 3-2
victory in one of the tournament's first games. He plays for
Barcelona, one of the world's biggest clubs, but that hasn't
stopped a host of other clubs from coveting him.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, a rest day, was a chance for players to wind down, and
for injuries to be patched up.
</P>
<P>
   Italy's captain Paolo Maldini is suffering from a thigh strain,
France's Dugarry has a broken nose and Emmanuel Petit a knee
injury. But all three could be back for the semis.
</P>
<P>
   The Portuguese are likely to be the freshest after a day off
Sunday spent outside the team hotel. But they're also walking a
disciplinary tightrope, with five players on yellow cards and all
in danger of missing a possible final if cautioned again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-27-00 0143 </TRAILER>
