<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Astros' Wagner To Have Surgery  </HEADLINE>
By BOB BAUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- Houston Astros reliever Billy Wagner, who was
third in the National League with 39 saves last season, will
undergo surgery on his left elbow Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros said Monday that a second opinion from Dr. Lewis
Yocum confirmed a partially torn flexor tendon. Yocum, the Anaheim
Angels medical director, will perform the surgery in Los Angeles to
repair the damaged tendon and remove scar tissue.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Astros will miss Wagner, manager Larry Dierker said
it's comforting to know there was a reason for the closer's
ineffectiveness this season.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's good to know that the reason he was struggling was,
partially at least, due to the fact there was something wrong with
his arm,'' Dierker said before Monday night's game at Arizona.
''Instead of being a mystery and wondering will he be able to get
anybody out again, we're saying, 'yeah, if he can get the pain out
of his arm and he can hit his spots again.'''
</P>
<P>
   The pain first surfaced late last season and was so serious that
Dierker said the left-hander would not have been able to throw
again if the playoff series against the Atlanta Braves had lasted
any longer.
</P>
<P>
   Tests showed tendinitis, but no tear. Doctors told Wagner that
an offseason of rest should solve the problem, but the pain began
to reappear early this season. Not wanting to blame his poor
performance on the injury, Wagner said he withstood the pain until
it was apparent it wasn't going to go away.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Wagner did not tell his teammates or his
manager how much he was hurting.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker said he had no idea that Wagner was injured.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't think there was anything wrong with his arm,''
Dierker said. ''I was really surprised when they said he had a
tear, because he was throwing real hard. It wasn't a matter of
velocity.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston entered Monday night's game at Arizona with the worst
record in the majors, 26-48. Wagner, who lost his closer's job
after blowing nine of 15 save opportunities, is 2-4 this year with
a 6.18 ERA. He has walked 18 and struck out 28 in 27 2-3 innings.
Last season, he was 4-1 with a 1.47 ERA, 124 strikeouts and 23
walks in 74 2-3 innings. He did not allow an earned run in his last
21 appearances of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner's struggles are a big reason for the Astros' woes,
Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he blew three saves last year,'' Dierker said. ''If he
was at a point where he'd been healthy and he'd only blown two
saves this year, we'd be close to .500. There have been that many
games in the ninth where we've had the lead and lost the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker said Wagner may not come back next season with the same
velocity, but he doesn't have to in order to be effective.
</P>
<P>
   ''He doesn't have to throw 98. The way he throws, if he throws
94 or 95, he'll be fine,'' Dierker said. ''He may not hit 100 mph
again. He hit 100 once about a month ago, but I don't think he has
to do that to be effective. But he does have to be able to throw
the ball where he wants it, and that's what he hasn't been able to
do this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Wagner's injury is the latest in a wave that has hit the Astros
this season. Seven of the starters on opening day have missed time
because of injury or illness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-27-00 0200 </TRAILER>
