<DOCNO> APW20000627.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 07:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> At the Movies: 'The Patriot'  </HEADLINE>
By BOB THOMAS
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of all the major U.S. wars, the Revolutionary War has been the
most overlooked by the movie industry.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Hollywood studios have concluded that audiences
cannot connect with characters in powdered wigs and three-cornered
hats who shoot front-loading muskets. Now Columbia Pictures is
striving to combat that notion with ''The Patriot,'' a big-scale
epic with Mel Gibson for box-office star power, playing a respected
South Carolina landowner and widower with seven growing children.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson's Benjamin Martin is unswayed by the call to arms sparked
by the Declaration of Independence in Philadelphia. The hidden
reason: a hero in the French and Indian War, he is haunted by the
atrocities of which he was a party.
</P>
<P>
   His teen-age son, played by Heath Ledger, is eager to join the
Continental Army, but his father forbids him.
</P>
<P>
   The situation changes when British troops, led by a sadistic
colonel played by Jason Isaacs, invade Gibson's plantation. After
helplessly watching his family brutalized and his son carried off
to be hanged, Gibson regains his war fervor.
</P>
<P>
   He organizes a ragtag militia and starts a guerrilla campaign
that thwarts the Brits' plans for an easy victory in the South.
</P>
<P>
   While both sides were lining up their troops and firing
point-blank at each other, Gibson employs stealth strategy -- he and
his followers hurtling out of swamps and forests for sudden attacks
on small enemy units. They concentrate their fire on officers, a
tactic the British consider not quite cricket.
</P>
<P>
   The redcoats are commanded by Gen. Cornwallis (the fine English
actor Tom Wilkinson), who believes the colonists can be subdued by
time-worn British army methods. Gibson arranges a meeting with
Cornwallis to exchange prisoners. The episode is the most engaging
in the movie; Gibson tricks the stuffy general and even steals his
two prize great Danes.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting sequences are offset by Gibson's returns to his
family, whose lives are threatened by the vindictive colonel. There
is a hint of romance with his dead wife's sister (Charlotte
Selton), but most of the time she is limited to casting fond looks.
</P>
<P>
   Having fought the British centuries before in ''Braveheart,''
Gibson brings the same intensity to ''The Patriot.'' He aptly
portrays the complex nature of a warrior turned pacifist who must
take up arms again.
</P>
<P>
   Ledger is effective as the militiaman's son, though his
character is sketchily defined.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkinson's Cornwallis dominates his scenes and would almost be
likable except for his snobbish pigheadedness. And Isaacs is
allowed to play the sadistic colonel way over the top.
</P>
<P>
   Roland Emmerich (''Independence Day'') directed ''The Patriot''
with his usual flourish, assisted by digital magic that can make
the line of troops seem a mile wide.
</P>
<P>
   John Williams' thundering score contributes to the drama. Robert
Rodat's screenplay keeps a good balance between military and family
matters, but most of the plot turns have a deja vu quality -- the
stuff of many a Hollywood war movie or Western.
</P>
<P>
   The tendency in period movies like this is to write stilted
dialogue. That may be how they wrote, but it's hard to imagine that
they spoke that way in normal conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Patriot'' seems likely to stir rebuttal from historians,
especially those on the other side of the pond. Did the British
army really commit Nazilike atrocities during the Revolutionary
War?
</P>
<P>
   The Columbia Pictures release was produced by Dean Devlin, Mark
Gordon and Gary Levinsohn. Rated R for violence and sadism. Running
time: 158 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
</P>
<P>
   G -- General audiences. All ages admitted.
</P>
<P>
   PG -- Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 -- Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
</P>
<P>
   R -- Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
</P>
<P>
   NC-17 -- No one under 17 admitted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-27-00 0737 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000627.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 07:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> At the Movies: 'Trixie'  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID GERMAIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trixie Zurbo is one smart cookie, though it's hard to
distinguish her insightful intellect amid the figure-of-speech
butchery that spills like idiot's wit from her mouth.
</P>
<P>
   With a zestfully off-kilter performance from Emily Watson in the
title role, director-screenwriter Alan Rudolph's ''Trixie''
delivers on his promise of a ''screwball noir'' flick, part homage
to Hollywood's great detectives, part spoof and part something
truly indefinable.
</P>
<P>
   The story is a bit unclear and criminal motives are hazy, but
the best of the classic noir films often emphasized character and
ambiance over their convoluted plots. ''Trixie'' is no different,
presenting a clever, engrossing portrait of a shrewd yet dotty
woman on a mission.
</P>
<P>
   A gum-chewing, soda-slurping gumshoe wannabe, Trixie (Watson) is
hot on the case of, well, a case. Relegated to store security
patrol and a new job fingering pickpockets at a casino resort,
Trixie reads Police Insight magazine and wants nothing more than a
shot at being a real ''private defective,'' as she puts it in her
malapropian speech.
</P>
<P>
   Trixie gets her wish when she becomes involved with the casino's
resident gigolo Dex (Dermot Mulroney). Dex unwittingly draws Trixie
into a murder mystery involving a ponderous senator (Nick Nolte), a
smarmy tycoon (Will Patton), a teen-age siren (Brittany Murphy) and
a bimbo (Lesley Ann Warren) the men all lust after.
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out these unusual suspects is Nathan Lane in a standout
turn as a boozy lounge impersonator who becomes enchanted by
Trixie's perversely wise innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Audiences will find Trixie equally enchanting. Awkward, twitchy
yet utterly adorable, Trixie offers plenty to love, and even more
to scratch your head over.
</P>
<P>
   A sampling of the world according to Trixie:
</P>
<P>
   -- ''It's time to fish or get off the pot.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ''Most people condescend from monkeys.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ''Boy, do I wish I had an answer to that question, because I'm
really getting tired of answering it.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ''I'm absolutely ravishing, where's the food?''
</P>
<P>
   -- ''She's dead now. She's never going to be the same again.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ''I don't want you letting anyone into the room when I'm not
here unless I recognize them, or else I'll beat you up good.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ''If you don't have the clues, the bread and butter can be
pulled right out from under your feet, and then there's only one
person to blame, and that's each other.''
</P>
<P>
   For all her seeming inanity, Trixie muddles through with
perseverance and perceptiveness. She offers a possible explanation
for why her tongue operates independently of her brain.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I was a kid, I got hit on the head with a bowling ball,
and I woke up unconscious,'' she says. And when they X-rayed her
head, doctors found nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Like Trixie, other characters have their own patterns of
miscommunication.
</P>
<P>
   Nolte pronounces: ''You have to wear your unpopularity as a
badge of honor, don't you?''
</P>
<P>
   Dex tells Trixie to ''bet big. The less you bet, the more you
lose when you win.''
</P>
<P>
   Lane's lounge performer philosophizes that ''we're each tap
dancers in the canoe of life.''
</P>
<P>
   The point of the film is that no one is who they seem, and
through her blundering detective work, Trixie exposes them all.
Mulroney and Patton's characters prove to be romantics at heart,
Lane's breezy mimic turns out to be haunted by past violence, and
Murphy's young temptress changes shades throughout.
</P>
<P>
   Nolte, spewing colorful but empty dialogue largely culled from
real-life political speeches, has two gripping encounters with
Trixie then has an anguished, cathartic, very public soul-baring.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, everyone in ''Trixie'' comes clean in unexpected
ways.
</P>
<P>
   As Trixie puts it: ''Hey, nobody's human. That's the way things
are.''
</P>
<P>
   Produced by Robert Altman, ''Trixie'' is a Sony Pictures
Classics release. It runs 117 minutes and is rated R for language,
sexuality and violence.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
</P>
<P>
   G -- General audiences. All ages admitted.
</P>
<P>
   PG -- Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 -- Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
</P>
<P>
   R -- Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
</P>
<P>
   NC-17 -- No one under 17 admitted.
</P>
