<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Up 29; Nasdaq Gains 27  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were modestly higher on the eve of the
Federal Reserve's decision on interest rates. Trading activity was
quiet Tuesday as most investors opted to wait for the Fed's
announcement before staking out major new positions.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was up 29.35 at 10,572.34 in
the early going on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also slightly higher. The Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 4.31 at 1,459.56, and the Nasdaq
composite index was up 27.16 at 3,939.28.
</P>
<P>
   A watch over interest rates kept many investors out of the
market. The Fed was meeting in Washington, and was expected to
announce its decision on interest rates Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Many economists expect the central bank to leave rates
unchanged, because the economy has shown signs of slowing from its
former breakneck pace. Financial stocks, which benefit from stable
rates, led the Dow's advance, with J.P. Morgan rising $3.063 to
$121.50.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday morning, the Conference Board offered the latest sign
that rising rates are taking a toll on consumers' enthusiasm. The
group said its Consumer Confidence Index fell to 138.8 in June from
a revised 144.7 in May as higher rates and soaring gas prices
pressured the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has raised rates six times in the past year to slow the
economy to a more sustainable pace, hoping to keep inflation at
bay.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 7-to-4 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 115.13 million
shares, behind Monday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 1.58 to 517.94.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 2.1 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 0.6 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 0.6 percent, and France's CAC-40 was
down 0.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
