<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 11:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Gains 67; Nasdaq Adds 6  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mostly higher in quiet trading
Tuesday on the eve of the Federal Reserve's decision on interest
rates. A muted report on consumer confidence provided the latest
sign that the Fed's long course of rate increases may be slowing
the economy enough to keep inflation at bay.
</P>
<P>
   In morning trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 66.78 at 10,609.81.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were slightly higher. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index was up 6.34 at 1,461.65, and the Nasdaq composite
index was up 6.23 at 3,918.35.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were buying stocks on the hope that the Fed will leave
interest rates unchanged when its two-day meeting ends Wednesday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has raised short-term rates six times in the past year,
but many economists expect the central bank to stand pat this week
because the economy has shown signs of slowing from its former
breakneck pace.
</P>
<P>
   ''The interest rate increases by the Fed are starting to bite,''
said Joseph T. Keating, chief investment officer at the Kent Funds
in Grand Rapids, Mich. ''But the economy isn't falling apart. We'll
still have growth -- just at a slower pace.''
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks, which benefit from stable rates, led the Dow's
advance, with J.P. Morgan rising $2.688 to $121.125.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday morning, the Conference Board offered the latest sign
that rising rates are taking a toll on consumers' enthusiasm. The
group said its Consumer Confidence Index fell to 138.8 in June from
a revised 144.7 in May as higher rates and soaring gas prices
pressured the economy.
</P>
<P>
   As the Fed tightened credit to cool growth to a more sustainable
pace, investors have started shifting money from sector to sector
as they debated which stocks will perform best in a slowing
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, technology stocks were leading the market higher. Intel
rose $1.438 to $135.625 and Cisco Systems rose $1.75 to $64.563.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 7-to-4 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 291.80 million shares
at late morning, slightly ahead of Monday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 2.19 to 514.17.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
