<HEADLINE> Glance at Regional AIDS Impact  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Regional breakdown of HIV/AIDS epidemic as estimated
by UNAIDS:
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- North America: Estimated 900,000 people living with AIDS virus
at end of 1999. United States has infection rate of 0.61 percent of
adult population, and Canada 0.30 percent. Concentrated among
injecting drug users and homosexual men. San Francisco studies
report increase in high-risk behavior among young homosexuals and
rise in gonorrhea, indicating danger of increase in HIV.
</P>
<P>
   -- Latin America and Caribbean: Estimated 1.67 million people
living with AIDS virus at end of 1999. Epidemic mainly spread by
heterosexual intercourse. Haiti worst hit, with 5.1 percent of
adults infected, followed by Barbados with 4.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   -- Europe: Estimated 940,000 people living with AIDS virus at end
of 1999. Increasing rates of infection in Eastern Europe and former
Soviet Union among drug addicts sharing needles. Ukraine has
highest rate in the region with 1 percent of adults infected.
</P>
<P>
   -- Asia: Estimated 6.13 million people living with AIDS virus at
end of 1999. Cambodia has highest rate with 4.4 percent infected,
largely through heterosexual intercourse. Thailand has infection
rate of 2.15 percent and has slowed spread of disease through
heterosexual intercourse by good prevention campaigns. Estimated
3.7 million people in India living with the virus, second highest
national total behind South Africa, with infection rate of 0.7
percent. World's most populous nation, China, has infection rate of
just 0.07 percent.
</P>
<P>
   -- Australia and New Zealand: Estimated 15,000 people living with
AIDS virus at end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   -- Sub-Saharan Africa: Estimated 24.5 million people living with
AIDS virus at end of 1999, with 4 million new infections last year
alone. More than one-tenth of adult population infected in 16
countries. Worst hit are Botswana (35.8 percent infection rate);
Swaziland (24.3 percent); Zimbabwe (25.1 percent); Lesotho (23.6
percent); Zambia (20 percent), South Africa (20 percent). Work
force is being devastated by high death rate among young adults,
development gains are being reversed, and health systems crumbling.
Spread mainly through heterosexual intercourse and women are worse
affected than men.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
