<DOCNO> APW20000627.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Richardson Defends Energy Policies  </HEADLINE>
By H. JOSEF HEBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Energy Secretary Bill Richardson again faced
testy lawmakers on Capitol Hill Tuesday, this time listening to
House Republicans ridicule the Clinton administration as
weak-willed in dealing with soaring gas prices and the OPEC oil
cartel.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, however, argued that ''our policy of quiet diplomacy
... is working,'' and gas prices, while still ''unacceptably
high,'' are falling 7 to 12 cents in the hard-hit Midwest.
Republican members of the House International Relations Committee
didn't seem to consider the efforts meaningful.
</P>
<P>
   ''This administration is still firing blanks when it should be
making an all-out attack,'' said Rep. Benjamin Gilman, R-N.Y., the
panel's chairman. He said the administration has been ''remarkably
passive'' in dealing with OPEC and has failed to promote greater
domestic oil production.
</P>
<P>
   Gilman last week introduced legislation that would allow
antitrust lawsuits to be brought against foreign energy cartels,
though legal experts have said little can be done legally to
prevent production or pricing agreements among sovereign nations.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats countered that the GOP-led Congress should accept much
of the blame for rejecting $2 billion worth of proposals since 1996
to promote energy conservation and development of alternate fuels.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some criticized the administration for not releasing oil
from the government's emergency reserve. Others suggested a harder
line is necessary to get friendly OPEC nations, such as Saudi
Arabia and Kuwait, to push for production raises beyond the modest
ones recently announced.
</P>
<P>
   After all, said Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif., ''we went to the
Persian Gulf to protect them'' when Iraq invaded Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson suggested that attempts to dictate to OPEC would be
counterproductive. He said he had always dealt firmly with OPEC,
and argued with foreign oil ministers that price stability favored
both producing and consuming nations.
</P>
<P>
   As evidence ''we are close to turning the corner,'' Richardson
cited new Energy Department figures that showed gasoline prices
nationwide dropped 3 cents a gallon over the last week.
</P>
<P>
   Low stocks and ''soaring demand'' have kept oil prices high,
above $30 a barrel, Richardson said. While worldwide production has
increased by 3.5 million barrels a day, demand also has risen, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said non-OPEC nations are producing at close to capacity, so
they can contribute only ''modest amounts'' of additional oil to
the market.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said high demand, low inventories, pipeline
disruptions and the high cost of cleaner-burning gasoline have
caused the dramatic price spikes in Chicago and Milwaukee; oil
companies have blamed these as well. But ''the oil companies have
some explaining to do,'' because, he said, there is no credible
answer for the price gap between conventional gas and the cleaner
fuel required in those cities.
</P>
<P>
   Although Richardson recently ordered loans of 500,000 barrels
each to two refineries that suffered supply interruptions, he has
steadfastly argued the Strategic Petroleum Reserve should only be
used for such supply disruptions, and not to influence prices.
</P>
<P>
   Northeastern lawmakers also were concerned about low stocks of
heating oil, and predicted possibly another winter of high prices
unless inventories increase.
</P>
<P>
   Heating oil stocks were 40 percent lower than normal in New
England at this time of year, said several lawmakers. Richardson
urged Congress to approve a proposal for stockpiling heating oil in
the Northeast for an emergency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-27-00 1504 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
