<HEADLINE> Dow Gains 34; Nasdaq Loses 34  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed in quiet trading Tuesday on
the eve of the Federal Reserve's decision on interest rates. A
muted report on consumer confidence provided the latest sign that
the Fed's long course of rate increases may be slowing the economy
enough to keep inflation at bay.
</P>
<P>
   But investors remained restless, shifting money from sector to
sector without much conviction about the underlying strength of the
market.
</P>
<P>
   With an hour left in Wall Street's regular session, the Dow
Jones industrial average was up 34.12 at 10,577.11.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was up 0.44 at 1,455.69, and the Nasdaq composite index was
down 33.60 at 3,878.52.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks got support from hopes that the Fed will leave interest
rates unchanged when its two-day meeting ends Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has raised short-term rates six times in the past year,
but many economists expect the central bank to stand pat this week
because the economy has shown signs of slowing from its former
breakneck pace.
</P>
<P>
   ''The interest rate increases by the Fed are starting to bite,''
said Joseph T. Keating, chief investment officer at the Kent Funds
in Grand Rapids, Mich. ''But the economy isn't falling apart. We'll
still have growth -- just at a slower pace.''
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks, which benefit from stable rates, led the Dow's
advance, with J.P. Morgan rising $2 to $120.438.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday morning, the Conference Board offered the latest sign
that rising rates are taking a toll on consumers' enthusiasm. The
group said its Consumer Confidence Index fell to 138.8 in June from
a revised 144.7 in May as higher rates and soaring gas prices
pressured the economy.
</P>
<P>
   As the Fed tightened credit to cool growth to a more sustainable
pace, investors have started shifting money from sector to sector
as they debated which stocks will perform best in a slowing
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, drug stocks and consumer goods companies were leading
the market higher. Johnson &AMP; Johnson rose $2.313 to $97.813 and 3M
rose $2 to $87.50.
</P>
<P>
   IBM fell $4.468 to $109.938 after a Merrill Lynch analyst said
he expects IBM's second-quarter revenue to be ''mediocre'' compared
with the year-ago quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said investors were demonstrating some cautious
optimism, evidenced by the fact that more stocks were rising than
falling. On the New York Stock Exchange, advancing issues
outnumbered decliners by a 4-to-3 margin.
</P>
<P>
   Also, trading activity was quiet, but not as anemic as some
analysts had expected on the day ahead of the Fed's decision. NYSE
volume came to 781.28 million shares in late afternoon, ahead of
Monday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   ''People are starting to put some money back to work,'' Keating
said. ''A good deal of cash built up on the sidelines while volume
tapered off in the past couple of months.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts noted that some buying and selling was due to
end-of-the-quarter reshuffling of portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 5.56 to 510.80.
</P>
