<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 15:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Sopranos' Faces Death of Actress  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Livia Soprano, the manipulative matriarch of New
Jersey's fictional mob family, would have really enjoyed this: Even
in death, people are consumed by her.
</P>
<P>
   The writers of HBO's ''The Sopranos'' are trying to figure out
how to deal with the death of actress Nancy Marchand, who played
Livia. They have nearly nine months before new shows air.
</P>
<P>
   Though Marchand made no secret of her lung cancer before dying
June 18, series creator David Chase said the writers had only once
before talked about losing her but quickly changed the subject
because it was too unpleasant.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, people have repeatedly come up to Chase and said,
''This is a problem for you, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   For while actor James Gandolfini, as Tony Soprano, is clearly
the star, Marchand's scenes were some of the most electric. The
relationship between Tony and his mother -- the woman who tried to
have him whacked in the first season -- is the emotional
underpinning of ''The Sopranos,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''One way or another, either through Livia's death or without
Livia's death, Tony Soprano has to get over his mother, which he
was doing,'' Chase said.
</P>
<P>
   The intrusion of real life into fiction is an occasional
challenge for TV writers, most recently seen with Michael J. Fox's
exit from ''Spin City.'' Some series handle it more adroitly than
others.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's character, New York City Deputy Mayor Michael Flaherty,
took the fall for a political scandal and quit his job. Fox is
leaving the series because of Parkinson's disease.
</P>
<P>
   When ''Cheers'' actor Nicholas Colasanto died suddenly in 1985,
so did his character, the bartender Coach. Actor Woody Harrelson
took his spot behind the bar.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Conrad, who as Sgt. Phil Esterhaus on ''Hill Street
Blues'' warned his officers, ''Let's be careful out there,''
continued in his role after contracting cancer, as did Jim Davis,
who was the patriarch Jock Ewing on ''Dallas.'' After their deaths,
the characters were killed and the shows went on.
</P>
<P>
   After Dick York left ''Bewitched'' because of illness in 1969,
actor Dick Sargent took over as Darrin and the series continued.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect a faux Livia on ''The Sopranos.''
</P>
<P>
   ''What we will probably do is deal with what does one feel like
when a parent dies with whom you haven't had a good relationship,''
Chase said.
</P>
<P>
   A misconception held by many of the show's fans is that Marchand
limited her appearances during the second season because of her
cancer. Instead, Chase said, her appearances were limited by her
dark-hearted character's deeds: Tony understandably held a grudge
over the hit attempt and didn't want to have anything to do with
Livia.
</P>
<P>
   Chase said he actually wrote scenes superfluous to the plot this
past year just to get Marchand more air time. Livia was in police
custody in her final scene, picked up with stolen airline tickets
that Tony had given her.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how Chase and his writers decide to deal with
Marchand's death, they will do their best to keep it a secret.
Chase would undoubtedly like the same look of surprise on viewers'
faces as Richie Aprile had when his girlfriend turned the gun on
him and fired.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is for certain: It will mean the end for one of Tony's
favorite sayings about his mother, one that became a catchphrase:
''She's dead to me!''
</P>
<P>
   ''No, we can't use that line,'' Chase said. ''But that line will
come back to haunt him, I'm sure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-27-00 1533 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000627.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 15:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FAA Runway Summit Debates Safety  </HEADLINE>
By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Concluding there's no ''silver bullet''
solution to the problem of close calls on airport runways, a panel
of experts proposed a series steps they called ''silver BBs.''
</P>
<P>
   Suggestions ranging from improved signs and lights to changes in
terminology, radio frequencies and better airport design were
debated Tuesday at the Federal Aviation Administration's National
Runway Safety Summit.
</P>
<P>
   The three-day conference is seeking to boil down ideas and
proposals collected during nine similar sessions around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Close calls on the nation's airport runways have increased
steadily over the last decade and are a growing concern in aviation
circles. More than 320 close calls were reported last year. Just
two weeks ago, the independent National Transportation Safety Board
returned to the issue and provided some proposals to the FAA.
</P>
<P>
   The agency is expected to develop a series of corrective actions
in the coming months based on the proposals it is accumulating.
</P>
<P>
   Special light signals that would tell a pilot turning on to a
taxiway when his plane is completely clear of the runway were
proposed by Kim Cardosi of the Transportation Department's Volpe
research center.
</P>
<P>
   ''The pilot may be clear of the runway, but the guy in seat 32J
may not be,'' she said, noting that with a large plane it can be
hard to tell when the whole craft is out of the runway and thus out
of the path of other planes.
</P>
<P>
   Vehicles as well as planes can pose a hazard on runways, and
Craig Williams of the American Association of Airport Executives
suggested requiring special tests and licenses for specific airport
activities.
</P>
<P>
   A limited license might be issued for people moving vehicles
around the apron and loading areas, he said, with an extended
license needed to drive a vehicle across runways and taxiways.
</P>
<P>
   Elaine McCoy of Ohio University also urged extra training in
ground operations for pilots, particularly private pilots who may
learn to fly at a small airport and later land or take off at a
larger, more complicated one.
</P>
<P>
   Raja Parasuraman of Catholic University of America suggested
improvements in lights to signal pilots, including the possibility
of red-green stop-and-go lights for crossing runways or waiting. A
red-green system is used at London's busy Heathrow Airport, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
   Several speakers urged that air traffic controllers not give
pilots taxi instructions when a plane is landing and completing its
rollout on the runway. This is a very busy time for pilots working
in a noisy cockpit, and it's easy to misunderstand instructions
that could wait a few minutes, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Discussing the problem of too much radio traffic, Cardosi
suggested that some current standard messages may be unnecessary.
For example, if a pilot has been waiting behind a jumbo jet for 10
minutes, and then watches the big plane take off, it shouldn't be
necessary to warn him about wake turbulence when he follows, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   David Kelley of the Mitre Corp. endorsed a Safety Board
suggestion that taxiing pilots be required to get specific
controller clearance before crossing each runway. Currently,
directions to proceed to a certain spot on the airport imply
permission to cross any intersecting runway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-27-00 1536 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000627.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Africa Oil Spill Worsens  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE COHEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) -- Their boots and overalls coated
with a layer of shiny oil, workers waded into rock pools Tuesday to
grab blackened pieces of kelp. With more oil hitting the mainland
with every tide, authorities predicted the ecological damage from
the spill could get much worse.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the slick has coated thousands of African penguins in
oil and angered many residents in a city that prizes its clean
coastline.
</P>
<P>
   ''As soon as the tide comes in, more oil comes in,'' supervisor
Mike Minaar said, gazing out at the Atlantic Ocean. He forecast at
least two more weeks of mopping up following Friday's oil spill.
</P>
<P>
   The large oil slick hit the mainland Saturday, the day after the
Panamanian-registered Treasure went down carrying 1,300 tons of
bunker oil and 90 tons of gas oil.
</P>
<P>
   So far only small patches of oil have been washed up on the
city's most popular beaches. But the Robben Island nature reserve,
home to about 14,000 adult African penguins and 6,000 chicks, has
been hit badly.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all the island's birds were coated with oil and efforts
are under way to evacuate the endangered birds -- the world's
third-largest penguin colony.
</P>
<P>
   The rescue effort is expected to become one of the largest of
its kind in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ''We suspect by the end of the week we will have between 10,000
and 12,000 birds to take care of,'' said Estelle van der Merwe of
the Southern African Foundation for the Conservation of Coastal
Birds. ''We have lost about 32 penguins so far.''
</P>
<P>
   The South African Maritime Safety Authority on Tuesday estimated
that 400 tons of oil had been released. Others had reported earlier
that just 100 to 300 tons had spilled.
</P>
<P>
   About 900 tons of oil were still thought to be trapped in the
ship, and cleanup workers are racing to pump it from the sunken
ship, said Capt. Bill Dernier of the maritime authority.
</P>
<P>
   The operation entails anchoring a barge over the wreck of the
Treasure and sending divers down with hoses to pump the oil out
from the ship's tanks.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are hoping to start pumping on Thursday, so we don't waste
the good weather,'' said Jimmy Cook, who is overseeing the dive
operation that's expected to take at least a week.
</P>
<P>
   It will be dangerous and difficult work.
</P>
<P>
   To reach some of the oil, divers will have to navigate their way
through the inside of the Treasure in chilly waters up to 100 feet
below the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Divers had to battle heavy swell when they used an underwater
video camera to survey the wreck, which showed the Treasure to be
badly damaged.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasure was managed by the Greek shipping company Good
Faith and owned by a Panamanian company, Dernier said. Earlier
reports said the Treasure was owned by a Chinese company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-27-00 1541 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
