<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Treasury Secretary Rubin Lauded  </HEADLINE>
By TERENCE HUNT
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Robert Rubin won praise for leading the
Treasury Department during America's longest economic expansion.
But President Clinton also remembered him as a failure -- as least
in his grasp of popular culture.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Rubin didn't know about the popular television
series, ''The X-Files.'' He didn't know who blues legend B.B. King
was. And he thought that folk singer Jimmy Buffett was the son of
billionaire investor Warren Buffett.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton poked fun at Rubin Tuesday -- and lavished praise on him,
too -- at the unveiling of Rubin's official portrait at the Treasury
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve Board chairman Alan Greenspan, Commerce
Secretary William Daley, and former Trade Representative Mickey
Kantor joined Clinton and Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers at
the unveiling.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin, now affiliated with Citigroup, served as Treasury
secretary from Jan. 10, 1995 until July 2, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wanted him because I knew he was committed at turning the
economy around,'' Clinton said. ''I knew he wanted the economy to
work for ordinary Americans. And I knew he cared very much about
poor people in poor places that are too often forgotten here in
Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton momentarily broke his 7&AMP;frac12; year rule against talking about
interest rates. Complimenting Summers for introducing him, Clinton
said, ''If that won't keep interest rates down, I don't know what
will.'' Clinton hastened to say he made the remark only to see who
would faint first: Summers or Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said that Clinton ''used to tease me, outrageously I
thought, about not knowing all the picky minutiae of popular
culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, Jimmy Buffett. ''Any normal person would say
Warren Buffett's son,'' Rubin said. He said he even checked with
Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
   ''And Alan said, 'It must be Warren's son,''' Rubin said. ''So,
it just goes to show, Mr. President.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said Clinton ''was not overwhelmingly impressed'' that
Greenspan had come up with the same answer. ''In fact, he said,
'That doesn't surprise me in the least.'''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.ustreas.gov
</P>
<P>
   www.whitehouse.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
