<HEADLINE> Youngsters Learn About Zoo-Keeping  </HEADLINE>
By CARL HARTMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Being a zoo keeper doesn't mean just cuddling
furry animals: the National Zoological Park is showing both
teen-agers and pre-teens that it can also mean cleaning up an
operating room with a mop and tin pail.
</P>
<P>
   ''How Do You Zoo?'' is a new interactive exhibit that covers
work with captive animals from serving appetizers to conducting
x-rays. For the pre-teens -- five to 10-year-olds -- it's play. They
pretend to feed oxygen, for example, into a small intensive care
unit with a plush owl inside. The teen volunteers -- there's a pool
of 20 -- get a four-day training course in the actual animal houses
so they can help handle the little ones.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a great way to build bridges,'' said Lucy Spelman, the
zoo's new director, introducing the program to reporters Tuesday.
She is the former chief vet.
</P>
<P>
   Clint Fields, executive director of the Friends of the National
Zoo, pointed out that play at being adults is an important part of
children's learning process.
</P>
<P>
   The ''Small Mammal House'' presents a choice of activities, the
zoo's statement said, ''including scooping up sloth 'poop'...'' At
the ''Commissary'' there are plastic food items in plastic
containers with menu cards listing the diets of different species.
The kids wear dark aprons rather than the white coats available in
the ''Animal Hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's morning session took on a K-5 group -- kindergarten
through fifth grade -- from the Turkey Thicket Recreational Center
in northeast Washington. One of the day's four volunteers was
13-year-old Christina Haramis, just graduated from a Montessori
school in Bowie, Md. Her ambitions don't run to zoo-keeping, but
she said she likes working with kids.
</P>
<P>
   Her interests run to marine life and archaeology and she hopes
to get a look at some ancient Greek ruins next March.
</P>
<P>
   ''That would be really wonderful,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Fields recalled that when he was a kid, all that he and his
friends thought of becoming were cowboys and Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ''We didn't know all the things we could be,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A zoo problem came up earlier in an unusual venue: the Senate
Committee on Rules and Administration. Lawrence M. Small, secretary
of the Smithsonian Institution which runs the zoo, was questioned
by panel chairman, Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky, about a shooting
among young visitors in April. Seven children were hurt and one
youngster charged with attempted murder.
</P>
<P>
   Small said the incident had occurred just outside the park.
</P>
<P>
   ''But it could have been 20 yards inside, too,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The only useful measure, he suggested, would be to increase both
internal security and cooperation with police on days when large
numbers of visitors are expected. The shooting occurred during an
annual black family day celebration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-27-00 1604 </TRAILER>
