<DOCNO> APW20000627.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Is Cautious on Mexico Election  </HEADLINE>
By KEN GUGGENHEIM
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Its southern neighbor and second-largest
trading partner is preparing for a dramatic election that could end
71 years of single-party rule. So what does the United States have
to say about Mexico's presidential election on Sunday?
</P>
<P>
   As little as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between the United States and Mexico are so sensitive
that the Clinton administration has avoided saying anything that
could even hint of U.S. interference.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico is historically wary of U.S. economic and military might,
and politicians routinely swear to defend national sovereignty.
U.S. officials are cautious about statements that could affect
cooperation on important issues including trade, drug smuggling or
immigration -- or become a campaign issue themselves.
</P>
<P>
   So, when pressed for comment, U.S. officials have made innocuous
comments praising Mexican democracy, saying they will accept
whatever choices Mexicans make and insisting that they have no
favorites among the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ''We very much look forward to seeing what the Mexican people
decide,'' Luis Gutierrez, deputy assistant secretary of state for
Western Hemisphere Affairs, told reporters in Washington last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Francisco Labastida of the governing Institutional Revolutionary
Party is in a tight race with Vicente Fox of the center-right
National Action Party. Cuauhtemoc Cardenas of the leftist
Democratic Revolution Party is a distant third.
</P>
<P>
   If the U.S. government had a favorite candidate, it would be
unlikely to admit it publicly. But even privately, U.S. officials
insist they have no preferences and are interested only in a fair
race that will assure Mexico's continued stability.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts generally believe them.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that a victory by one or the other does have some
implications for the United States, but they're much less
significant than the view that the election is seen as free and
fair,'' said Robert Pastor, a political science professor at Emory
University and a former director of Latin American and Caribbean
Affairs on the National Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of the front-runners has indicated they would make major
changes in the relationship with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   A Labastida victory could offer greater continuity in
U.S.-Mexican relations. But a Fox victory could please U.S.
officials who see it as an important advance in Mexican democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, a former Coca-Cola executive who speaks English, is
generally seen as being more open to a closer relationship with the
United States. But in Mexico, he has been accused of accepting
illegal foreign contributions and his patriotism has been
questioned. That means he would likely face greater scrutiny in his
relations with the United States -- and have less room to maneuver --
than Labastida would.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that each candidate has its pros and cons, but I think
they do somehow even out,'' said Armand B. Peschard-Sverdrup,
director of the Mexico Project at the Center for Strategic and
International Studies in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Election day could be trickier for U.S. officials than the
campaign has been. Most polls show Labastida and Fox in a
statistical tie, though Labastida has a slight advantage.
</P>
<P>
   If Labastida is declared the winner by a narrow margin and
opposition candidates challenge the vote, any declaration by the
United States -- or maybe even the lack of a declaration -- could be
seen in Mexico as interference.
</P>
<P>
   Just a month ago, the United States criticized the Peruvian
presidential run-off after the opposition candidate backed out,
citing fears of fraud.
</P>
<P>
   No one expects a similar response over Mexico. There's no chance
of the same kind of election-day fraud, said George Grayson, a
Mexico expert at the College of William &AMP; Mary in Williamsburg, Va.
</P>
<P>
   And the United States could never take a heavy-handed approach
with Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think Washington will bend over backward to not involve
itself in adjudicating the Mexican election,'' Grayson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-27-00 1609 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000627.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Exhibit Features Viet Photo  </HEADLINE>
By SUE LEEMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Associated Press photographer Nick Ut's wrenching
picture of a 9-year-old Vietnamese girl fleeing a napalm attack
went on display Tuesday for the first time with the camera used to
shoot the famous image.
</P>
<P>
   The 1972 shot of Phan Thi Kim Phuc earned Ut a Pulitzer Prize
and thrust the burned, screaming youngster into photographic
history.
</P>
<P>
   Along with other Ut photographs, they form part of a display on
technology at the $75 million Wellcome Wing of London's Science
Museum, which opens Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a good place to show the camera because a lot of
people will see it,'' said Ut, who attended the press viewing
Tuesday with Kim Phuc, the girl in his famous photo and now a
longtime friend. ''Everyone knows the photo, but not the camera.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Queen Elizabeth II toured the exhibit, exclaiming ''Is it
really you?'' when she saw the 37-year-old Kim Phuc standing next
to the picture, clad in a black silk Vietnamese tunic and trousers.
</P>
<P>
   In preparing the exhibit, senior curator Andrew Nahum said he
looked at many photographs ''but I couldn't persuade myself that
any of them had the emotional power of the Kim Phuc photo.''
</P>
<P>
   ''More than just showing the iconic image, we want to unpack the
history around it,'' Nahum said. So the exhibit identifies other
children in the photo, including Kim's older brother, who lost an
eye but survived the South Vietnamese army's napalm bomb attack on
the village of Trang Bang, 25 miles northwest of Ho Chi Minh City.
</P>
<P>
   Next to Ut's Leica viewfinder with its wide-angle lens stands a
Muirhead transmitters once used to send photographs around the
world. Other Ut pictures show two of Kim Phuc's male cousins, one
just 9 months old, who died in the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Stretched over four floors, the Wellcome Wing has displays on
genetics, digital technology, bio-medicine and artificial
intelligence, and a 450-seat IMAX cinema.
</P>
<P>
   A section on new developments already displays details of
Monday's announcement that scientists have mapped the human genetic
code.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most museums have a 'build and walk away' philosophy,'' said
John Durant, head of the Wellcome Wing program. ''We will stay on
the pace.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim Phuc, who was treated for her burns in West Germany, studied
and married in Cuba, and defected to the West in 1992. Ut, now an
AP photographer based in Los Angeles, often visits her in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Ut returned to Trang Bang in April, the 25th anniversary of the
end of the Vietnam War, but Kim Phuc -- who works as a UNESCO
ambassador and runs a foundation for children damaged by war -- has
not visited her homeland since leaving in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am not ready yet, financially or emotionally,'' she said
Tuesday. ''Someday, I'll go. Now I'm just happy to be free.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Science Museum site: http://www.sciencemuseum.org.uk
</P>
</TEXT>
