<HEADLINE> RETRANSMITTING to fix cycle designator  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) - Convicted murderer Robert O. Marshall is
another step closer to execution after 14 years on death row.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall's first appeal in the federal courts has been rejected,
continuing a string of setbacks in state courts, where the onetime
insurance salesman from Ocean County has exhausted his appeals.
</P>
<P>
   No date has been set for his execution, pending further appeals.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Joseph E. Irenas rejected the inmate's bid
for freedom, finding no merit to Marshall's argument that he was
denied a fair trial.
</P>
<P>
   In a ruling filed Friday and publicized Tuesday, Irenas denied
Marshall's application seeking a chance to gather evidence and have
a hearing in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   Irenas, who sits in Camden, wrote he believes ''as the New
Jersey Supreme Court found, that (any error in) petitioner's trial
was neither 'fundamentally unfair' nor 'so infected the entire
trial that the resulting conviction violated his due process.'''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall, who is imprisoned at New Jersey State Prison in
Trenton, was told of the ruling by one of his public defenders,
said Judith L. Borman, a public defender who prepared the latest
appeal, known as a ''habeas corpus'' petition.
</P>
<P>
   ''I assume he was very disappointed,'' Borman said.
</P>
<P>
   She said the defender's office will prepare a request to the 3rd
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, asking for permission to appeal the
ruling to the circuit court. Habeas rulings have no automatic right
of appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe we have substantial constitutional issues, and it
should have been granted,'' Borman said.
</P>
<P>
   The petition was opposed by the state attorney general's office,
which was pleased with the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a well-reasoned decision. We always contended his
federal claims were without merit, and the judge agreed he got a
fair trial,'' office spokesman Chuck Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall was convicted in 1986 of hiring men to murder his wife,
Maria, in 1984 so he could collect life insurance and continue an
extramarital affair.
</P>
<P>
   The case was chronicled in Joseph McGinniss' 1989 best seller,
''Blind Faith'' and in a television mini-series based on the book.
</P>
<P>
   In his habeas petition, Marshall claimed misconduct by the Ocean
County prosecutor's office, including improperly failing to
disclose evidence favorable to him.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall also said his constitutional rights were violated
because he had an ineffective lawyer and an unfair jury.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Marshall claims the state's death penalty and
appeal procedures are unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Irenas rejected all 22 claims made by Marshall, 60, who had
lived in Toms River with his wife and their children.
</P>
<P>
   He was sentenced to death by lethal injection for hiring three
Louisiana men to murder Maria so he could collect $1.4 million in
life insurance and continue an extramarital affair with Sarann
Kraushaar, who testified against him.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Marshall, 42, was found shot to death on Sept. 7, 1984, at
a rest area along the Garden State Parkway. Marshall, a prominent
businessman, has maintained his innocence. He told police he had
pulled over to check on a tire and was knocked unconscious.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Marshall became the first death row inmate to have his
death sentence upheld by the state Supreme Court since New Jersey
restored capital punishment in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1997, that court again affirmed his death sentence,
following the post-conviction relief process. The U.S. Supreme
Court, which hears appeals from state high courts, declined in
October 1997 to take his appeal of that decision.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey has conducted no executions since restoring the death
penalty. Fifteen men are on death row.
</P>
<P>
   The habeas petition raised many of the issues rejected by the
state Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall contended that his trial lawyer, Glenn Zeitz, failed to
