<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Chilean Soldier Ready To Talk  </HEADLINE>
By EVA VERGARA
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- Relatives of the missing urged a former
Chilean army guard on Tuesday to go to authorities with all he
knows about the reported execution of political prisoners after the
1973 military coup.
</P>
<P>
   The former soldier, Roberto Saldias, told state-owned television
in an interview Monday night that prisoners were routinely executed
at a soccer stadium in the Chilean capital after the coup led by
Gen. Augusto Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
   Saldias' disclosure marked the first time that a member of the
armed forces has verified stories of executions publicly and
without the cloak of anonymity. Rumors about executions, torture
and other violations of human rights at the National Stadium after
the coup have been rampant for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Viviana Diaz, who heads a group of relatives of the missing,
told The Associated Press that the next step is for Saldias to take
his information to authorities probing human rights violations of
the former dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only thing to do is to hand this information over to the
competent authorities ... to the tribunals,'' said Diaz, whose
group for years has sought the whereabouts of loved ones and
punishment for those responsible.
</P>
<P>
   According to an official report, 3,197 people were killed and
more than 1,000 are missing from the 17-year regime that began with
the September 1973 coup that toppled Marxist president Salvador
Allende.
</P>
<P>
   In the television interview, Saldias said he was prepared to
identify the executioners by name. ''They took the law into their
own hands,'' said Saldias.
</P>
<P>
   Saldias said he was one of the hundreds of guards at the main
Santiago soccer stadium, which was used as a prison camp. According
to Saldias, prisoners there were put in groups identified by
yellow, black and red discs.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whoever received a red disc had no chance'' and would be
killed, Saldias said.
</P>
<P>
   The army said Tuesday it would have no comment.
</P>
<P>
   Saldias' willingness to reveal the names of alleged human rights
violators could be the first concrete, public result of the armed
forces' commitment to help determine the fate of more than 1,000
dissidents who disappeared after being arrested under the
dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   An agreement with the military was reached last week that
included the guarantee of anonymity for those who deliver
information on those who disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   President Ricardo Lagos backed the accord and insists it will
help find out the truth. Wherever he goes, Lagos has appealed for
unity among Chileans, who remain deeply divided over Pinochet's
1973-90 dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   At Lagos' unveiling of a monument Monday to Allende, he again
called for unity even as demonstrators shouted: ''Trial for
Pinochet!''
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet, 84, has appealed to the Supreme Court to overturn a
lower court ruling stripping him of diplomatic immunity.
Prosecutors want to try him for human rights violations committed
during his regime, and the high court's decision was expected in
July.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-27-00 1629 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000627.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mugabe Appeals For Reconciliation  </HEADLINE>
By RAVI NESSMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- President Robert Mugabe appealed for
national reconciliation Tuesday after his ruling party narrowly won
parliamentary elections following a bitter campaign marked by
violence and intimidation.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe promised to work with Zimbabwe's newly elected
parliament, which will have a serious opposition presence for the
first time in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our next parliament is certainly destined to prove very
lively, but hopefully lively in a very positive way,'' the
76-year-old authoritarian president said.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition candidates, promising a change from the country's
disastrous economic performance, made sweeping gains in the vote.
The 9-month-old Movement for Democratic Change won 57 seats,
compared to 62 for Mugabe's ZANU-PF party. An independent party won
one.
</P>
<P>
   The previous parliament had only three opposition members.
</P>
<P>
   The strong opposition showing in the weekend vote, however, will
not give it much say in running the country. Its strength will be
diluted after Mugabe appoints 30 members to the 150-seat
parliament, as permitted by the constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe has said he will not bring the opposition into the
Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   The voting Saturday and Sunday came after months of political
violence and intimidation that left more than 30 people dead.
European Union monitors said the violence, which they called
state-sponsored terror, meant the elections were flawed and the
campaign was not free and fair.
</P>
<P>
   MDC leader Morgan Tsvangirai expressed disappointment that his
party had not won a majority, but said the country was ''on the
path of change.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Anyone who believes the destiny of this country rests on
Robert Mugabe must have his head examined,'' Tsvangirai said.
</P>
<P>
   Tsvangirai said he would challenge Mugabe when the president's
term expires in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   In his televised address Tuesday, Mugabe said it was now time
for the country to unite across racial, class and ethnic divides.
</P>
<P>
   During the election campaign, Mugabe branded the opposition as
puppets of the country's small, but economically powerful white
community and stooges of Britain, the former colonial power. He
called white farmers enemies of the country and promised to seize
some of their land and redistribute it to the country's
impoverished, landless blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the campaign's violence and intimidation, voters turned
out in large numbers -- more than double the turnout of the last
parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
   In February, voters shocked the government by rejecting a
referendum that would have strengthened Mugabe's powers. The
parliamentary vote also was seen as a blow to the government, which
had predicted the opposition would be lucky to win three seats.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition's strong showing was clearly a protest vote
against the government, said Jonathan Moyo, a spokesman for the
ruling party, the Zimbabwe African National Union-Patriotic Front.
Many voters cited endemic corruption and Zimbabwe's withering
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwe had one of Africa's strongest economies at independence
in 1980. Today, it is wracked with high unemployment and soaring
inflation, crippling fuel shortages and chronic shortages of hard
currency.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're on a course that is not sustainable, but we've got a
government that is very proud of itself and may not want to
change,'' said independent economist John Robertson.
</P>
<P>
   Since February, armed ruling party militants, with Mugabe's
support, have occupied more than 1,600 of the country's white-owned
commercial farms and demanded they be redistributed to landless
blacks. The occupations have badly damaged commercial farming, the
most important sector of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of its election victory, the government will push
forward with its plans to seize at least 800 white farms, Moyo
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The majority of people who voted for ZANU-PF ... voted for
land, and they will get that,'' Moyo said.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling party performed strongly in rural areas, its
traditional stronghold. However, those were the areas most affected
by a campaign of political violence and intimidation, and MDC
officials said the tactics worked in some areas.
</P>
<P>
   Tsvangirai, who lost his bid for a parliamentary seat, said the
opposition would challenge the results in up to 20 districts.
</P>
<P>
   The violence, the promise of land seizures and Mugabe's heated
condemnations of whites have hurt Zimbabwe's chances of gaining
economic support from Western countries, said Robertson.
</P>
<P>
   ''The credibility of the government has suffered such damage
that people are not going to accept anything it says,'' he said.
''Zimbabwe is going to have to earn its right to be taken seriously
again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
