<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Another error in summer school notifications  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Letters were sent out in error this week
incorrectly telling some public-school students that they must
attend summer school, the Board of Education said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We know some letters were sent out in error,'' said Pam
McDonnell, board spokeswoman. ''It does not seem to have been just
in one spot in the city.''
</P>
<P>
   She attributed the problem to errors in entering data from
standardized test scores that help determine whether children are
promoted to the next grade.
</P>
<P>
   She said parents are allowed to appeal decisions made regarding
whether their children should attend summer school, and delays in
processing the results of those appeals may also have created some
errors on the final list.
</P>
<P>
   McDonnell could not provide an estimate of how many children
were affected.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second major problem to plague the city's new policy
of requiring children to attend summer school if their grades on
standardized tests don't measure up.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, more than 8,600 city elementary and middle school
students were told to attend summer school or were held back
because a testing company incorrectly evaluated their grades.
</P>
<P>
   CTB/McGraw-Hill, a Monterey, Calif.-based company which has
tested millions of students across the nation in its 72 years,
notified the Board of Education about the mistake after the 1999
summer school sessions were completed.
</P>
<P>
   This year's mistake is also causing anguish among parents. One
mother, Yasmin Sanchez, said on Tuesday her son's third-grade
teacher told her a few weeks ago that her son had passed both the
standardized math and reading tests, and that he would be promoted
to fourth grade at PS 59 in Belmont in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Then she got the letter this week from the Board of Ed informing
her 8-year-old boy that he had to go to summer school.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was devastated,'' she said. ''I was furious. I was upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez went to the principal's office and was told ''I wasn't
the only one. There were more parents who received the letter after
being told their child had passed, and they were complaining.''
</P>
<P>
   McDonnell said school officials are double-checking the names of
children who received the letters against the lists of children who
are not going to be promoted.
</P>
<P>
   But McDonnell noted that test scores are not the sole criterion.
If a child fails one but not the other of the two standardized
tests but has good attendance and decent classwork, a teacher can
recommend that the child be promoted. She said some of the
confusion over who must attend summer school may stem from a lack
of communication between parents and teachers over a child's
progress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
