<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba Embargo for Food Sales To Ease  </HEADLINE>
By PHILIP BRASHER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Republicans cut a deal Tuesday to allow
direct sales of U.S. food to Cuba for the first time in four
decades as hard-line anti-communists yielded to pressure from the
farm and business lobbies to ease the embargo on Fidel Castro's
government.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, concluded early Tuesday after 5&AMP;frac12; hours of
negotiations, may be largely symbolic: It would bar both the
federal government and U.S. banks from financing food sales.
</P>
<P>
   The House is expected to attach the agreement to a military
construction bill this week. It still must be approved by the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. George Nethercutt, R-Wash., a leading advocate for easing
the embargo, said the agreement was a ''huge breakthrough for our
farmers.'' He said Cuba could finance its purchases of U.S. food
through other countries.
</P>
<P>
   The White House was wary of the deal, because it also would
require congressional approval before a president could impose
future embargoes on food and medicine to other countries.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are not opposed to allowing things like food and medicine
to go to Cuba, as long as it is for the benefit of the people and
not the benefit of the Castro government,'' said White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart. ''We do have concerns, on what I call an
institutional basis, based on the limits that it puts on
presidential prerogatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Anti-Castro negotiators sought to downplay the agreement's
impact. Rep. Ileana Ross-Lehtinen, R-Fla., said the legislation
would ''make it as difficult as possible'' for such sales to take
place. The agreement also would write into law the existing ban on
Americans going to Cuba as tourists.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe that what Castro has wanted is access'' to U.S.
financial markets, she said. ''He's not going to get any of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The World Policy Institute has estimated that the United States
could commercially export more than $400 million in food and
agricultural products to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   But the restrictions on financing mean Cuba is likely to buy no
more than $45 million worth of U.S. farm goods in the first year --
largely rice, soy and powdered milk, said John Kavulich, president
of the U.S.-Cuba Trade and Economic Council.
</P>
<P>
   ''Short-term, this is symbolic. Medium- to long-term it can
provide some substantive opportunity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both the American Farm Bureau Federation and the U.S. Chamber of
Commerce praised the pact as well. ''We view this as step one.
We'll be back for step two and step three later,'' said Mary Kay
Thatcher, a lobbyist for the farm bureau.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute over whether to weaken the 38-year-old embargo has
stalled passage of an agricultural appropriations bill for a month.
</P>
<P>
   A provision the House Appropriations Committee attached to the
bill in May would allow private U.S. financing of food sales to
Cuba, something that would be forbidden under the agreement reached
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate voted overwhelmingly last year to ease the Cuban
embargo, but the House refused to go along. The effort gained
momentum this year because of tight re-election races faced by
Nethercutt and other GOP proponents of easing the embargo.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats also dropped their support of the embargo after
the immigration battle over Elian Gonzalez, the boy who has been
the subject of a legal tug-of-war between his Florida relatives and
his father, who lives in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Ashcroft, a Missouri Republican who has led the Senate
effort to roll back the Cuban embargo, was studying the agreement
Tuesday, aides said. But he issued a statement saying ''a
tremendous accomplishment for American agriculture, and an
affirmation of America's humanitarian values, is in sight,''
</P>
<P>
   An ally of Ashcroft's, Democratic Sen. Byron Dorgan, said the
agreement was ''more symbolic than real.''
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Dick Armey and Republican Whip Tom DeLay,
both of Texas, had strongly opposed weakening the embargo but left
it up to Castro critics Ross-Lehtinen and Rep. Lincoln Diaz-Balart,
R-Fla., to negotiate a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sometimes you're the windshield. Sometimes you're the bug. In
this case I'm the bug,'' Armey said Tuesday, quoting a popular
song. ''There is a strong desire to open that market for American
sales. You cannot thwart the will of the House.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban American National Foundation criticized the agreement
and said it would continue running pro-embargo ads in Nethercutt's
district.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement would not affect sales of U.S. medicine and health
products, which have been permitted since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: U.S.-Cuba Trade and Economic Council:
http://www.cubatrade.org
</P>
<P>
   Cuban American National Foundation: http://www.canf.org/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
