<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State pledges $41M to redevelop Camden neighborhood  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Gov. Christie Whitman on Tuesday unveiled a
$41.2 million financing package for construction of hundreds of new
homes in a blighted neighborhood in Camden, the state's poorest
city.
</P>
<P>
   The state pledged $33 million in conditional funding for
Westfield Acres/Hope VI, a planned development of 523 homes and
apartments that would replace the dilapidated Westfield Acres
public housing complex.
</P>
<P>
   The state funds are contingent on a successful application for
federal funds by the Camden Housing Authority and some financing
approvals by the New Jersey Housing and Mortgage Finance Agency.
</P>
<P>
   The state also has approved $8.2 million for construction of a
50-unit rental development next to the Hope VI site. That
development, on North 32nd Street, will consist of 45 duplex units
and five single-family units to be rented to low-income families.
</P>
<P>
   The development is being funded with $1.3 million from the state
Department of Community Affairs and $6.9 million from the Housing
and Mortgage Finance Agency.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are laying the foundation for a strong new community,''
said Jane M. Kenny, commissioner of the Department of Community
Affairs. ''We're fast approaching that point of critical mass that
turns an entire neighborhood around.''
</P>
<P>
   The Camden Housing Authority is applying to the U.S. Department
of Housing and Urban Development for about $35 million in
additional funding under a program that tries to replace blighted
and obsolete public housing with mixed-income, low-rise town houses
and garden-style apartments, as well as road and infrastructure
improvements and social service programs.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is much more than housing,'' said Kenny. ''It represents
the rebirth of the entire neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   If the federal application is successful, the Westfield
Acres/Hope VI project would be developed by St. Joseph's Carpenter
Society, a nonprofit community development corporation, with
private developers K. Hovnanian and Pennrose Properties.
</P>
<P>
   Pennrose also is the developer of the North 32nd Street project,
with the St. Joseph's Carpenter Society.
</P>
</TEXT>
