<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Urges To Uphold Ohio Motto  </HEADLINE>
By KATHERINE RIZZO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House gave its symbolic support to Ohio's
state motto -- ''With God, all things are possible'' -- which a
federal appeals court ruled violated church-state separation
provision of the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   On a vote of 333-27 Tuesday, with 66 other lawmakers voting
''present,'' the House said the court ruling should be overturned.
</P>
<P>
   ''The court's action is nothing more than political correctness
run rampant,'' said Rep. Mike Oxley, R-Ohio, chief sponsor of the
nonbinding resolution.
</P>
<P>
   The group Americans United for Separation of Church and State
issued a statement calling the vote an election-year stunt.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is shameless political grandstanding,'' said the Rev.
Barry W. Lynn, the group's executive director. ''It is deplorable
to see government meddling with religion in such a reckless and
political fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the ''no votes'' on the resolution was from Rep.
Stephanie Tubbs Jones, a Democrat from Cleveland who said her vote
stemmed from her great respect for laws and the courts. ''As a
former prosecutor and judge, I take decisions made by the courts
very seriously,'' she said. ''This violated the separation of
church and state as written into the United States Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohio adopted the motto in 1959. It became an issue in 1997 when
then-Gov. George Voinovich decided to etch it on a bronze plaque
embedded in front of the Statehouse.
</P>
<P>
   In a 2-1 decision in April, a panel of the 6th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals said U.S. District Judge James Graham of Columbus
erred in 1998 when he concluded the words were acceptable as a
motto if the state did not attribute them to their biblical source.
In the New Testament, Matthew 19:26 attributes the comment to
Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   In a dissent, Judge David Nelson said he found Ohio's motto no
more troubling than the national motto ''In God We Trust'' that
appears on money.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio has appealed the ruling to the full court.
</P>
<P>
   During debate on the resolution, Rep. Steve Chabot, R-Ohio,
noted the day's session began with a prayer, and the House chamber
displays the national motto.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's one of the things that I think makes people wonder about
their government and what's going on here,'' Chabot said. ''It's
such a ludicrous decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim Traficant, D-Ohio, drew a smattering of applause with a
floor speech in which he called federal judges a ''bunch of
overeducated nincompoops.''
</P>
<P>
   ''They have become so politically correct they're street-stupid
and miss the whole point,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio is not the only state with a motto mentioning God. Arizona
uses ''God Enriches,'' and South Dakota's is ''Under God the people
will rule.'' Florida's motto of ''In God we trust'' mirrors the
nation's.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Vasvari, legal director for the American Civil Liberties
Union of Ohio, which is challenging the Ohio motto, said the other
slogans ''have much more casual or bland references to God.'' The
ACLU went to court over Ohio's motto because it uses sacred text,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The resolution is H.Res. 494.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://thomas.loc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-27-00 1653 </TRAILER>
