<HEADLINE> St Dept: China Can't Use Building  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The State Department is prohibiting China's
state-run news agency from occupying an apartment building it
bought near the Pentagon while the department decides whether to
allow cancel the purchase.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese Embassy provided the department Monday a copy of a
May 22 letter the department never received that was to notify the
U.S. government of the Xinhua agency's intention to buy the
seven-story building, State Department spokesman Philip Reeker
said.
</P>
<P>
   Reeker said under rules governing Chinese government purchase of
property in Washington, the department has until Aug. 26 to approve
or disallow the sale, which Xinhua said was completed this month.
</P>
<P>
   ''As of right now, the Xinhua news agency has been put on notice
by the department, through the embassy of the People's Republic of
China, that they may not occupy or use the building they have
purchased without first seeking department approval, and we will
continue to look at this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reeker repeated assertions that Xinhua failed to observe U.S.
law in making its decision to purchase the building.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're currently evaluating the situation and are considering
options available to us under the Foreign Missions Act,'' he said.
He would not elaborate on the options.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the House approved a measure to withhold from the
State Department any money it might use to approve the a sale.
Reeker said the issue should be resolved before the law could have
any impact.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of Congress and others have said Xinhua could spy
on the Pentagon from the building. The Chinese deny that the news
agency's employees are spies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
