<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Jews Hurt On Beautification  </HEADLINE>
By FRANCES D'EMILIO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- At a seminar on Pope Pius IX, a woman stood from the
audience and introduced herself: Elena Mortara, great-great-niece
of a Bolognese Jew who was forcibly baptized as a toddler and then
taken from his family to be virtually adopted by the 19-century
pontiff.
</P>
<P>
   Now Pius IX is due to be beatified Sept. 3, and Elena Mortara
said she hoped that doesn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have been damaged by this,'' she told the seminar Tuesday,
referring to the forced conversion.
</P>
<P>
   Italian Jewish leaders said the beatification -- which advances
Pius on the path to sainthood -- threatens to harm two decades of
efforts by Pope John Paul II to improve Vatican relations with
Jews.
</P>
<P>
   The Mortara case ''is the biggest wound that remains in the
Italian Jewish world .... that still hasn't scarred over'' after
more than 150 years, said Amos Luzzatto, president of the Union of
Italian Jewish Communities. His organization and a historical
society were hosts of the seminar, which examined Pope Pius IX's
legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Edgardo Mortara was baptized secretly when he was two years old
by a housemaid worried about his soul when he had a high fever.
When he was six he was snatched away from his parents by papal
police in 1858 and brought to Rome, where Pius IX took him under
his wing. The boy later entered a seminary and became a priest.
</P>
<P>
   B'nai B'rith International's president, Richard D. Heideman, has
expressed dismay in a letter to the head of the Vatican
congregation that handles the process toward sainthood.
</P>
<P>
   ''From the Jewish perspective, Pius IX was the pope who
countenanced the abduction of a 6-year-old Jewish child and his
conversion -- obviously against the will of this family -- to
Catholicism,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Many Jews are already upset by John Paul's defense of another
Pius, Pius XII, who is a candidate for beatification and who Jews
and others allege didn't use his moral authority enough to save
Jews during the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Yet John Paul has won widespread admiration from Jews for his
efforts at healing centuries-old wounds between Catholics and Jews,
including his groundbreaking trip this year to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Elena Mortara, who recalled that her father used to talk with
Edgardo before the latter's death in 1940, said the Jewish
community is ''embarrassed'' to intervene in the beatification
process, she cannot help but protest her ancestor's forced
conversion.
</P>
<P>
   Italian Jewish leader Luzzatto said the Pius IX beatification
will ''leave in us a bitterness'' that will affect Jewish-Vatican
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Monsignor Carlo Liberati, a Vatican official involved in the
process leading to Pius IX's beatification, said Catholics have the
duty to try to ''send to paradise'' the soul of an unbaptized child
in danger of dying.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I were Pius IX, I would have baptized him too,'' Liberati
said of the Mortara boy. He criticized opponents of the
beatification for what he said was ''using today's mentality to
judge the facts of 150 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Liberati, in a telephone interview, said Edgardo Mortara
deposited testimony on behalf of Pius IX's beatification.
</P>
<P>
   Pius IX's pontificate, from 1846 to 1878, was the longest in
history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-27-00 1723 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000627.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peace Corps Expands Anti-AIDS Fight  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BRISCOE
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- All Peace Corps volunteers in Africa will be
trained in methods necessary to slow the spread of AIDS, the agency
announced Tuesday in launching a worldwide campaign against the
disease.
</P>
<P>
   Peace Corps director Mark Schneider, as part of the
unprecedented effort, asked for up to 200 former volunteers to
return to duty as a ''crisis corps'' for up to six months to help
combat the disease that has hit sub-Saharan Africa harder than any
other region.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers formerly worked exclusively in agriculture, small
business, education and other projects but now will spend part of
their time teaching AIDS prevention and care. Health volunteers
will focus even more on the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Additional volunteers will be recruited to spend all their time
fighting spread of the sexually transmitted HIV virus, Schneider
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Peace Corps has 2,400 volunteers in Africa. With turnover,
5,000 are expected to receive AIDS training over the next three
years. In all, 7,000 volunteers are in 76 countries.
</P>
<P>
   The AIDS drive follows a Clinton administration declaration in
April that the global epidemic of the sexually transmitted disease
is a threat to U.S. national security -- a proclamation criticized
by Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., and some other
Republicans as a political move to appeal to ''certain groups.''
</P>
<P>
   ''With specialties that cut across every sector of society, ...
Peace Corps volunteers are in a unique position to impact AIDS from
every angle,'' Schneider told a crowd of Peace Corps and other
officials as well as 29 new volunteers headed for Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no option for any organization working in development
other than to play a role in helping these countries confront the
HIV-AIDS crisis,'' Schneider said in an interview before the
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS outpaces malaria and war fatalities as the leading cause of
deaths in sub-Saharan Africa. Two-thirds of the 31 million
HIV-infected people live on the continent. The disease has killed
11 million Africans, 80 percent of total world AIDS deaths.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. concern for AIDS abroad has increased with intelligence
projections that the depth of the AIDS crisis correlates with the
likelihood of revolutionary wars, ethnic conflicts, genocide and
failure of partial democracies.
</P>
<P>
   Schneider said Peace Corps volunteers can have a big influence
because they work with local communities and can spread their
expertise to hundreds of thousands of people.
</P>
<P>
   Extra funding for the effort comes from the Bill and Melinda
Gates Foundation and the David and Lucile Packard Foundation,
Schneider said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-27-00 1725 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000627.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Sopranos' creator is trying to deal with actress' death  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Livia Soprano, the manipulative matriarch of New
Jersey's fictional mob family, would have really enjoyed this: Even
in death, people are consumed by her.
</P>
<P>
   The writers of HBO's ''The Sopranos'' are trying to figure out
how to deal with the death of actress Nancy Marchand, who played
Livia. They have nearly nine months before new shows air.
</P>
<P>
   Though Marchand made no secret of her lung cancer before dying
June 18, series creator David Chase said the writers had only once
before talked about losing her but quickly changed the subject
because it was too unpleasant.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, people have repeatedly come up to Chase and said,
''This is a problem for you, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   For while actor James Gandolfini, as Tony Soprano, is clearly
the star, Marchand's scenes were some of the most electric. The
relationship between Tony and his mother - the woman who tried to
have him whacked in the first season - is the emotional
underpinning of ''The Sopranos,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''One way or another, either through Livia's death or without
Livia's death, Tony Soprano has to get over his mother, which he
was doing,'' Chase said.
</P>
<P>
   The intrusion of real life into fiction is an occasional
challenge for TV writers, most recently seen with Michael J. Fox's
exit from ''Spin City.'' Some series handle it more adroitly than
others.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's character, New York City Deputy Mayor Michael Flaherty,
took the fall for a political scandal and quit his job. Fox is
leaving the series because of Parkinson's disease.
</P>
<P>
   When ''Cheers'' actor Nicholas Colasanto died suddenly in 1985,
so did his character, the bartender Coach. Actor Woody Harrelson
took his spot behind the bar.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Conrad, who as Sgt. Phil Esterhaus on ''Hill Street
Blues'' warned his officers, ''Let's be careful out there,''
continued in his role after contracting cancer, as did Jim Davis,
who was the patriarch Jock Ewing on ''Dallas.'' After their deaths,
the characters were killed and the shows went on.
</P>
<P>
   After Dick York left ''Bewitched'' because of illness in 1969,
actor Dick Sargent took over as Darrin and the series continued.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect a faux Livia on ''The Sopranos.''
</P>
<P>
   ''What we will probably do is deal with what does one feel like
when a parent dies with whom you haven't had a good relationship,''
Chase said.
</P>
<P>
   A misconception held by many of the show's fans is that Marchand
limited her appearances during the second season because of her
cancer. Instead, Chase said, her appearances were limited by her
dark-hearted character's deeds: Tony understandably held a grudge
over the hit attempt and didn't want to have anything to do with
Livia.
</P>
<P>
   Chase said he actually wrote scenes superfluous to the plot this
past year just to get Marchand more air time. Livia was in police
custody in her final scene, picked up with stolen airline tickets
that Tony had given her.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how Chase and his writers decide to deal with
Marchand's death, they will do their best to keep it a secret.
Chase would undoubtedly like the same look of surprise on viewers'
faces as Richie Aprile had when his girlfriend turned the gun on
him and fired.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is for certain: It will mean the end for one of Tony's
favorite sayings about his mother, one that became a catchphrase:
''She's dead to me!''
</P>
<P>
   ''No, we can't use that line,'' Chase said. ''But that line will
come back to haunt him, I'm sure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-27-00 1727 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000627.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Rebel Attack Kills 2 Cops  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Guerrillas firing homemade missiles
flattened a church and a police station and killed two officers in
an overnight attack on a small southern town, officials said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Two other policemen were wounded, and a bank and several homes
were destroyed in the 12-hour siege of Algeciras, 162 miles from
the capital, Bogota.
</P>
<P>
   ''They arrived, they entered (the town), and they destroyed
everything,'' one resident, fighting back tears, told a Colombian
television crew. The man, who said his house was commandeered by
rebels during the fighting, asked not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   Guerrillas from the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or
FARC, retreated early Tuesday after air force fighters were called
in to repel the attack, military said.
</P>
<P>
   Algeciras is just 48 miles from San Vicente del Caguan, the hub
of a demilitarized zone about twice the size of New Jersey cleared
of government troops to facilitate peace talks with the FARC,
Colombia's largest rebel band.
</P>
<P>
   Regional army commander Col. Alberto Tamayo said FARC rebels
based in the peace zone carried out the attack on Algeciras.
</P>
<P>
   Peace negotiations to end the South American country's 36-year
conflict are going forward without a cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of European delegates are expected to arrive in San
Vicente del Caguan on Thursday for a two-day conference hosted by
the government and the FARC on eradicating illegal drug crops.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-27-00 1730 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000627.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vacationers Urged To Be Careful  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- At the onset of the tourist season, the State
Department on Tuesday urged American citizens worldwide to be on
the lookout for possible threats from terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   An announcement by the department said the advisory was not
issued in response to any particular threat, but is intended to
emphasize an ongoing concern for the security of Americans
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement said that periods on or around significant
dates, such as the Aug. 7 second anniversary of the bombings of the
U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania, ''may be chosen as
opportunities for further terrorist acts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
