<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Assemblyman renews pledge to fight beach fees  </HEADLINE>
By HANAH CHO
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Despite little support from his fellow
legislators, an assemblyman has renewed his pledge to fight beach
fees.
</P>
<P>
   This time Assemblyman Neil Cohen, D-Union, has an ally in
Philadelphia sports radio personality Angelo Cataldi, who is
challenging beach fees in court.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen has been trying since 1997 to make all New Jersey beaches
free and raise public awareness of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ''Even when the Soviet people were not free, their beaches
were,'' Cohen said at a news conference Tuesday. ''Access to the
shore area, whether it's the Bahamas, California, Cape Cod, North
Carolina, or South Carolina ... are free of charge.''
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly's Environment Committee is reviewing two bills
sponsored by Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   One would prohibit towns from charging fees to beachgoers and
establish a $20 million fund for beach maintenance. The second
measure would create a 20-member commission to study beach access
issues.
</P>
<P>
   On the judicial end, WIP's Cataldi is fighting a ticket he
received last August on a beach in Avalon. He was with his
daughter, but only had one beach badge.
</P>
<P>
   The case is pending an appeal. Cataldi said he plans to
challenge the constitutionality of the state's beach fee system.
</P>
<P>
   If Cataldi is found guilty, he could be fined between $55 and
$1,000 or sentenced to three months in jail.
</P>
<P>
   ''They may not love me down there, but the fact of the matter is
that beach tags are wrong,'' said Cataldi, of Mount Laurel, who
recently bought a summer house in Sea Isle City.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen also has proposed two constitutional amendments that have
garnered little support from other legislators.
</P>
<P>
   One would grant New Jersey residents free access to public
beaches, and the other would authorize a lottery system to fund the
cost of beach maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   Although proposed measures over beach fees have languished in
the lower house, Cohen believes the issue will reach a resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's something that will take a long time,'' Cohen
said. ''Ultimately, if this cannot be resolved by legislation, I
think there will be a court challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ''With the right case, beach access is free. They are running
the risk by ignoring reasonable legislative actions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1930s, when the state Legislature passed a law
allowing towns to charge beach fees, a growing number of resort
communities have chosen to charge visitors for the pleasure of
playing in the surf.
</P>
<P>
   Local officials say the fees go toward specific beach expenses
such as police protection, trash removal and equipment maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all the state's beach towns charge between $2 and $6 for
daily beach badges. Atlantic City and the Wildwoods charge no
admission, while Seaside Heights and Sea Isle City offer free
access on certain weekdays.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
