<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge rejects sheriff bid for restraining order on new law  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) - A federal judge on Tuesday rejected a
temporary restraining order seeking to block provisions of a new
state law that could lead to abolishment of the county sheriff
system.
</P>
<P>
   The state's eight high sheriffs argued in a lawsuit filed Monday
that the law passed in May by the General Assembly violates their
constitutional right to freedom of expression.
</P>
<P>
   The law prohibits county sheriffs from soliciting contributions
from deputies, their immediate families or business associates, and
also takes away sheriff's power to hire and fire. The law puts the
future of the sheriff system in the hands of voters during a
November referendum.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing arguments behind closed doors and then in open
court Tuesday, U.S. District Judge Alan H. Nevas rejected the
sheriffs' request for a temporary restraining order.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said cases dating back to 1876 show that Congress and
other governmental bodies prohibited government employees from
soliciting contributions for political purposes.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the new law does prohibit the sheriffs from talking
about the referendum with voters.
</P>
<P>
   ''They can speak out as much as they like about this issue,''
Nevas said.
</P>
<P>
   But a lawyer for the sheriffs, George Springer Jr., called the
ruling ''devastating'' and said the law effectively stops the
sheriffs from speaking at all on the issue because their remarks
could indirectly result in contributions that could later be called
a violation of the law. He said the statute also does not define
what a business associate is, so sheriffs do not know who exactly
they are precluded from soliciting for donations.
</P>
<P>
   ''The statute does not define what they can and cannot do, who
they can say it to and when they can say it,'' Springer said.
''It's a grotesque infringement of free speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers who pushed for the law have criticized the sheriffs,
saying they have a history of strong-arming their deputies for
political contributions. The sheriffs vehemently deny those
allegations.
</P>
<P>
   ''Strong-arm? You can ask any of my deputies. I don't ask them
to ... do anything. They have their own minds in my county,'' said
Charles M. Valentino Sr., the high sheriff of Fairfield County.
</P>
<P>
   ''They've set it up so that we cannot engage in any meaningful
dialogue,'' said Walter J. Kupchunos Jr., the Hartford County high
sheriff. ''What they're basically saying is we're going to tie both
hands behind your back, we're going to tie up your legs, we're
going to put tape over your mouth, and go speak on the
referendum.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Richard Blumenthal said the judge's ruling
''reaffirms the importance of letting the voters decide whether to
reform the sheriff system without undue influence.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The high sheriffs remain free to advocate for defeat of the
proposal at the polls because the statute simply and solely
prohibits their soliciting money from their staff, which in no way
violates their constitutional rights,'' Blumenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriffs are also seeking a preliminary injunction. A
hearing is scheduled for July 11 in U.S. District Court.
</P>
<P>
   If voters approve the ballot issue, the office of county sheriff
would be terminated and most of its duties would move to the
Judicial Branch.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff system is under investigation by Blumenthal. Two
sheriffs are facing criminal charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-27-00 1739 </TRAILER>
