<HEADLINE> Kimeses sentenced to life in prison for murder of elderly widow  </HEADLINE>
By SAMUEL MAULL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A scam artist and her son were sentenced on
Tuesday to more than 120 years to life in prison after being
convicted of the murder of an 82-year-old millionaire widow whose
body was never found.
</P>
<P>
   State Supreme Court Justice Rena Uviller said the sentence for
Sante Kimes, 65, is ''just desserts'' for a life spent preying on
the ''weak,'' and is mitigated only by the fact that she will not
live to serve all of it.
</P>
<P>
   The sentence for Kenneth Kimes, 25, who first seemed to be ''a
vacuous dupe of his mother but is now a remorseless criminal,'' is
meant for his ''permanent incapacitation'' so that he is never free
again, Uviller said.
</P>
<P>
   The Kimeses, Las Vegas residents who recall the mother and son
played by Anjelica Huston and John Cusack in the film, ''The
Grifters,'' were convicted May 18 on some 60 counts, including the
murder of Irene Silverman, 82.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Los Angeles District Attorney Gil Garcetti
said his office will begin extradition proceedings to bring the
Kimeses to California to stand trial for murder this week. The
Kimeses have been indicted in Los Angeles for the 1998 murder of a
business associate of theirs, David Kazdin, 63.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors - there were four in the New York case - said the
Kimeses killed Silverman, a former Radio City Music Hall dancer and
widow of a real estate millionaire, in their scheme to steal her $7
million six-story home.
</P>
<P>
   The Kimeses, who had rented a first-floor apartment in
Silverman's Beaux Arts mansion on Manhattan's East 65th Street on
June 14, were arrested on July 5, 1998, on unrelated charges
involving an allegedly stolen car, the last day Silverman was seen
alive.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant District Attorney John Carter said that at some point
that morning, with the house empty, Kenneth Kimes had pulled
Silverman into his apartment and strangled her.
</P>
<P>
   ''What terror she have felt,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor said the Kimeses ''packaged'' Silverman in
garbage bags, put her into the trunk of their green 1997 Lincoln
Town Car, and between 11:30 a.m. and 2:30 p.m. disposed of her body
in a place only they know.
</P>
<P>
   When police searched the Kimeses' car and luggage, they found
guns, a knockout liquid, plastic handcuffs, fright masks, syringes,
tapes of Silverman's telephone conversations and a fake deed to
Silverman's home.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the Kimeses' crimes and Mrs. Kimes' convictions, Carter
said the two are suspected in other murders, called them serial
killers and told the court, ''She'll never change.''
</P>
<P>
   ''She's almost 66 years old,'' Carter said. ''She will continue
to cheat and steal, and kill anyone who stands between her and her
goals. She is so incorrigible she should get the maximum
sentence.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge called the Kimeses ''the most degenerate defendants to
ever appear in this courtroom,'' and said Mrs. Kimes' continuing
protestations of innocence were as fake as any bad check she had
ever passed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It comes as no surprise that she is one of the rare people in
this century to be convicted of slavery,'' Uviller said. The judge
was referring to Mrs. Kimes' 1986 conviction for illegally
transporting and keeping young Mexican girls as prisoners and
household slaves in her Las Vegas home.
</P>
<P>
   The Kimeses made a mistake by overrating their own cleverness,
Uviller said. Referring to Mrs. Kimes' notebook diaries that jurors
said helped them vote to convict, the judge said she could think of
nothing as ''staggeringly stupid'' as Mrs. Kimes writing out the
steps of a crime she was planning.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kimes, given the chance to speak, told Uviller that she was
rich, that she was a friend of Silvermanf03029k588
u f BC-RussellIndexes     06-27 0069
BC-Russell Indexes,0067
</P>
