<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Little Progress In Kurdsish S.East  </HEADLINE>
By SELCAN HACAOGLU
<TEXT>
<P>
   DIYARBAKIR, Turkey (AP) -- Youths crowd internet cafes and
couples take romantic, late-night walks in the streets of the
overwhelmingly Kurdish city of Diyarbakir, once the site of
gunbattles and firebombings.
</P>
<P>
   Since Kurdish rebel leader Abdullah Ocalan ordered a cease-fire
from his prison cell, there has been little fighting in the largely
Kurdish areas of southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   But as Turkey marks the first anniversary of a court's June 29
death sentence against Ocalan, there also has been little
reconciliation between Kurds who demand increased cultural freedoms
and a government that fears Kurdish nationalism could lead to the
collapse of a unified state.
</P>
<P>
   After defeating the rebels on the battlefield and later
abducting their leader from Kenya, where he had fled, the Turkish
government seems satisfied with the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think this nationalist government would make any
concessions to the Kurds at this stage,'' said Huseyin Bagci, a
political analyst at Ankara's Middle Eastern Technical University.
</P>
<P>
   On the streets of Diyarbakir there is anger, but also exhaustion
from the war which left hundreds of thousands of Kurds homeless.
Some 37,000 people died in 15 years of fighting, most of them
Kurdish civilians.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am fed up with the tension,'' said Faruk Tuzger, a
22-year-old welder. ''Neither the government nor the politicians
are doing anything for us at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Pro-Kurdish politicians swept to power in local elections last
year, but the central government has slowed down funding to the
municipalities, leaving the mayors largely powerless.
</P>
<P>
   Several leading members of the pro-Kurdish People's Democracy
Party or HADEP, have been detained by police, some for days.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey's tough stand and its refusal to grant Kurds cultural
freedoms, such as the right to teach or broadcast in Kurdish, is
not only likely to keep tensions high in the region, but could also
frustrate the country's efforts to gain membership in the European
Union. The group has demanded that Turkey improve its human rights
record before it can become a full member.
</P>
<P>
   ''Instead of giving minority status to citizens of Kurdish
origin, the implementation of all rights given to Turkish citizens
is enough,'' Turkey's all powerful National Security Council said
last month.
</P>
<P>
   Although Turkey grants Jews, Armenians and Greeks minority
rights, it considers all Muslims living within the country to be
Turks.
</P>
<P>
   ''We do not consider Kurds a separate entity. After so many
generations it is difficult to differentiate a Turk from a Kurd,''
Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit said during a visit to Norway early
June.
</P>
<P>
   Ocalan's rebels, who have demanded autonomy in the southeast,
now say they will try to press for increased cultural rights using
political means, a move that Turkey has already rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those who have given up hopes for armed separatism will not
achieve political separatism,'' Ecevit said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ocalan waits on death row in an island prison.
</P>
<P>
   Parliament must approve his execution before he can be hanged,
but legislators say they will wait for the results of an appeal to
the European Court of Human Rights before taking any action. The
appeal could take at least another year.
</P>
<P>
   And while the politics remain deadlocked, signs of tensions lurk
beneath the surface.
</P>
<P>
   When a Kurdish businessman greeted Ecevit in Kurdish during a
recent visit to Diyarbakir, the premier smiled bitterly.
</P>
<P>
   ''Kurdish is my mother tongue,'' said Ramazan Ore, a fruit
merchant who was selling black mulberries. ''I want it to be
freed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
