<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brother of police officer convicted of bank robbery accused of perjury </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - The brother of a police officer convicted of
the gunpoint holdup of a bank in his own district was indicted
Tuesday on charges he lied during the officer's trial and to a
grand jury about $3,500 found at his residence.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony by Michael Spinello was offered to bolster Officer
Robert Spinello's alibi that the money was the remainder of casino
winnings.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors maintained that the money found by investigators
just hours after the robbery was the exact amount - in identical
denominations - as that taken from the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Spinello, 27, of San Francisco, lived in an Edison
condominium owned by his brother at the time of the robbery, Jan.
13, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   He testified to a federal grand jury in September 1999, and
during the trial in May that he put the $3,500 in an end table, and
that the money was from the officer's gambling winnings.
</P>
<P>
   The cash was in the same denominations as the money taken from
the bank, trial testimony revealed: $1,000 in $100 bills, $1,000 in
$50 bills, $1,000 in $20 bills, and $500 in $10 bills.
</P>
<P>
   The defense said the money was from Caesars in Atlantic City,
but prosecutor's called a casino manager who testified winnings
like that would not be paid with $20 bills and $10 bills, U.S.
Attorney Robert J. Cleary said.
</P>
<P>
   Cleary, the ranking federal law officer in the state, tried the
case. He maintained that Spinello turned to robbery amid
desperation over debts.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Spinello was not arrested. He is to enter a plea before
a federal judge here within two weeks. That arraignment has not yet
been scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   He faces four counts of perjury, each of which carry up to five
years in prison and a $250,000 fine, although the actual penalties
would be far less, under federal guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, Kevin H. Marino, said he could not comment since he
had not yet seen the indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Spinello was fired and placed in federal custody after
his May 17 conviction, awaiting sentencing Sept. 6 by U.S. District
Judge Joseph A. Greenaway Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Spinello, 32, of Brick, Ocean County, did not testify during the
nine-day trial. His lawyer told the jury that the 11-year officer
was the victim of ''an unfortunate series of coincidences,''
including mistaken identity.
</P>
<P>
   He was found guilty on all three charges he faced - bank
robbery, armed bank robbery and using a gun during a crime -
following about six hours of deliberations over two days.
</P>
<P>
   The most serious charge, armed bank robbery, carries up to 25
years in prison, although under sentencing guidelines, the actual
term would be about four years. Combined with a five-year mandatory
consecutive term on the gun charge, he faces about nine years
without parole.
</P>
<P>
   Spinello was arrested shortly after he reported to work Jan. 13,
1999, about an hour after a man not wearing a mask showed a teller
at the First Savings Bank in Edison a revolver and fled with
$3,500.
</P>
<P>
   His trial lawyer, Lawrence S. Lustberg, did not immediately
return a call seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: U.S. Attorney's Office news release:
http://www.njusao.org/break.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
