<HEADLINE> Cigarette companies win state's first tobacco-liability trial  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - A Brooklyn jury sided with Big Tobacco on
Tuesday, finding that R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. and other cigarette
makers are not liable for a smoker's lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The six-member jury voted 5-1 in favor of the defendants to
conclude the state's first tobacco-liability trial. Similar legal
battles have been fought in at least a half dozen other states.
</P>
<P>
   The two-month trial pitted Clyde Anderson, 56, a laborer with
lung cancer, against five cigarette producers. In a lawsuit,
Anderson said he mainly smoked R.J. Reynolds' Salems for 33 years
before being diagnosed in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiff alleged that before 1969 - when Congress made
cigarette makers put warning labels on their product - the
defendants suppressed information about the dangers of smoking. His
suit also claimed that after 1969 the industry should have produced
safer cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Kaczynski, an attorney for R.J. Reynolds, said the
verdict shows the jury believed defense arguments that Anderson was
aware of the health risks - and chose to smoke anyway. The defense
has also pointed out that he had been exposed to toxic substances
as part of his work.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's attorney, Leonard Finz, did not immediately return a
call for comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
