<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Down 39; Nasdaq Falls 53  </HEADLINE>
By EILEEN GLANTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Investors lost their nerve on the eve of the
Federal Reserve's decision on interest rates, sending key stock
indexes lower Tuesday in a late-afternoon selloff.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks had been modestly higher for most of the session as
investors speculated that the Fed will leave interest rates
unchanged Wednesday. But investors remained uncertain and restless,
shifting money from sector to sector without much conviction about
the underlying strength of the market.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, stocks slipped.
</P>
<P>
   ''Fear of higher interest rates is putting some pressure on the
market and causing it to be very, very selective,'' said Mark T.
Minervini, president of Quantech Research Group in New York. ''We
want the market to be working on all cylinders and right now that's
not the case.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 38.53 points to close at
10,504.46.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index was down 4.76 at 1,450.55, and the Nasdaq composite index
was down 53.16 at 3,858.96.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said investors were demonstrating some cautious
optimism, evidenced by the fact that more stocks were rising than
falling. On the New York Stock Exchange, advancing issues
outnumbered decliners by a 4-to-3 margin.
</P>
<P>
   Most investors kept their eyes on Washington, where Fed
policy-makers gathered Tuesday to begin discussing interest rates.
Central bankers were scheduled to announce their decision Wednesday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has raised short-term rates six times in the past year,
but many economists expect the central bank to stand pat this week
because the economy has shown signs of slowing from its former
breakneck pace.
</P>
<P>
   ''The interest rate increases by the Fed are starting to bite,''
said Joseph T. Keating, chief investment officer at the Kent Funds
in Grand Rapids, Mich. ''But the economy isn't falling apart. We'll
still have growth -- just at a slower pace.''
</P>
<P>
   A muted report on consumer confidence provided the latest sign
that the Fed's long course of rate increases may be slowing the
economy enough to keep inflation at bay. The Conference Board said
its Consumer Confidence Index fell to 138.8 in June from a revised
144.7 in May as higher rates and soaring gas prices pressured the
economy.
</P>
<P>
   As the Fed tightened credit to cool growth to a more sustainable
pace, investors have started shifting money from sector to sector
as they debated which stocks will perform best in a slowing
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, drug stocks and consumer goods companies were leading
the market higher. Johnson &AMP; Johnson rose $2.375 to $97.875 and 3M
rose $1.375 to $86.875.
</P>
<P>
   Yet those groups were merely the sectors du jour, Minervini
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We haven't seen any sign that we've established leadership,''
he said. ''There's nothing you can sink your teeth into.''
</P>
<P>
   IBM fell $4.656 to $109.75 after a Merrill Lynch analyst said he
expects second-quarter revenue to be ''mediocre'' compared with the
year-ago quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Also, semiconductor stocks, among the best performers in recent
weeks, fell as investors took profits. JDS Uniphase fell $6.625 to
$119 and Rambus fell $8.734 to $108.641.
</P>
<P>
   Trading activity was quiet, but not as anemic as some analysts
had expected on the day ahead of the Fed's decision. NYSE composite
volume came to 1.25 billion shares, compared with 1.08 billion on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''People are starting to put some money back to work,'' Keating
said. ''A good deal of cash built up on the sidelines while volume
tapered off in the past couple of months.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts noted that some buying and selling was due to
end-of-the-quarter reshuffling of portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 8.28 to 508.08.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 2.1 percent.
Germany's DAX index rose 0.3 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 fell 0.5
percent, and France's CAC-40 fell 0.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
