<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FDA Meets On Lotronex Bowel Drug  </HEADLINE>
By LAURAN NEERGAARD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sixteen women suffered serious intestinal side
effects -- some requiring surgery -- after using a treatment for
irritable bowel syndrome that has been on the market for only four
months, federal health officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday's unprecedented public debate about the safety of
Lotronex, a long-awaited treatment, signals the Food and Drug
Administration's concern goes far beyond this one medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Shaken by a spate of drugs banned in part because doctors
disregarded or never even read safety warnings, the FDA has begun a
new initiative to swiftly counter side effects of newly approved
drugs -- especially when the risk may be caused by improper
prescribing.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some of Lotronex's side effects appear to have been
caused because doctors gave the drug to women who shouldn't have
taken it.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the FDA often has assumed that putting safety
warnings in the fine print of a drug's label was enough unless
large numbers of patients were injured or someone died.
</P>
<P>
   No more, declared Dr. Florence Houn, FDA's chief of
gastrointestinal drugs.
</P>
<P>
   In a surprising move, the FDA convened its scientific advisers
to debate Lotronex's risks even though just a handful of some
100,000 users have reported serious side effects.
</P>
<P>
   Critics might ask ''isn't the government jumping the gun?'' Houn
acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   But ''it's in everyone's interest'' to address risks early, she
added. ''We need to create a new culture about safe drug use.''
</P>
<P>
   Glaxo Wellcome Inc.'s Lotronex is the first new therapy in
decades for irritable bowel syndrome, or IBS. The mysterious
intestinal disorder affects up to 15 percent of the U.S.
population, mostly women.
</P>
<P>
   IBS involves chronic or recurrent abdominal pain, the sudden and
urgent need to go to the bathroom, and either frequent diarrhea or
constipation or both.
</P>
<P>
   Lotronex is only for women with diarrhea-predominant IBS,
offering modest relief of their illness. It does not work for men.
And it is not supposed to be used by constipated women, because it
can worsen that symptom.
</P>
<P>
   Since the drug's approval on Feb. 9, seven users developed
serious constipation, six so severe they were hospitalized. Three
required surgery, including one woman who had her entire colon
removed. Some had been prescribed Lotronex even though they had a
history of constipation problems.
</P>
<P>
   In premarket testing of Lotronex, 27 percent of users suffered
constipation, but none considered truly serious.
</P>
<P>
   Also, 13 Lotronex users have suffered ischemic colitis, a
potentially life-threatening inflammation of the large intestine.
Four cases occurred during premarket testing, and an additional
nine have occurred since February. So far, patients have recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Glaxo insisted Lotronex is a big help when properly prescribed,
and said it's not nearly risky enough to warrant bearing FDA's
strongest safety warning. Instead, Glaxo plans a special campaign
to ensure Americans and their doctors know how to use Lotronex
safely.
</P>
<P>
   Among the plans are physician education and patient leaflets
explaining side effects and clearly outlining who should avoid the
drug.
</P>
<P>
   But a drug maker can only do so much, cautioned Glaxo chief
medical officer Richard Kent.
</P>
<P>
   ''We cannot sit in the physician's office with a patient and say
... you are a sloppy, uncaring physician'' who didn't warn about
side effects or gave Lotronex to the wrong woman, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA's scientific advisers didn't vote Tuesday on what safety
steps Glaxo should take, but called clearly worded warnings made
directly to patients as imperative as educating doctors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-27-00 1803 </TRAILER>
