<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Claritin Patent Extension Opposed  </HEADLINE>
By FREDERIC J. FROMMER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A bipartisan group of lawmakers renewed
efforts Tuesday to block a patent extension for the allergy drug
Claritin, fearing that supporters will try to add the provision to
one of the spending bills now moving through Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ''People are sick and tired of this kind of wheeling and
dealing,'' said Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn. ''Who in the world are
we representing? The pharmaceutical companies that are making
obscene profits off the misery, illness and sickness of people? Or
are we representing the people back in our states?''
</P>
<P>
   Claritin now sells for up to $2.66 per tablet, a price so high
some health insurance companies have stopped paying for it. The
expiration of the patent would allow cheaper, generic versions of
the drug to be developed and sold.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Schering-Plough, which makes Claritin, has sought
legislation that would allow it to seek a three-year extension of
its patent, scheduled to expire in 2002. Supporters of the
provision have tried to add it to one of the must-pass spending
bills.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Judiciary Chairman Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, a supporter of
the extension, acknowledged that a draft with his name on it had
been circulated on Capitol Hill. But he said his staff had drafted
the provision without his knowledge or instruction.
</P>
<P>
   ''If someone is attempting to attach such legislation to an
appropriations bill, it is not me,'' said Hatch, who made use of
Schering-Plough's private jet during his presidential campaign last
year.
</P>
<P>
   The issue grew out of a 1984 bill, when Congress extended the
patents of future drugs by five years in recognition of the lengthy
approval process by the Food and Drug Administration. Drugs already
being reviewed by the FDA, like Claritin, got two-year extensions.
Because Claritin wasn't approved for another nine years,
Schering-Plough has argued that it should be allowed to seek an
additional three-year extension of its patent.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a matter of Schering-Plough asking that they be given
an opportunity to have their day in court to prove they should be
treated like other drug companies who were granted a five-year
patent extension, instead of a two-year extension,'' said Linda
Daschle, a Schering-Plough lobbyist.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle is married to Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle of
South Dakota. To avoid any conflict, she is lobbying only the
House, not the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Another senator opposing the extension, Republican Jim Jeffords
of Vermont, said drug companies can't argue they don't want any
government interference, and then ask the government to extend
their patents.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can't have it both ways,'' said Jeffords, who chairs the
Senate Health Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The group of lawmakers also criticized Sen. Judd Gregg, R-N.H.,
for inserting a provision into an agriculture spending bill to help
Columbia University -- his alma mater -- win a patent extension on a
process for making some widely sold biotechnology drugs. The
patent, which nets Columbia up to $100 million a year in royalties
from companies using the procedure, is set to expire in August.
</P>
<P>
   ''These provisions are simply a giveaway by Congress to
patent-holders who don't deserve them,'' said Sen. Edward M.
Kennedy, D-Mass.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-27-00 1805 </TRAILER>
