<HEADLINE> House Votes On Women's Violence Act  </HEADLINE>
By JESSE J. HOLLAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House Judiciary Committee has voted to
reauthorize the Violence Against Women Act but rejected efforts to
overturn the Supreme Court decision banning rape victims from suing
in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Democrats pushed for the amendment to the domestic
violence law Tuesday, which in part renews funding for domestic
violence programs established in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   But the Supreme Court last month struck down the part of the law
allowing rape victims to sue their attackers in federal court.
States, not Congress, should provide such help for victims of
violence, the court said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, led by ranking Democrat Rep. John Conyers of
Michigan, say rape victims deserve that right. ''There is a great
need to repair what the Supreme Court has torn asunder,'' said Rep.
Sheila Jackson-Lee, D-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   However, each attempt to add it back into the law was blocked by
Rep. Bill McCullom, R-Fla., who had it ruled non-germane to the
bill. In addition, ''it is highly improbable what you have drafted
is constitutional,'' said McCullom, chairman of the Judiciary crime
subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Conyers even tried to get through an amendment to allow
unlimited authority for those victims to sue in state court in its
place, but McCullom defeated it on a technical maneuver as well.
''It did not mean I was opposed to the concepts,'' McCullom said
later, ''they were just not germane to the bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Before passing the bill, the committee did add amendments to
create a task force to coordinate domestic violence research,
target funds for disabled women, have the Justice Department create
a national standard for rape kits and genetic sampling and adding
domestic violence records to electronic records checked for gun
purchases.
</P>
<P>
   The full House will consider the bill next. A similar bill could
be considered in the Senate Judiciary Committee as early as this
week.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department says the rate at which women were
attacked by ''intimate partners'' -- current or former spouses,
boyfriends, girlfriends or partners -- dropped 21 percent during the
mid-1990s. Attorney General Janet Reno and the sponsors of the 1994
legislation credited VAWA for the decrease.
------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: House Judiciary Committee:
http://www.house.gov/judiciary
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
