<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chain-reaction crash triggers questions about police pursuit  </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) - The city's black leaders, mindful of the
death of a young man by East Haven police three years ago, are
questioning the Hamden police department's role in a chain-reaction
crash that injured 15 people.
</P>
<P>
   Some witnesses to Monday evening's chaotic crash report that the
Hamden police were chasing a suspect in a sport utility vehicle
down Dixwell Avenue, a mostly residential street in a main
thoroughfare between Hamden and New Haven.
</P>
<P>
   Hamden Police Chief Robert Nolan said Tuesday he does not
believe there was a high-speed pursuit. Nolan said other witnesses
reported there was no chase.
</P>
<P>
   The State Police Major Crime Squad and the New Haven state's
attorney's office are investigating.
</P>
<P>
   The sport utility vehicle hit eight cars in its wild ride down
the street. Fifteen people, including four children and the
suspect, were injured and sent to area hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Anderson, 29, of New Haven, was arraigned in Meriden
Superior Court Tuesday on charges of reckless endangerment, evading
responsibility for an accident, operating a car with a suspended
license and failure to obey a stop sign.
</P>
<P>
   Ministers from New Haven and Hamden said they were flooded with
telephone calls and visits from people who witnessed the crashes
and the arrest of Anderson by Hamden police.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Tuesday with political and police leaders
from both municipalities, some ministers questioned the right
Hamden police have to pursue and arrest a suspect in New Haven.
Some said they doubted a white suspect would have been treated the
same way as Anderson, who is black.
</P>
<P>
   ''My question is, 'Would they chase a 27-year-old European for
whatever reason?' and my answer is no, because of the issues that
have been happening in our community,'' said the Rev. W. David Lee,
pastor of Varick Memorial AME Zion Church in New Haven.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan said that pursuing suspects on the basis of race is not
tolerated and that he would fire any officer who engaged in racial
profiling.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Donald Morris of Wayfaring Ministries in Hamden said
the incident reminded him of the death of Malik Jones, a black New
Haven man who was shot and killed in 1997 by a white East Haven
police officer following a pursuit. An investigation found that the
shooting was justified.
</P>
<P>
   Parishioners are looking for answers about why Hamden police
were allowed to pursue and arrest someone in New Haven, Morris
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''People are very angry, very hurt,'' he said. ''It's a blessing
no one was killed.''
</P>
<P>
   New Haven Police Chief Melvin Wearing said it is commonplace for
police from one town to make an arrest in another town for an
incident that occurred in their jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   A high-speed pursuit, however, is a different story, Wearing
said, since pursuits are not permitted in New Haven for minor
offenses. He deferred to the state police investigation to
determine if the Hamden officer was chasing Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   ''The offending car was traveling at a high rate of speed. If
they were pursuing, I don't know,'' Wearing said.
</P>
<P>
   Radio communications showed that Officer Stephen DeGrand was not
engaged in a high-speed pursuit, Nolan said. He said the officer
called headquarters to let them know the suspect was going into New
Haven, so that New Haven police would be notified. Wearing said he
did not know if the notification was made.
</P>
<P>
   DeGrand began following Anderson after police say Anderson
nearly hit DeGrand's cruiser. As DeGrand followed Anderson, a
police received a report of a hit-and-run crash in Hamden,
reportedly involving Anderson's car.
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt Wilson, 36, said he had just parked his car along
Dixwell Avenue in New Haven when he saw a truck flip over in the
road in front of him. It had hit a car, which ran into his car and
caused his car to bump into another car.
</P>
<P>
   The police cruiser came to a stop behind him, Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He didn't have no siren on or nothing,'' said Wilson, who
estimated the speeding sport utility vehicle was going 80 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ''He should have turned that fellow loose and waited for backup.
Somebody could have been killed,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   New Haven emergency medical technician Myron Oliver was called
to help Wilson and others who were injured in the crashes.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was very chaotic - the magnitude of the debris and cars and
the number of injuries,'' Oliver said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
