<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Jews Hurt by Beatification  </HEADLINE>
By FRANCES D'EMILIO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- At a seminar on Pope Pius IX, a woman stood from the
audience and introduced herself: Elena Mortara, great-great-niece
of a Bolognese Jew who was forcibly baptized as a toddler and then
taken from his family to be virtually adopted by the 19th-century
pontiff.
</P>
<P>
   Now Pius IX is due to be beatified Sept. 3, and Elena Mortara
said she hoped that doesn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have been damaged by this,'' she told the seminar Tuesday,
referring to the forced conversion.
</P>
<P>
   Italian Jewish leaders said the beatification -- which advances
Pius on the path to sainthood -- threatens to harm two decades of
efforts by Pope John Paul II to improve Vatican relations with
Jews.
</P>
<P>
   The Mortara case ''is the biggest wound that remains in the
Italian Jewish world .... that still hasn't scarred over'' after
more than 150 years, said Amos Luzzatto, president of the Union of
Italian Jewish Communities. His organization and a historical
society were hosts of the seminar, which examined Pope Pius IX's
legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Edgardo Mortara was baptized secretly when he was 2 years old by
a housemaid worried about his soul when he had a high fever. When
he was 6 he was snatched away from his parents by papal police in
1858 and brought to Rome, where Pius IX took him under his wing.
The boy later entered a seminary and became a priest.
</P>
<P>
   B'nai B'rith International's president, Richard D. Heideman, has
expressed dismay in a letter to the head of the Vatican
congregation that handles the process toward sainthood.
</P>
<P>
   ''From the Jewish perspective, Pius IX was the pope who
countenanced the abduction of a 6-year-old Jewish child and his
conversion -- obviously against the will of this family -- to
Catholicism,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Many Jews are already upset by John Paul's defense of another
Pius, Pius XII, who is a candidate for beatification and who Jews
and others allege didn't use his moral authority enough to save
Jews during the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Yet John Paul has won widespread admiration from Jews for his
efforts at healing centuries-old wounds between Catholics and Jews,
including his groundbreaking trip this year to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Elena Mortara, who recalled that her father used to talk with
Edgardo before the latter's death in 1940, said the Jewish
community is ''embarrassed'' to intervene in the beatification
process, she cannot help but protest her ancestor's forced
conversion.
</P>
<P>
   Italian Jewish leader Luzzatto said the Pius IX beatification
will ''leave in us a bitterness'' that will affect Jewish-Vatican
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Monsignor Carlo Liberati, a Vatican official involved in the
process leading to Pius IX's beatification, said Catholics have the
duty to try to ''send to paradise'' the soul of an unbaptized child
in danger of dying.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I were Pius IX, I would have baptized him too,'' Liberati
said of the Mortara boy. He criticized opponents of the
beatification for what he said was ''using today's mentality to
judge the facts of 150 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Liberati, in a telephone interview, said Edgardo Mortara
deposited testimony on behalf of Pius IX's beatification.
</P>
<P>
   Pius IX's pontificate, from 1846 to 1878, was the longest in
history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
