<HEADLINE> Florio to assist Gore on energy, environment  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - Former Gov. Jim Florio, who lost his bid for
the Democratic nomination for U.S. Senate, will work with Al Gore's
presidential campaign as an adviser on energy and environmental
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Florio said he hopes to help refine and ultimately implement the
energy plan that the vice president unveiled Tuesday in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's proposal, which aims to reduce U.S. reliance on foreign
oil, includes $75 billion in tax incentives over 10 years to
promote fuel-efficient technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign aides to Republican presidential candidate George W.
Bush derided Gore's energy ideas as ''recycled,'' but Florio
praised the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the sort of thing I've been talking about for years,''
Florio said, ''trying to harmonize energy concerns with
environmental concerns with business concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Florio said he spoke last week with President Clinton about how
he can remain involved in politics now that his Senate bid is over.
He was defeated in the June 6 Democratic primary by Jon S. Corzine.
</P>
<P>
   That discussion led to a conversation Tuesday morning with Peter
Knight, a longtime Gore fund-raiser, over how Florio could help the
Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Energy and the environment were two top interests of Florio
during his 15 years in Congress before becoming governor in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote the bill creating the Superfund program to clean up the
nation's worst toxic chemical waste dumps, and he was a member of
the House committee on energy and commerce.
</P>
<P>
   He now teaches energy and environmental policy at Rutgers
University and serves on an advisory board to U.S. Energy Secretary
Bill Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   Florio said many people incorrectly assume that energy
production and environmental preservation are competing goals. Some
steps, like promoting gas-fired plants to replace coal-fired ones,
would boost both economic efficiency and clean air, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Florio said energy is a topic discussed only ''in times of
crisis,'' such as this time of soaring gasoline prices.
</P>
<P>
   He said he envisions his goal as trying ''to keep this alive,
not only through the course of the campaign if gas prices start to
stabilize, but into a new administration.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
