<HEADLINE> Beruit Hails Israel Border Report  </HEADLINE>
By HUSSEIN DAKROUB
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- A Lebanese man was injured by stones
thrown from Israel on Tuesday, and Lebanon welcomed a U.N. report
that said Israel was violating Lebanese territory more than a month
after its troops withdrew.
</P>
<P>
   The 40-year-old man was wounded in the head on the
Lebanese-Israeli border when an Israeli soldier, apparently
responding to Lebanese stone-throwers, hurled some stones back,
Lebanese officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Since Israel withdrew its troops from southern Lebanon on May
24, there have been frequent incidents on the border, with Lebanese
demonstrators taunting Israeli soldiers and pelting them with
stones.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Israeli soldiers opened fire on a Jordanian union
delegation visiting Fatima gate on the border, wounding four
people. An Israeli soldier guarding the border was hit in the head
Sunday by a rock thrown from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanon's U.N. Ambassador Selim Tadmoury sent a letter to U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan, condemning the attack on the
Jordanians as ''an act of provocation.''
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Lebanese President Emile Lahoud said the U.N.
Security Council's acknowledgment that Israel was violating
Lebanese territory ''amounted to an international recognition of
Israel's failure to strictly implement U.N. Resolution 425,''
according to a statement by his office.
</P>
<P>
   Resolution 425, adopted by the Security Council after an Israeli
invasion of southern Lebanon in 1978, called for a complete and
unconditional Israeli troop withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council called Monday night for an immediate end to
the Israeli infringements of Lebanese territory after the U.N.
peacekeeping force in Lebanon reported half a dozen border
violations.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanese Prime Minister Salim Hoss told reporters Tuesday that
the Lebanese cartographers working with U.N. officials had found 14
Israeli infringements.
</P>
<P>
   Lahoud said he hoped the United Nations' efforts would force
''Israel to quickly withdraw to the internationally recognized
border'' with Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   The Lebanese government has refused to deploy troops in southern
Lebanon, where anti-Israel guerrillas are the de facto authority,
until it is satisfied that Israel has completely withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   On June 16, the United Nations said it had verified that Israel
had completely withdrawn from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday, in its first report since the verification, the
peacekeeping force cited violations such as military patrols on
roads that cut into Lebanon and Israeli machine-gun posts on
Lebanese territory.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the first 50 Ukrainian troops of a detachment of 650
arrived at Beirut airport with minesweeping vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   They are to help the 4,500-strong U.N. peacekeeping force in
south Lebanon remove thousands of land mines reportedly planted by
Israeli forces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
