<HEADLINE> Union leaders approve tentative contract  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Leaders of the state's second-largest public
employee union Tuesday approved a four-year contract calling for
pay hikes of three percent in the first two years and 3.5 percent
in the next.
</P>
<P>
   The deal approved by the Executive Board of the Public Employees
Federation now goes to the rank-and-file members for ratification.
Ballots to the union's 54,000 members will go out July 26 and the
votes will be counted Aug. 11.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the pay hikes, the pact calls for a $500 bonus
for full-time employees (prorated for less than full-time); better
dental benefits; increased copay for office visits to $10 from $8;
a decrease to $5 from $8 for generic prescriptions; and an increase
to $15 from $8 for name-brand prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Gov. George E. Pataki agrees to support legislation
enhancing members pension benefits.
</P>
<P>
   PEF represents 54,000 white-collar, mostly public-sector
employees around the state.
</P>
</TEXT>
