<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Appeals court allows Apple Tours' buses back on the road  </HEADLINE>
By SAMUEL MAULL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A state appeals court in Manhattan has ruled
that under certain conditions, New York Apple Tours' familiar red,
double-decker buses can resume sightseeing trips around the city.
</P>
<P>
   A five-judge panel of the Appellate Division on Monday said
buses and drivers can get back to work once a court-appointed
monitor, Ross Sandler, finds they comply with city and state laws
and regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The decision lifts the automatic stay that the state and city
got earlier this month when they appealed a June 14 ruling by State
Supreme Court Justice Phyllis Gangel-Jacob. The judge had ruled
that suspending Apple Tours' bus registrations and tour licenses
without proper hearings raised questions of due process and
fairness.
</P>
<P>
   Hayim Grant, president of Apple Tours, said he hoped to have the
company operating by the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to contact 350 employees to see if they are
available,'' he said. ''I hope they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Apple Tours' most popular ticket costs $40 for two days and
permits the tourist to hop on or off any of the company's buses at
any time at any of 65 stops in Brooklyn and Manhattan, Grant said.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who has said Apple Tours should be put
out of business, said in a statement that he was ''deeply
disappointed that the Appellate Division has disregarded both the
state and city's determination that New York Apple Tours in unfit
to operate safely.
</P>
<P>
   ''The city will continue vigorously to pursue the administrative
hearing, begun last April, seeking to revoke their license and
cease their operation.''
</P>
<P>
   Apple Tours was closed down on May 31 when the city's Department
of Consumer Affairs suspended its license. On the same day, the
state Department of Motor Vehicles suspended the registrations of
the company's 63 tour buses.
</P>
<P>
   In shutting down Apple Tours, state and city officials charged
that the company was operating buses that had hundreds of
violations and using drivers who were in many cases unqualified.
They alleged that the company had ignored the rules for years and
willingly paid fines as a cost of doing business.
</P>
<P>
   The company's closing - to cheers in many neighborhoods - was
spurred by an accident in which one of the tour buses struck and
killed Randolph Walker, a 71-year-old actor, in mid-Manhattan on
May 22.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-27-00 1846 </TRAILER>
