<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000627.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BC-NY--Money Laundering,0305  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Current and former New York City employees were
among 17 defendants charged on Tuesday with money laundering for
allegedly trying to legitimize millions of dollars in cash
generated by narcotics organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Charges were contained in criminal complaints issued by federal
prosecutors in Brooklyn and Manhattan who want to shut down what
they said was a large-scale money laundering organization.
</P>
<P>
   Those charged with crimes that carry potential penalties of up
to 20 years in prison include a New York City building inspector
earning less than $50,000 annually and a New York City lifeguard
who earns less than $35,000.
</P>
<P>
   Former employees of the city include Othniel Simpson, who
allegedly led the organization and fled to Ecuador in January after
other members of the group were charged in Fort Myers, Fla., with
money laundering, prosecutors said in court papers filed in U.S.
District Court in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the organization allegedly tried to hide the criminal
source of their money by depositing cash in banks in denominations
smaller than $10,000, an amount which requires the filing of a
Currency Transaction Report with the Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   After depositing the money in various banks, members of the
organization wired money to entities and individuals throughout the
United States and in Central and South America, prosecutors
alleged.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1999, about $200,000 in narcotics proceeds was
seized from a member of the organization in Fayetteville, N.C.,
according to court papers.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the money laundering organization hired a paralegal
employed at a Brooklyn law firm to file a fictitious claim to
retrieve the money from law enforcement officials, prosecutors
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
