<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Mediates Mideast Dispute  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright sought
Tuesday to bolster Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak's resolve to
make widespread concessions to the Palestinians. The Israeli leader
was under attack from his own Cabinet as offering to give up too
much.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the spectrum, the troubled Barak faced a
renewed rhetorical assault from the Palestinians, who threatened to
set up their own state if Israel does not agree to the one they
want to established on virtually the entire West Bank, Gaza and in
East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for Albright's trip was to narrow differences between
the two sides enough to bring Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat together for a Camp David-style summit, but prospects for a
Washington-area summit did not appear bright.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides remain too far apart even for the most ardent
mediation by President Clinton to bring them into line on
statehood, the future of Jerusalem, refugee claims and the future
of Jews who live on land progressively falling under Arafat's
control.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, President Clinton scheduled a news conference for
Wednesday, his first since March. No agenda was announced.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Barak was losing favor with his own government
partners.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister David Levy, in an interview on Israel
television, said, ''We have made no progress. Israel has offered
the maximum without receiving the minimum of the minimum,'' Levy
said.
</P>
<P>
   The deadline for an agreement is mid-September, and Clinton is
running out of time to claim a legacy as a Middle East peacemaker.
He will be turned out of the White House in January.
</P>
<P>
   Barak is eager to attend a summit meeting, and has signaled in
various ways willingness to live alongside a Palestinian state in
control of far more than the 40 percent of the West Bank and Gaza
already under Palestinian control.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, trying to rally his coalition partners to take the
plunge, called them to an unusual meeting with Dennis B. Ross, the
senior U.S. mediator participating in the session.
</P>
<P>
   American officials were eager to squelch reports that an
American document had been circulated outlining Israel's positions
on land-for-peace, Jerusalem, water, refugees and other knotty
issues.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a U.S. document, it does not accurately reflect U.S.
views, and much of it is in error, a senior U.S. official told The
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Albright is trying to determine if the time is right for a
summit, but at this stage there is no basis for one, said the
official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The report evidently stems from an account given by a Barak
adviser to American Jewish organizations. Some participants opposed
to the prime minister's dovish stance then leaked it in an apparent
effort to undercut him.
</P>
<P>
   Ross's participation in Barak's session with members of the
government coalition in the prime minister's office Tuesday may
have been unprecedented. It underscored the U.S. stake in
concluding a deal while also giving Ross an audience to promote his
views. U.S. Ambassador Martin Indyk was present as well.
</P>
<P>
   Ross also accompanied Albright in a Tuesday night meeting with
Barak, who was assisted in the two-hour meeting by Danny Yaton, his
chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Boucher, the State Department spokesman, called it ''a
thorough and useful discussion of the issues.'' He said Clinton
would decide whether the time is right to convene a summit after
Albright flies home Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   At least two of the six parties in Barak's unwieldy coalition
have said they would pull out if Barak makes far-reaching
concessions that have been leaked to the media in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   That could crimp Barak's ability to make a deal acceptable to
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian negotiator Ahmed Qureia told the Voice of Palestine
Radio a summit could be convened only after Israel carried out an
additional West Bank troop withdrawal and released Palestinian
security prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   The troop pullback was initially due June 23, but the
Palestinians agreed to a U.S. request for a two-week delay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
