<HEADLINE> Blackthorne's wife testifies he never discussed killing ex-wife  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SAN ANTONIO (AP) - The wife of South Texas millionaire Allen
Blackthorne testified Tuesday that her husband is a loving father
who never discussed killing his ex-spouse.
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Blackthorne took the stand in Blackthorne's federal
trial in San Antonio. She said that while her husband disliked
Sheila Bellush, he was not involved in her 1997 shooting and
stabbing death.
</P>
<P>
   ''He didn't like Sheila, and he hated some of the things she
did,'' Maureen Blackthorne said.
</P>
<P>
   She said her husband was a caring father to their two young sons
and was concerned about the welfare of his two daughters with
Bellush.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the 45-year-old businessman testified that he was
innocent of Bellush's murder but admitted he once threatened to
kill her.
</P>
<P>
   Blackthorne denied accusations that he asked a golfing buddy,
Daniel Rocha, during a golf trip to Oregon to find a hit man to
kill his ex-wife.
</P>
<P>
   Bellush was killed Nov. 7, 1997, shortly after moving with her
second husband, Jamie Bellush, and six children to Sarasota, Fla.
Her 2-year-old quadruplets from her second marriage were discovered
unharmed in the house, two of them crawling in their mother's
blood. Jamie Bellush and the children now live in Sussex County,
N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Blackthorne is charged with interstate conspiracy to commit
murder for hire and interstate domestic violence. He faces a
mandatory life sentence if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Blackthorne was the last witness called by defense
attorneys. Jurors will be off Wednesday and convene again Thursday
morning for closing statements.
</P>
<P>
   During daylong testimony Monday, Blackthorne told his lawyer
that he once became so upset after his younger daughter fell out of
a second-story window that he told Bellush he would kill her if
''anything happens to my kids.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple divorced in 1989. Blackthorne said he decided to give
up the custody fight in July 1997 because his older daughter and
pregnant second wife weren't getting along. He surrendered his
parental rights.
</P>
<P>
   But on cross-examination, Assistant U.S. Attorney John Murphy
got Blackthorne to admit that he repeatedly has lied. Blackthorne
did not dispute that he changed his name to hide from a debtor,
that he hid assets during his divorce proceedings and that while he
fought to get his child support payments reduced from $1,250 a
month, he regularly lost that amount gambling on a round of golf.
</P>
<P>
   He said that while his gambling losses to Rocha in 1997 totaled
between $75,000 and $200,000, he has not sent his daughters any
money since their mother was killed. He said his lawyer advised him
to wait until after the trial is over.
</P>
<P>
   Rocha testified earlier in the trial that he contacted a friend,
Sammy Gonzales, who hired his cousin, Jose Luis Del Toro, the
alleged gunman.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gonzales and Rocha are serving prison terms in Florida for
solicitation of murder.
</P>
<P>
   Del Toro, 23, a former high school football star in Uvalde, is
scheduled for trial next month in Florida.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
