<HEADLINE> Senate Rejects Education Amendment  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senate Republicans rejected Democratic
attempts Tuesday to increase education funding and reduce class
sizes.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals were offered in a series of amendments to a
measure that renews education spending for kindergarten through
high school. The package provides roughly $15 billion in federal
K-12 grants to help schools pay for programs ranging from boosting
poor children's grades and test scores to training their teachers.
</P>
<P>
   This year Republicans have proposed increasing the program to
about $20 billion. The education package is part of an overall
spending measure that includes funds for the departments of Labor
and Health and Human Services.
</P>
<P>
   One amendment proposed by Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., rejected
on a 52-47 vote, would have increased Title I funding in the
measure to $10 billion. Title I is an $8.3 billion program to help
10.5 million poor children in 90 percent of the nation's school
districts.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a mandate to . . . give this small, but significant
increase to Title I,'' Wellstone said. ''It is time to stop talking
about this and do something. We have to show that our commitment to
education is more than just for photo ops and bumper stickers.''
</P>
<P>
   Other amendments by Sens. Jeff Bingaman of New Mexico and Patty
Murray of Washington, also Democrats, would have allotted $250
million to increase accountability at failing schools and $1.75
billion to reduce class sizes. Those amendments also failed, by
votes of 50-49 and 55-44 respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill is H.R. 4577.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://thomas.loc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
