<HEADLINE> Italian Inmates Start Fires  </HEADLINE>
By ALESSANDRA RIZZO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- Protesting against prison overcrowding, inmates
across Italy set sheets on fires, pounded on cell bars and waved
signs demanding amnesty for their crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Few injuries were reported during the fourth day of protests,
which stretched from the southern city of Palermo in Sicily to
Trieste in the northeast.
</P>
<P>
   But a convict in the northern city of Bergamo cut a guard on the
arm with a razor, while six guards in Novara, also in the north,
were treated for smoke inhalation from a fire started by prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   In some prisons, inmates dangled signs out windows, demanding
amnesty.
</P>
<P>
   The protests have fueled a political debate over whether to
grant some sort of amnesty to ease overcrowding.
</P>
<P>
   Italy's 217 prisons, built to hold 40,000 inmates, now house
about 54,000.
</P>
<P>
   Senators from the governing center-left coalition were trying to
work out an amnesty proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The government is also looking at hiring more guards or building
new prisons.
</P>
<P>
   An amnesty would eliminate prison time for people convicted of
nonviolent crimes and given relatively short sentences.
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty is especially touchy in Italy because it might affect
those convicted in the huge and politically charged corruption
scandals of the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The right-wing National Alliance, the Northern League and the
Democrats are against it, while Silvio Berlusconi's Forza Italia,
former Christian Democrats and the Greens back it.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling coalition's largest party, the Democratic Left, is
split.
</P>
<P>
   ''The amnesty does not resolve either the problem of the
inmates' rights ... or the security that citizens demand,'' Chamber
Speaker Luciano Violante said. ''It is an illusion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
