<HEADLINE> Mexican Mountain Climber Dies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Mexico's highest mountain claimed its fourth
victim this year -- a climber who fell while scaling the 18,400-foot
Pico de Orizaba, the state news agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Two companions were injured Monday during the climb, which was
complicated by strong winds and icy conditions, Notimex said. It
did not say how the two were hurt.
</P>
<P>
   The three climbers began their ascent Sunday morning from the
south side of the mountain, 200 miles east of Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   The harsh weather conditions prevented rescue workers from
recovering the body immediately.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the frozen bodies of three Russian climbers who had
been missing for several days were found on Orizaba. One of the
climbers appeared to have slipped, and may have caused all three to
fall down a steep incline, the Televisa network reported at the
time.
</P>
</TEXT>
