<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Disabilities Act Said Not Enforced  </HEADLINE>
By D. IAN HOPPER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Ten years after its enactment, the Americans
With Disabilities Act is not being enforced aggressively enough by
federal agencies, a study says.
</P>
<P>
   The National Council on Disability, an independent federal
agency that makes policy recommendations to the president and
Congress, said Tuesday that while agencies follow up on complaints,
they have been ''overly cautious, reactive and lacking any coherent
and unifying national strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   The report cites underfunding, understaffing and the bureaucracy
culture as contributors to the problem, saying that the ''net
impact has been to allow the destructive effects of discrimination
to continue without sufficient challenge in some quarters.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1990 act prohibits discrimination against people with
disabilities and requires that they have access to transportation
and other public accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   Four federal agencies, the Justice Department, Transportation
Department, the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission and the
Federal Communications Commission are primary enforcers of the act.
</P>
<P>
   In those agencies, the report blames lack of leadership for
inconsistencies in enforcement. Just within the Transportation
Department, the report says, six sections have different
interpretations of the law, investigation methods and priorities.
</P>
<P>
   To fix these problems, the council recommends that the Justice
Department take a lead role in ADA implementation across the
federal government, and the other federal agencies should be more
aggressive in enforcing ADA as well as take part in community
outreach and education.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department said it does not agree with the council's
report as a whole. But the department conceded that, even with 30
new positions requested for the fiscal year ending Sept. 30, its
ADA enforcement arm is understaffed.
</P>
<P>
   ''Since the law took effect we have reached hundreds of
settlements improving access across the country and have engaged in
an extensive effort to educate the public about the law,'' the
Justice Department said in a statement. ''And we regret that we do
not have sufficient resources to address every ADA violation that
is brought to our attention.''
</P>
<P>
   The Equal Employment Opportunity Commission, which enforces ADA
against private employers, local governments and others, responded
to the report by citing its successes. The commission reports that
it has obtained more than $300 million in compensation on behalf of
more than 20,000 litigants, as well as nonfinancial benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ''In addition to vigorously enforcing the ADA, the commission
provides education, outreach and technical assistance to the
private sector in order to promote understanding and voluntary
compliance with the act,'' said Paul Steven Miller, EEOC
commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   The National Council on Disability is not alone in wanting more
from the agencies enforcing ADA. The American Institute of
Architects last week called for ''greater clarity and certainty''
from the Justice Department in the act's requirements. The industry
group has been frustrated with conflicting statements from state
and federal government in building codes.
</P>
<P>
   ''Architects have been striving to meet the intent of the ADA
since its adoption 10 years ago, but can never be certain they've
met the requirements unless they get sued,'' said R.K. Stewart, a
member of the AIA's Accessibility Task Force.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: National Council on Disability: http://www.ncd.gov/
</P>
<P>
   American Institute of Architects: http://www.aiaonline.com/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
