<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kosovo Emergency Bill Worked On  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional leaders labored Tuesday to craft
a trimmed-down emergency bill financing U.S. peacekeepers in
Kosovo, Colombia's battle against drug traffickers and recovery
from hurricanes, fires and other domestic disasters.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is going to be the slimmest Christmas tree you've seen
around this place in a long time,'' said Senate Appropriations
Committee Chairman Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, using a Capitol Hill
idiom for a bill laden with gifts for lawmakers' districts.
</P>
<P>
   Though numbers and details were changing by the hour, House
Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., and Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott, R-Miss., discussed a tentative compromise of up to $5.5
billion, said participants speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   House Appropriations Committee Chairman Bill Young, R-Fla.,
however, said he believed the final package could be several
billion dollars larger than that.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Lott and Hastert agreed to try holding the cost to no
more than $12 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But the leaders were willing to pare the price tag in hopes of
speeding congressional approval so the bill could be shipped to
President Clinton by week's end -- when Congress' weeklong July 4
break begins. Aides have said Republicans want to finish the bill
quickly to avoid blame for any problems the Pentagon might face as
it juggles money to pay for U.S. peacekeepers in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a really novel idea. Let's go with real emergencies,''
said Lott.
</P>
<P>
   Lott had criticized earlier, larger versions of the package for
being too costly and containing unnecessary items, which slowed
Senate work on the measure for two months.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, participants said that as part of the final package,
the House and Senate would each get a $100 million kitty for
various lawmakers' home-district projects.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators and aides said that some amendments that would make
controversial policy changes would also be omitted from the final
package.
</P>
<P>
   That included an effort by Schering-Plough Corp. to win an
extension of its patent for Claritin, the popular and profitable
allergy drug. Also left off the bill was language by Sen. Judd
Gregg, R-N.H., aimed at extending a lucrative patent his alma
mater, Columbia University, has on a process its scientists
invented for making some widely sold biotechnology drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The measure could, however, end up with compromise language
struck Tuesday that would lift the four-decade-old U.S. food
embargo against Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Participants said the compromise the leaders were discussing
would include $2.05 billion to repay the Pentagon for the costs of
5,700 American troops serving with the NATO peacekeeping team in
Kosovo; $1.3 billion to help Colombia battle drug traffickers and
their right- and left-wing allies; at least $660 million for
rebuilding from the government-set fires that ravaged Los Alamos,
N.M.; and $250 million to help North Carolina and other states
recover from last September's Hurricane Floyd and other
agricultural problems.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Hastert have both been strong supporters of the aid
for Colombia as a way to combat drug use in the United States.
Colombia supplies most of the cocaine used in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Aides have said that Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., chairman of
the Senate Appropriations Committee's subcommittee that oversees
foreign aid, has been trying to keep the Colombia money out of the
emergency package.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving it in the regular foreign aid bill could increase
leverage on Clinton to sign it, aides say. Lott nevertheless
indicated that in the name of completing the emergency bill
quickly, McConnell seemed ready to let the Colombia money be
included.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton requested $5.2 billion for Kosovo, Colombia and natural
disasters early this year.
</P>
<P>
   The House approved $13 billion in March, mostly by adding extra
money for the Pentagon. Last month, the Senate approved roughly $9
billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
