<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Meets With Armenian Leader  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Links between peace and economic reform in the
Caucasus region highlighted a 35-minute meeting in the Oval Office
Tuesday between President Clinton and Armenian President Robert
Kocharian.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton pledged support for peace in the Nagorno-Karabakh region
of the Caucasus Mountains of southwest Asia. The meeting was a
follow-up to one Clinton had in February with Azerbaijani President
Geidar Aliev.
</P>
<P>
   Armenia has had a cease-fire with Azerbaijan for five years, but
has failed to resolve disputes over independence claims by
Nagorno-Karabakh, which is controlled by Armenia, but is located
within Azerbaijan.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our message to President Kocharian was that the United States
will do its part along with the international community to support
and implement a durable settlement,'' White House spokesman P.J.
Crowley told reporters after the meeting. ''The opportunity is
there if both sides want to pursue peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States is a co-chair with Russia and France of the
Minsk Group, formed by the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe to urge a peaceful resolution to the
conflict. The territorial dispute has cost several thousand lives,
created nearly 1 million refugees and caused severe economic
hardships and disrupted economic and social ties in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives from the three co-chair nations are traveling to
the region late next week, Crowley said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have an interest in seeing the region develop in terms of
building prosperity but part of that comes with preventing or
ending conflict,'' Crowley said. ''That was primarily our message
today -- that there's clearly an opportunity for greater prosperity
for Armenia, but that has to come through a stable situation that
then gives confidence to those who wish to invest in Armenia.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States' primary concern in the region is a planned
pipeline to carry Caspian sea oil, being extracted by U.S. and
European oil companies, across Azerbaijan to the Mediterranean at
Ceyhan, Turkey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
