<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trooper statistics show higher percentage of minority stops on turnpike </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - First-ever statistics for traffic stops by
troopers statewide show a higher percentage of minorities were
pulled over on the New Jersey Turnpike than anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in the Attorney General's office said the statistics
for the first four months of 2000 are preliminary and inconclusive.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, they have yet to finish a study on whether a
higher proportion of blacks and Hispanics use the busy turnpike
than the rest of the state's roads.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics show 38 percent of the motorists stopped by the State
Police barracks covering the turnpike over the four-month period
were black, Hispanic or of another minority group.
</P>
<P>
   However, for units covering the rest of the state, only 22
percent of the motorists stopped were minorities, a figure that
aligns more closely with the state's population. About 13 percent
of the state population is black, 10 percent is Hispanic and 3
percent is Asian, according to census figures.
</P>
<P>
   In cases where the traffic stops resulted in an arrest
statewide, 57 percent of those arrested were minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Officials Tuesday would not say whether they regard this data as
some sort of report card on the progress of reforms promised by the
Whitman administration to snuff out racial profiling by troopers.
</P>
<P>
   Similar data in May showed minority drivers on the turnpike
still faced a higher likelihood of being stopped and of being
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Tuesday's data shows minority traffic stops on the
increase or the decline, Assistant Attorney General Paul Zoubek,
''No one can make that statement because there is not the body of
information of what was going on in prior periods of time.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the higher proportion of minorities stopped on the
turnpike, Zoubek said nothing could be inferred from that result.
</P>
<P>
   ''What is necessary is an appropriate survey done in
consultation with the Department of Justice that reflects what the
population actually is on the turnpike,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rev. Reginald Jackson, executive director of the Black
Ministers Council of New Jersey, said much of that has already been
proved, adding the disparity between minority traffic stops on and
off the turnpike was meaningful.
</P>
<P>
   ''All statistics have some meaning, and so I do think that there
must be some effort at least to determine what that meaning is as
far as the disparity,'' Jackson said. ''There ought to be some
effort made as to why there is that gap and not simply dismiss it
as insignificant.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson noted the statewide figures for minority stops appear
proportionate to the population, adding further question as to what
is happening on the turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is not a surprise, but I guess it does at least raise an
eyebrow because it is the first time we have seen the
information,'' he said. ''I think it goes back to this thing of the
turnpike being a drug artery, and it goes back to the mindset of
the former superintendent who said, who taught his men, minorities
were more involved with drugs than others were.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's data were prepared for U.S. District Judge Mary L.
Cooper, who was assigned to enforce a legal settlement of civil
rights charges against the New Jersey State Police.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement was reached between Attorney General John Farmer
and the U.S. Justice Department to forestall a federal civil rights
lawsuit against the state. Cooper with the aide of appointed
monitors will evaluate the state's progress for up to five years.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for three men shot and wounded by troopers on the
turnpike in 1998 have filed a private civil rights lawsuit against
the troopers and the state, and they have said they will use racial
profiling patterns to document their claims.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting spurred a state inquiry into the controversy and
led Farmer's predecessor, former Attorney General Peter Verniero,
to issue a report in April 1999 confirming the existence of racial
profiling - what some activists call the crime of ''driving while
black.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's statistics show that statewide, of the 118,213 people
stopped from Jan. 1 to April 30, 74 percent of them were white, 16
percent black, 6 percent Hispanic and 4 percent Asian or American
Indian.
</P>
<P>
   But of the 27,831 motorists stopped on the turnpike by the four
State Police units covering the turnpike - units organized
collectively as ''Troop D'' - 62 percent of those stopped were
white, 22 percent black, 10 percent Hispanic and 6 percent Asian.
</P>
<P>
   The highest proportion was at the Moorestown barracks, where 45
percent of those stopped were minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide statistics show that black motorists who have been
stopped by troopers are far likelier to be arrested than whites.
However, this was relatively consistent statewide, on or off the
turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 87,500 whites stopped over four months, 1,670 were
arrested for some crime, including 378 for drugs and 15 for
weapons, for an arrest rate of 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Only about a fifth as many blacks were stopped, 18,468, but that
resulted in more arrests, 1,801, with 188 for drugs and 17 for
weapons, for an arrest rate of 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But while the traffic-stop statistics for minorities on the
turnpike are sharply higher than in other units in the state, there
was no great difference in arrests. Statewide, 57 percent of those
arrested were minorities, while on the turnpike it was 61 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-27-00 1956 </TRAILER>
