<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lazio seeks to rally GOP troops at Manhattan fund-raiser  </HEADLINE>
By FRANK ELTMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Long Island congressman Rick Lazio and the man
he replaced in the U.S. Senate race - New York Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani - took a tag-team approach Tuesday night in attacks on
Hillary Rodham Clinton at a Manhattan fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, who spoke to several hundred supporters at the Sheraton
Hotel, repeated themes he has developed in his nearly six-week-old
campaign: He's the native New Yorker with a record of ''legislative
accomplishment'' who is battling not only the first lady, but the
entire Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   ''Talk to your friends, talk to your colleagues and
co-workers,'' the Long Island congressman said with his wife, Pat,
at his side. ''Tell them that we're about fighting for New York.
The future of New York is at stake. We need them. You've got to
think about this: The entire White House is lined up behind the
other side.''
</P>
<P>
   Twice during his speech, Lazio acknowledged the presence of
former U.S. Sen. Alfonse D'Amato in the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ''I promise you, I will work hard, as hard as anyone worked; as
hard as even Senator D'Amato has worked for this job,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, D'Amato said he thinks Lazio has done well in the
early days of his campaign, which was launched May 20 when Giuliani
dropped out citing prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he's done incredibly well, given the relentless
attacks that the first lady's surrogates have been conducting upon
him,'' D'Amato said. ''He just has to let the people meet him and
spend time with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio left the Republican rally early to head back to Washington
to attend to business in the House of Representatives. But before
he left, he introduced Giuliani, who picked up on the anti-Clinton
theme.
</P>
<P>
   ''I mean it really is hard, when you step back from this, to
really completely assess the arrogance of all this; never having
lived here, never having held public office and 'I want to be your
senator.' I mean we have to demand more than that, don't we?'' the
mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani also suggested that the candidates scrap the notion of
debates:
</P>
<P>
   ''I think what they should do is put Rick and Hillary in an
automobile at LaGuardia Airport and figure out who can actually get
home on their own.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
