<HEADLINE> Patrols Ease Border Tensions  </HEADLINE>
By MATT KELLEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Stepped-up patrols along the Arizona-Mexico
border have defused tensions between illegal immigrants and
residents, authorities say. But some Arizonans who came to Capitol
Hill said the situation still is explosive.
</P>
<P>
   ''Both sides are afraid. The residents are afraid of the
migrants and the migrants are afraid of the residents,'' said Sally
Holcomb of Bisbee, Ariz., a restaurateur and mental health program
manager who spoke at a news conference Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions have mounted with reports of armed residents detaining
illegal immigrants in remote Cochise County in southeastern
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Cochise County Sheriff Larry Dever and David Aguilar, the Border
Patrol's top official in the Tuscon, Ariz., regional office, met
Tuesday with Sen. John Kyl, R-Ariz., and assured him the situation
has been overblown.
</P>
<P>
   ''The characterization of conflict along the border as rancher
vigilantism is a real unfortunate and inaccurate characterization
of those conflicts,'' Dever said. ''We have had some extremely
isolated incidents that have led to that characterization.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been only 32 incidents in the past eight months where
citizens have detained suspected illegal immigrants, Aguilar said.
The Border Patrol has nearly tripled its horseback patrols of
Cochise County ranches in the last six months, helping ease
tensions, Aguilar said.
</P>
<P>
   Some immigrant rights activists say the government should arrest
residents who hold illegal immigrants at gunpoint. That amounts to
kidnapping and assault, said lawyers for the Tucson-based group
Coalicion de Derechos Humanos, or Coalition for Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
   ''The government needs to take a strong stance and say, 'This is
illegal and you will be prosecuted if you continue,''' said Isabel
Garcia, a Tuscon lawyer and member of the rights group.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides agree that Border Patrol crackdowns in California and
Texas have driven more immigrants to Arizona. Dever and Garcia
criticized the Border Patrol for not giving enough warning or help.
</P>
<P>
   Kyl said he was seeking congressional approval for $5 million in
emergency funding for Arizona and additional funding to hire 1,000
new border patrol agents, though the House has approved only 430.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia and other critics said that would only further
''militarize'' the border, where motorists are questioned at
checkpoints about their citizenship and destination.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service:
http://www.ins.usdoj.gov/graphics/index.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
