<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panel Declines Abortion Limits Ease  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A House committee refused to ease
international abortion restrictions included in a $13.3 billion
foreign aid bill.
</P>
<P>
   By a 34-26 mostly party-line vote Tuesday, the House
Appropriations Committee rejected a Democrat-led effort to end
limits on U.S. support for international family planning
organizations that advocate abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy is perennial, and in past years it has held up
payment of almost $1 billion in back U.S. dues to the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   ''I regret that we have to have this discussion year after year
after year,'' said Rep. Nita Lowey, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   She sought passage of an amendment to modify the current law to
allow U.S. support of nongovernmental organizations that use their
own, separate money to lobby for changes in abortion laws.
</P>
<P>
   Not challenged was the U.S. law that bans outright the use of
U.S. aid money to perform abortions.
</P>
<P>
   The committee also rejected a proposal by Rep. Sonny Callahan,
R-Ala, chairman of the foreign operations subcommittee, that would
have penalized Israel's proposed sale of a $250 million airborne
early warning system to China.
</P>
<P>
   At $2.8 billion annually, Israel is the largest single recipient
of U.S. foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
   Callahan's proposal already was turned down by his subcommittee.
He indicated he will raise the issue again before the full House.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate version of the foreign aid bill, approved last week
by the full Senate, does not contain any restrictions on the Israel
aid.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional conservatives have protested the pending sale to
China of the advanced airborne radar system, and some have
suggested slashing Israel's aid allowance to protest.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with Israel television, Israel's foreign
minister, David Levy, was asked about such concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ''Israel would never do anything that would endanger the
security of the United States, and therefore we must discuss how
Israel can on the one hand fulfill its minimum commitments and on
the other hand not let the Americans feel their security has been
impaired by Israel,'' Levy said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The House bill does not yet have a number. The Senate foreign
aid bill is S. 2522.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
