<HEADLINE> Vieques Protesters Take on Navy  </HEADLINE>
By LYNNE SLADKY
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIEQUES, Puerto Rico (AP) -- Around midnight they gathered -- a
band of students and independence activists from the main island of
Puerto Rico, armed only with wire cutters and a belief that the
Navy should not be bombing Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   Their mission: to invade the training ground early Tuesday and
impede the first major Navy exercises in the 14 months since
civilian guard David Sanes was killed there by stray bombs, setting
off a furor of protests laced with anti-American sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   From the meeting place at Monte Carmelo overlooking Navy
property, about 60 people set off in three squads, following a few
camouflaged men who knew the terrain and led the way along a dirt
road marked by holes and big jutting rocks. No flashlights
disturbed the Caribbean night. In their dark clothes they were
barely visible to each other.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let's go! Let's go!'' they whispered.
</P>
<P>
   Critics deride the Vieques protesters as unreasonable -- for the
U.S. government has already agreed to phase out use of the Atlantic
Fleet's prime training ground within three years, and for
exploiting the Vieques issue to drum up support for the broader and
far less popular cause of Puerto Rican independence.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters made their way toward the chain link fence
marking the border with Camp Garcia, the Navy bombing range that
occupies the eastern third of Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   After about 15 minutes of walking they froze in their tracks:
helicopters flew overhead, cutting the darkness with search lights
that swept close by. The group hit the ground, lying in the dirt
until the helicopters roared away.
</P>
<P>
   ''Go home, Yankees! This is our land!'' shouted Elba Diaz, a
43-year-old Vieques housewife, casting caution aside.
</P>
<P>
   Below, they could see Navy vehicles crawling along the fence.
And they knew observation posts held lookouts monitoring every
movement with night vision devices as well.
</P>
<P>
   The first group moved downhill to an abandoned house, where they
spent nearly an hour hiding from the searchlights. When it was
finally deemed safe, and no patrols were visible, they scrambled
across some shrubs to the fence, uprooted a section and crawled,
flat down on their backs, through the opening.
</P>
<P>
   There they broke the silence, raised their hands and chanted:
''Vieques, Yes! Navy, No!''
</P>
<P>
   They began moving further into the Navy zone, hoping to reach
the target range of bombing and shelling and hide in the interior.
Another group soon entered, this one cutting the fence with a large
wirecutter to speed entry.
</P>
<P>
   The first group was only in for five minutes before they were
spotted by a patrol car. In an orderly and peaceful procedure, the
protesters held out their arms to be handcuffed and were loaded
onto trucks -- a procedure carried out for some 300 individuals in
recent days.
</P>
<P>
   Interaction was minimal -- beyond a complaint by the detainees
that the officers addressed then in English, not Spanish.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-27-00 2013 </TRAILER>
