<HEADLINE> Cow statue disappears from Queens  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Call it the mystery of the heisted heifer.
</P>
<P>
   One of the 500 fiberglass cows placed around the city as part of
CowParade New York 2000 has been stolen, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The cow - painted with orange, red, white, blue, and green
stripes - disappeared from the Richmond Heights section of Queens.
It was last seen at 11 a.m. on Monday, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The statue weighs 80 pounds, and stands 7 feet long, 4 feet tall
and 3 feet wide.
</P>
<P>
   The organization that sponsored the exhibit, CowParade Holdings,
Inc., offered a $1,000 reward for information leading to the arrest
and conviction of anyone responsible for the theft.
</P>
<P>
   ''The cows are here for everyone to enjoy,'' said company
president Jerome Elbaum. ''Pet them, kiss them, take your picture
with them. But why would anyone want to damage these beautiful cows
which were decorated with such love and creativity by talented
artists, including New York City schoolchildren?''
</P>
