<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Byron Scott to coach Nets, first pick in draft up in the air </HEADLINE>
AP Photo   
Eds: AMs. Retransmitting to fix coding. STANDS for digest item
slugged BC-BKN--Nets Coach.   
 TOM CANAVANAssociated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) - Selecting Byron Scott to coach the
New Jersey Nets turned out to be a no-brainer for Rod Thorn on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Making the decision on the first overall pick in Wednesday's NBA
draft is proving a lot more difficult for the Nets new president.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was looking for someone with a lot of energy,'' Thorn said
after giving Scott his first head coaching job. ''I was looking for
somebody who was a good coach, who knew X's and O's, and I was
looking for a real character-type guy. I think Byron brings all of
that to the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott, 39, was given a multiyear contract to replace Don Casey,
who was fired after the Nets (31-51) missed the playoffs for the
second straight year. Terms were not disclosed, but the deal
reportedly covers three years and is worth $9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Scott's credentials are impressive. A member of three
championship teams with the Los Angeles Lakers, he developed his
coaching skills while playing under two of the league's top
coaches, Pat Riley and Larry Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Scott also walks into a very odd situation. He takes over a team
that has the top pick in a draft that really doesn't have a
can't-miss top pick.
</P>
<P>
   Scott had a definite idea who he wants to take but he didn't say
who it is.
</P>
<P>
   Thorn didn't either because he isn't sure whether the Nets will
use it or trade it, and there have been some interesting deals
offered.
</P>
<P>
   The trading deadline is 2 p.m. Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   If the New Jersey does make the pick, Thorn said the final
choices have come down to forwards Kenyon Martin of Cincinnati,
Stromile Swift of LSU and Darius Miles, the high school phenom out
of East St. Louis, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Martin broke his leg in a postseason tournament but Thorn said
team doctors have said the injury is nothing to prevent the Nets
from selecting him.
</P>
<P>
   ''You want to pick the right one,'' Thorn said. ''Obviously,
Kenyon is more ready, other than his injury, today than the other
two, but you try to project what they're going to be. That's what
gets ticklish. Sometimes guys with great potential realize it and
sometimes they don't.''
</P>
<P>
   There seems to be no doubt in Thorn's mind about Scott, who
spent the last two seasons as an assistant coach with the
Sacramento Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Scott, who thought was he going to get the job of replacing
Larry Bird in Indiana, became a candidate for the Nets' job right
after Thorn left the NBA offices to take over the Nets.
</P>
<P>
   Thorn and Scott met in Chicago earlier this month and then
returned there 10 days ago and spent five hours talking basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Thorn brought a magnetic board which depicts a court and they
discussed game situations, particularly instances where the Nets
lost games in the fourth quarter, and there were a lot of them.
</P>
<P>
   ''During the interview, I was amazed with how astute he was with
the X and O part of it,'' said Thorn, who offered Scott the job
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Scott was ready for the interview. He has kept a notebook of how
he would handle late-game situations for the past six years,
something he started in Indiana while playing for Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had an answer for everything,'' Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott also has no doubt he'll do a good job, noting that NBA
coach of the year Doc Rivers had no head coaching experience when
he left the television booth to take over the Orlando Magic this
past season.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think what Doc had going for him is the same things I have
going for me,'' Scott said. ''I played this game, I understand the
players. I understand what it takes to win. I've been to the
mountaintop.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have achieved unbelievable success in the NBA as a player,''
Scott added. ''So I know what it takes to get to the next level and
I know how to push those buttons. Hopefully, I'll get those guys to
believe in the same things I believe in on both ends of the
court.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott wants the Nets to play an uptempo game, but he admits they
have to play much better defense and rebound a lot better to do
that.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm just looking forward to coming to New Jersey, having some
fun, and getting this team to the top of the Eastern Conference,''
Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott was the shooting guard on the Lakers' championship teams
led by Kareem Abdul-Jabbar and Magic Johnson. He played in the
league from 1983-97 with the Lakers, Pacers and Vancouver
Grizzlies. The former Arizona State guard, was the fourth pick in
the 1983 draft.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
