<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN: Mongolian Drought Causing Havoc  </HEADLINE>
By HARMONIE TOROS
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- A severe drought followed by Mongolia's
worst winter in 30 years has killed millions of livestock, creating
an economic crisis for 500,000 Mongolians, U.N. and Mongolian
officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   More than 2.2 million cows, horses, camels, goats and sheep
starved or froze to death, leaving some areas with decaying
carcasses every 100 yards, said Douglas Gardner, the U.N.
Development Program's regional disaster coordinator in Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
   With one third of Mongolia's 2.4 million people directly
dependent on raising livestock, ''this is not just a crisis of
animals,'' Gardner told a news conference, ''it's a human drama.''
</P>
<P>
   Although less than 10 people are believed to have died as a
result of the disastrous weather, it has affected at least half a
million people.
</P>
<P>
   In a documentary presented at U.N. headquarters Tuesday, a
Mongolian herder said he combed his dead goats and sold the
cashmere to buy wheat and flour after most of his livestock died in
the fierce winter, when temperatures dropped as low as minus 50.
</P>
<P>
   ''But what will happen when we run out of this, I just don't
know,'' said 50-year-old herder Ayuurzan, who uses just one name.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has received $371,000 for emergency relief
aid for Mongolia -- just 10 percent of its initial appeal for $3
million.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the arrival of the summer has also brought new
dangers and fears of more drought in Mongolia, a vast, sparsely
populated Central Asian nation where approximately one-third of the
people still live a nomadic life.
</P>
<P>
   ''With summer coming there is growing danger of the decaying ...
of dead livestock that could contaminate not only the immediate
environment, but also water resources,'' said Jargalsaikhany
Enkhsaikhan, Mongolia's ambassador to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   ''The likelihood of the outbreak of different diseases is quite
high,'' he said. Cholera and other diseases can be transmitted by
contaminated drinking water.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-27-00 2114 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000627.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tuesday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNumber of War Criminals Denied Canadian Entry Grows
<TEXT>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- Canada's war crimes program prevented more accused
war criminals from entering the country and evicted more of them in
1999-2000 than it has in previous years, the government says.
</P>
<P>
   In their annual Report on War Crimes, released Tuesday, the
Justice and Immigration Departments reported that 581 people were
denied entry to Canada and 38 were removed.
</P>
<P>
   The new data come two years after the two departments, along
with the RCMP, received $46.8 million over three years to
investigate and litigate new war crimes cases and improve efforts
abroad to keep suspected war criminals out.
</P>
<P>
   While interested groups say the numbers are encouraging, they
argue the government isn't doing enough to ferret out the last of
the Second World War criminals believed to be still living in
Canada -- and aging quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, the government has pursued only 17 such cases. Of
those, two left the country voluntarily and four were found to have
obtained citizenship by misrepresentation. The rest of the cases
are either continuing or have failed.
</P>
<P>
   ---
July 1 Tax Cuts Fatten Paychecks
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- The average family could enjoy a couple of extra
pizzas -- with additional toppings -- and maybe a beverage to wash it
all down next month, thanks to federal tax cuts that kick in
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Tax reductions announced in the February budget by Finance
Minister Paul Martin take effect July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Finance Department officials say about 90 per cent of Canadians
will feel the effects.
</P>
<P>
   That includes about 15 million taxpayers who will see their
personal income tax levies reduced.
</P>
<P>
   As well, most families will be affected by improvements to the
Canada Child Tax Benefit on top of the income tax cut, officials
added.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the changes, an average family of four with two
incomes totalling $60,000 will save about $38 a month beginning
July 1.
</P>
<P>
   That would rise to about $41.75 a month -- $501 annually -- next
year, the first full year the cuts apply, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Dcotors Release Cost of Smog Study
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Smog will kill about 1,900 Ontario residents this
year and cost the province's economy and health-care system more
than $1 billion, the Ontario Medical Association said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The group that represents the province's doctors is offering the
use of groundbreaking new computer software that will allow medical
officers across Canada and anyone else to quantify the effects of
air pollution according to the specific characteristics of their
regions.
</P>
<P>
   ''The costs of poor air quality are extremely high,'' said Dr.
Ted Boadway, the association's executive director of health policy.
''Air pollution must be reduced. If we can agree on the goals, then
doctors industry, governments and citizens can work together to
bring the human and economic costs of air pollution down
significantly.''
</P>
<P>
   In a report called Illness Costs of Air Pollution, researchers
concluded smog costs Ontario residents more than $1 billion a year
in hospital admissions, emergency room visits and absenteeism from
work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
