<HEADLINE> Torre Ejected for Arguing  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- New York manager Joe Torre was ejected from the
Yankees' game at Detroit on Tuesday for arguing a double-play call
against his team in the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees led 3-1 and had the bases loaded with one out when
Chris Turner hit a hard grounder that was stopped by second baseman
Damion Easley. Easley flipped to shortstop Deivi Cruz for one out,
and Cruz's relay to first was ruled in time by first base umpire
Jeff Kellogg.
</P>
<P>
   Torre came out to argue the call briefly and returned to the
dugout. He returned after apparently looking at a replay, renewing
the argument before he was ejected by Kellogg.
</P>
<P>
   Bench coach Don Zimmer then joined the argument before play
finally resumed.
</P>
<P>
   Replays indicated Turner beat the throw to first. The ejection
was Torre's first since June 12, 1999, at Florida.
</P>
