<HEADLINE> Dipoto Making Progress in Rehab  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN MOSSMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- The skies were darkening, and the Colorado
Rockies, already saddled with 21 games in 20 days before the
All-Star break, were worried that a rainout would worsen that
already overloaded schedule.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no black cloud over the head of Rockies closer
Jerry Dipoto, who frankly couldn't have been happier.
</P>
<P>
   Dipoto, on the disabled list for most of this season with a
bulging disk in his neck, threw Monday for the first time since
having surgery May 3.
</P>
<P>
   Dipoto's workout consisted only of about 60 pitches thrown from
60 feet, but it represented a major step in his recovery. Expected
to miss the remainder of the season following his surgery, Dipoto
is ahead of schedule and now hopes to pitch again before the season
is out.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm ecstatic,'' a beaming Dipoto said. ''I had no pain at all.
My neck felt spectacular. I'll do this every other day and we'll
build up to 150, 180 feet. It's a matter of getting my arm strength
back to where it was. I think my neck has generally healed. My body
strength is good. Everything else is good. It's just a matter of
getting the arm going and of getting back in a pitching rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   ''Not having thrown for two months, it's kind of like I'm coming
out of the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ''The original diagnosis was that I wouldn't pitch again until
next year. So we're well ahead of schedule in that regard. A month
ago I was real down because of the fact I was missing out on a
season where the team was doing so well and I wanted to be a part
of it. Now I'm a little more optimistic that I'll be able to play
again this year. If you're there at the end, boy, you forget a lot
about the five months before.''
</P>
<P>
   Dipoto went to spring training expecting to be the Rockies
closer, a job he held for most of the 1997 and 1998 seasons. When
the disk injury surfaced and intensified, Jose Jimenez slipped into
the role.
</P>
<P>
   Rockies manager Buddy Bell said he was pleased with Dipoto's
limited progress but added, ''We're not going to hurry this thing.
We've got to make sure we do what's right.''
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Tom Probst said team physicians ''have told us that he's
healed very nicely and probably a little bit quicker than they had
thought originally. He has been doing his workouts with Mike Allen,
our physical therapist, and has been progressing very well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
