<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gwynn Needs Up to 3 Months of Rehab  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO (AP) -- San Diego Padres outfielder Tony Gwynn will
need two to three months of rehabilitation after having surgery on
his left knee Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn underwent arthroscopic surgery to remove small pieces of
cartilage in his left knee joint and will be on crutches for about
four weeks, the team said.
</P>
<P>
   Team doctors Dr. Jan Fronek and Dr. Steven Copp performed the
surgery at Green Hospital Scripps Clinic in La Jolla.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn has been bothered by inflammation in the knee off and on
this season, and has had to have it drained seven times since
spring training. When he was on the disabled list earlier this
season he had injections of a substance that stimulates bodily
fluid that lubricates the joint.
</P>
<P>
   He has little cartilage left in the joint after five previous
surgeries.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn, 40, who reached the 3,000 hit mark last season, has
signed with the Padres through the end of the year with an option
for 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-time NL batting champion, who has 3,108 hits in his
19-year career, was hitting .323 with 12 doubles, one homer and 17
RBIs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
