<HEADLINE> Wife Beats Husband in S.C. House  </HEADLINE>
By BRUCE SMITH
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) -- The divorce court and the lawyers have
yet to divide up the property, but voters on Tuesday gave Shirley
Hinson her statehouse seat back.
</P>
<P>
   In a bitter primary race that became entangled with their bitter
divorce, the two-term state representative, defeated her estranged
husband to win the GOP nomination for her suburban district about
20 miles from Charleston.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm thrilled. I couldn't be happier. And I'm glad it's over,''
Shirley Hinson said. ''It says negative campaigning is not what the
people want. I have always run a positive campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Shirley Hinson captured 52 percent of the vote in the runoff for
the Republican nomination. The win is tantamount to election
because Democrats did not offer a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The defeated Hinson said he would do whatever he could to
support his estranged wife.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had many years of a very good marriage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shirley Hinson, a former school board member, said her husband's
aggressive election campaign was all about revenge. But Jimmy
Hinson, a retired school principal, said he was running to improve
education.
</P>
<P>
   The couple's well-known marital difficulties -- which includes
alleged death threats, rumors of infidelity, jail time and a
restraining order -- pushed aside most other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Jimmy Hinson was charged with making a telephone
death threat to another GOP legislator, based on rumors that the
legislator and Shirley Hinson were having an affair. A grand jury
refused to indict Jimmy Hinson, though a private investigator
described nighttime meetings between Shirley Hinson and her fellow
lawmaker.
</P>
<P>
   Both denied they were ever romantically involved.
</P>
<P>
   The Hinsons ran in a three-way primary two weeks ago, neither
getting the more than 50 percent required to avoid a runoff.
Shirley Hinson got 42 percent of the primary vote; her husband got
32 percent. The rest went to a third-place candidate who later
endorsed Jimmy Hinson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
