<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fiji Rebel Accord Deadline Passes  </HEADLINE>
By STEVEN GUTKIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- Defying Fiji hostage-takers, the country's
military rulers said Wednesday they would appoint a civilian
government without consulting further with the gunmen.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels holding Fiji's government hostage have demanded a
presence on the interim government before releasing their
prisoners, who include deposed Prime Minister Mahendra Chaudhry.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came a day after a rebel leader, once an
officer in an elite British anti-terrorism unit, warned that the
captives will die if the army tries to rescue them.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will die with the hostages,'' Maj. Ilisoni Ligairi told The
Associated Press Tuesday in an interview inside the parliamentary
compound where 27 members of the ousted government are being held
captive. ''Blood will be shed'' in any rescue attempt, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many Fijians believe Ligairi is as powerful, or even more so,
than George Speight, the former insurance and timber executive who
has dominated headlines in recent weeks as the gunmen's loquacious
leader.
</P>
<P>
   Ligairi's tough talk came as Fiji's army issued issued an
ultimatum late Tuesday giving Speight 24 hours to agree to sign an
accord which paved the way for the hostages immediate release, and
set out procedures to appoint the new government.
</P>
<P>
   But Speight quickly rejected the military's ultimatum, saying
any attempt to appoint a new government without the rebels' input
''will invite the wrath of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Military spokesman Lt. Col. Filipo Tarakinikini said Wednesday
the deadline had passed without a positive response from the
rebels, and that the army would proceed to name the new government.
</P>
<P>
   He gave no further details, saying the army's position would be
outlined in a news conference later Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Talks broke down between the gunmen and the military at the
weekend after Speight backed down and refused to sign the accord,
despite saying earlier he would do so, and issued new demands.
</P>
<P>
   On May 19, the rebels stormed parliament and took the government
hostage, claiming to be acting on behalf of Fiji's indigenous
majority whose rights had been trampled upon by Chaudhry -- who was
the country's first prime minister of Indian descent.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels released their four remaining female hostages on
Sunday, but instead of easing tensions, the release was accompanied
by a renewed breakdown in talks to free the other 27 hostages.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the rebels' demands to disenfranchise Fiji's Indians
have already been met, including the firing of Chaudhry and the
elimination of the country's 1997 multiracial constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The standoff, now in its sixth week, has pitted Fiji's poor
indigenous majority against its relatively affluent Indian
minority, whose ancestors were brought to Fiji by English
colonialists over a century ago to work in the country's rich sugar
cane fields.
</P>
<P>
   Speight claims to be acting on behalf of indigenous Fijians,
whose rights, the rebels say, were being trampled by Chaudhry. The
rebel raid has sent the economy into a tailspin and raised concern
in the international community that Fiji has descended into racism
and intolerance.
</P>
<P>
   Ligairi, 62, who served for more than two decades in Britain's
elite Special Air Service -- a top commando unit in charge of
hostage rescues -- said his captives will not be released until the
gunmen are assured of a presence in the interim government.
</P>
<P>
   He said the non-Christian hostages, including Chaudhry, a Hindu,
were being given lessons in Christianity because ''what we are
fighting for is a Christian state.''
</P>
<P>
   Ligairi ruled out allowing any Fijians of Indian descent
positions in the interim administration. ''If you really believe in
your teachings,'' he said, ''you can't let any other faiths come in
and run your house.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-27-00 2233 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
