<HEADLINE> Clinton Praises Congressman  </HEADLINE>
By FREDERIC J. FROMMER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton paid tribute to the
environmental accomplishments of Rep. Bruce Vento, a Minnesota
Democrat who is retiring at the end of the year because of lung
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has steered into law more than 300 bills to protect our
natural resources,'' Clinton said Tuesday night at a dinner held in
Vento's honor, which raised more than $500,000 for a scholarship in
the congressman's name to help recruit science teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ''The thing I like even more about Bruce Vento is he cares about
people, especially people without a voice -- the homeless.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that it was appropriate that the dinner was held
the day after scientists announced that they had mapped the human
genetic code. Vento was a science and social studies teacher before
he became a congressman 24 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''Bruce said, 'Well, that's exciting. Now we have to have find a
few science teachers to explain what it means,''' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that Vento had been a friend and trusted adviser
throughout his presidency. ''He never stopped being a teacher,'' he
said. ''Bruce, your influence will never stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Vento, 59, who represents St. Paul, said that one of the first
calls he got after announcing his retirement was from Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday night, Clinton attended an annual conference that
Democratic Rep. Ruben Hinojosa holds for residents of his Texas
district. The event was closed to the press.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also attended a fund-raiser for California state Sen.
Adam Schiff, a Democrat challenging GOP Rep. James Rogan in one of
the most closely watched races in Congress. Schiff's campaign
estimated the event at the Frederick Douglass Museum in Washington
raised $250,000 from about 150 people.
</P>
</TEXT>
