<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mets' Rodriguez Accepts Demotion  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Struggling Mets reliever Rich Rodriguez accepted
a demotion to Triple-A Norfolk on Tuesday and will spend the next
two weeks in the minor leagues.
</P>
<P>
   New York recalled right-hander Eric Cammack from Norfolk to take
Rodriguez's place on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, who signed a $1.5 million, two-year contract with New
York in the offseason, is 0-1 with a 7.67 ERA in 23 appearances. He
has mostly been used in mopup duty, but has struggled in that role.
</P>
<P>
   In his last appearance, Rodriguez entered with one out in the
eighth inning with a 10-3 lead. He allowed five of six batters to
reach, including two RBI singles, before being replaced.
</P>
<P>
   ''This gives him a chance to get some work, get his rhythm back
and a chance to pitch,'' general manager Steve Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, in his 11th season, had the right to refuse the
demotion but chose to take the opportunity. He will be recalled
July 13 after the All-Star game.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Bobby J. Jones recently accepted a 10-day
assignment to Norfolk and returned last week, beating Pittsburgh
8-1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
