<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Envoy Joins Israel Gov't Talks  </HEADLINE>
By RON KAMPEAS
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Backed by U.S. muscle, Prime Minister Ehud
Barak met with his coalition partners on Tuesday to persuade them
to back the far-reaching concessions he believes Israel will have
to make for a permanent peace treaty with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Barak brought Dennis Ross, the top U.S. envoy to the region,
with him to the meeting just hours before the arrival of Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright, who is attempting to convene an
Israeli-U.S.-Palestinian leadership summit to spur the peace
negotiations to a conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Albright is trying to determine if the time is right for a
summit, but at this stage there is no basis for one, a senior U.S.
official told The Associated Press on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said Clinton would
decide whether the time is right to convene a summit after Albright
flies home Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Ross's presence was a rare occurrence at an internal Israeli
political meeting, and one that underscored the U.S. stake in
concluding a deal by the September deadline the sides have set for
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   At least two of the six parties in Barak's unwieldy coalition
have said they would pull out if Barak makes the far-reaching
concessions that have been leaked to the media in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   That could cripple Barak's ability to make peace, and the prime
minister apparently brought Ross to remind his partners of the
interest Israel's closest ally has in a peace deal.
</P>
<P>
   Barak acknowledged he needed the two parties -- the pro-Jewish
settlements National Religious Party and the Russian immigrant
Israel B'Aliya party -- if and when he convenes a summit with the
U.S. and Palestinian leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want them with us the whole way, until a summit,'' he said
after the coalition briefing.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Minister Natan Sharansky, who heads Israel B'Aliya,
would not elaborate on Barak's presentation, except to say that if
Barak goes to a summit in Washington on the terms he outlined on
Tuesday, ''I'm out of the government.''
</P>
<P>
   The Likud opposition wasted no time in mocking Barak for
inviting an ''American Uncle'' as an enforcer.
</P>
<P>
   ''A senior U.S. official comes to a political meeting to help
the prime minister solve a political problem,'' Likud legislator
Danny Naveh told Israel television. ''That crosses a line.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of Jewish settlers demonstrated in Jerusalem against
U.S. interference, gathering outside the hotel where Albright was
staying.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrators held up signs warning, ''Clinton, God will punish
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli radio stations reported that Barak told his coalition
partners that Israel would have to hand back at least 85 percent of
the West Bank, matching what some Palestinians have said is the
minimum required for a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's office immediately denied that numbers were raised at
the meeting. Palestinian officials, speaking off the record, have
said that Barak has in recent days offered 92 percent of the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Barak brought Ross to the meeting just hours ahead of Albright's
arrival in Jerusalem to discuss convening the summit between Barak,
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat is reluctant to agree to a summit, fearing U.S. mediators
will side with Israel on many issues and that he will be pressured
into concessions during a summit.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are not against the summit, but first negotiations should
be able to bridge the gaps so the leaders would only have to deal
with limited issues,'' one of his top advisers, Nabil Abourdeneh,
told The Associated Press. ''We are against going to a summit that
would fail.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak wants the top-level gathering, saying lower-level
negotiators have exhausted their options.
</P>
<P>
   ''The negotiations with the Palestinians have reached a stage in
which the leaders ... have to take difficult decisions,'' Barak's
senior policy adviser, Danny Yatom, told Israel army radio.
</P>
<P>
   While the sides appear close on one of three crucial issues --
borders -- significant differences remain on the other two,
Jerusalem and refugees. Arafat wants nothing less than a capital in
east Jerusalem; Barak is reportedly offering only civil control of
Arab neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The widest differences are over the descendants of Palestinian
refugees created by Israel's independence war in 1948: Palestinians
want at least a symbolic right of return; Israel sees even that as
undermining its legitimacy, and instead proposes international aid
to resettle Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians also want Israel to carry out an additional West
Bank troop withdrawal and release Palestinian security prisoners
before a summit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
