<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexican Candidate Vows To Forge On  </HEADLINE>
By LISA J. ADAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Running a distant third in the polls,
Cuauhtemoc Cardenas angrily rejected an offer Tuesday to join
forces with an opponent, turning down the opposition's last chance
to unite before Sunday's presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   Vicente Fox of the National Action Party, who is running
neck-and-neck with the ruling party's Francisco Labastida in the
polls, made an emotional plea last week for Cardenas to join him in
ending the Institutional Revolutionary Party's 71-year rule.
</P>
<P>
   But Cardenas -- making his third bid for the presidency in what
many see as his last hurrah -- denied in an interview with The
Associated Press that he would even consider throwing his votes to
Fox.
</P>
<P>
   ''If Fox wants an opposition victory, then he should stand
aside, he should go home, go back to his ranch and his businesses,
and get out of politics,'' Cardenas said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, however, told hundreds at a rally Tuesday in the southern
Mexican city of Tapachula in the troubled state of Chiapas that he
is the only one who can topple the ruling party.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the attacks by Cardenas, Fox said: ''Who is
Cuauhtemoc Cardenas? That subject doesn't interest me.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas, meanwhile, claimed his center-left Democratic
Revolution Party ''definitely'' still has a chance to win the
presidential race, despite the fact that almost all polls show him
with less than 20-percent support among voters.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida was favored by 42 percent of likely voters, and Fox by
39 percent, in a poll released Friday by ACNielsen. The poll had a
margin of error of 2.5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas declined to say whether he thought the presidential
campaign had been fair to date. But he pledged that if Sunday's
vote is free of fraud, ''we will accept the results, whatever they
are.''
</P>
<P>
   He warned that ''if the process is not clean, we won't accept
any results at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Talks between Fox and Cardenas on an alliance broke down amid
bickering late last year. While election law bars any formal
alliance at this late date, candidates could still make de-facto
endorsements of each other. One of the smaller-party candidates
already has told his supporters to vote for Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas denied speculation that by focusing his criticism on
Fox instead of Labastida, he is actually paving the way for another
in a string of ruling-party victories stretching back to 1929.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those are more of the slander and lies which you people in the
media spread sometimes,'' he said. ''We had to respond to Fox, and
his lies. We are certain that if Fox wins, the country will go from
bad to worse.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Cardenas focused his fire on Fox, more evidence
emerged that the ruling party, known as the PRI, may be using
government resources to defeat the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   In Villahermosa, capital of the Gulf coast state of Tabasco,
employees of Mexico's state-run oil company said Monday that the
company and union officials were pressuring them to vote for
Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   Pemex workers Jose Luis Rosas Munoz and Gilberto Quintero Reyes
showed reporters forms from the Union of Petroleum Workers in
Mexico that required members to give the number of their voting
credential and vote for Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are obliged to sign these forms,'' Rosas said. ''If we
refuse, we run the risk of administrative officials refusing to
lend us money and give us a line of credit for living expenses.''
</P>
<P>
   The workers also showed reporters an e-mail from the secretary
of management of Pemex Gas that encouraged workers to ''fill out
the form with the names of voters that you have secured.''
</P>
<P>
   The return addresses on the forms were of Pemex offices --
despite a law forbidding use of government installations for
political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Pemex workers in Monterrey, capital of the northern state of
Nuevo Leon, voiced similar concerns Monday, saying company and
union officials had required them to vote for Labastida or risk
losing their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the company denied accusations of vote coercion -- but
did not launch an investigation -- after other Pemex workers voiced
similar complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Political activism by government employees on their time and
with their own resources is not prohibited in Mexico, but any use
of those resources is considered a crime, as is job-related
political pressure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
