<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Counterfeits Cost Russia Millions  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- At least 40 percent of alcohol produced in Russia
is bootleg, contributing to millions of dollars of potential tax
revenues the government is losing annually to counterfeit goods,
officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   From 40 to 50 percent of Russia's alcohol is not licensed, as is
35 to 45 percent of tobacco produced in Russia, said Vladimir
Samoilenko, who heads a tax and investment center for former Soviet
republics, according to the ITAR-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
   Samoilenko was speaking at an international conference in Moscow
on property rights.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian government loses hundreds of millions of dollars
annually because of counterfeit goods, the director of Russia's
Patent Committee, Alexander Korchagin, was quoted as telling the
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Korchagin said 1,000 criminal proceedings were instituted last
year over ownership rights, ITAR-Tass reported.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Russian officials claimed to be making progress on
stemming the illegal alcohol trade, bringing it down to 35 percent
of all alcohol production. But bootleg alcohol is still widely
available and inexpensive, and the poor quality contributes to
thousands of alcohol poisoning deaths every year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
