<HEADLINE> Second suspect convicted in murder of elderly women  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SCHENECTADY, N.Y. (AP) - A 20-year-old man was convicted of
murder Tuesday, the second person linked to a burglary that ended
in the bludgeoning death of two elderly women.
</P>
<P>
   A jury deliberated 10 years before convicting George Johnson
Tuesday. The Schenectady man was convicted of 10 counts against him
including murder and burglary. He faces 15 years to life.
</P>
<P>
   Matilda DiMaria Montenaro, 84, and her sister-in-law, Lois
DiMaria, 81, were found dead Dec. 16, 1998 in different rooms of
the city house they shared. A fire was set after the slayings, and
investigators discovered the women's bodies while responding to an
alarm.
</P>
<P>
   After the murders, upset community leaders and outraged citizens
raised a reward of $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   Also charged in the crime is Terrence Travis Townsend, 19, of
Schenectady, charged with two counts of first-degree burglary.
Townsend was not charged with murder.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said much of the evidence for Townsend's charges
came from testimony he and another suspect, Aaron Umber, gave at a
sentencing hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Umber, 22, has admitted to two counts of second-degree murder
and related charges of robbery, burglary and arson in exchange for
a maximum prison term of 40 years to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent L. O'Connor, 31, has not been charged in connection with
the killings but prosecutors are introducing evidence linking him
to the crimes in order to get him a maximum term of life in prison
as a persistent felony offender.
</P>
</TEXT>
