<HEADLINE> Small craft loses power, makes emergency landing  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   COLONIE, N.Y. (AP) - A small airplane lost power 15,000 feet
above Albany International Airport then made a forced crash landing
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody was hurt in the 10 p.m. crash landing on Runway 1 at the
airport, according to airport spokesman Doug Myers.
</P>
<P>
   The three men were en route from Rochester to Connecticut when
the Piper Malibu lost all power, Myers said. The pilot circled the
airport twice then approached the runway from the south.
</P>
<P>
   When he landed the plane, the nose gear was either still in the
raised position or collapsed upon impact, Myers said.
</P>
<P>
   Runway 1 was closed for about an hour but Myers said no flights
were delayed as a result of the crash.
</P>
<P>
   An investigator from the Federal Aviation Administration's
Flight Standard Division was headed to the scene late Tuesday.
</P>
