<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 23:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official Probes Chavez Resignation  </HEADLINE>
Military officer under investigation after calling for Chavez to
resign
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Venezuela's defense minister said
Tuesday he had ordered an investigation into comments by a military
officer claiming disgruntled members of the armed forces want
President Hugo Chavez to resign.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement by Defense Minister Ismael Eliezer Hurtado came
one day after a videotape was released to the media of an interview
with Capt. Luis Garcia, a member of the national guard, who said
some officers want Chavez to step down.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia said a group of military officers had been meeting over
the last six months with the goal of seeking Chavez resignation and
made a direct appeal during the 10-minute interview with
Globovision, a Venezuelan television network.
</P>
<P>
   ''Be intelligent, Mr. President, and resign,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Defense minister Hurtado said military officials were examining
the interview and considering what action, if any, to take against
Garcia. As a member of the armed forces, Garcia is prevented by law
from making political statements.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia's comments come a month ahead of presidential elections
in Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show the left-leaning Chavez enjoying an advantage of up
to 20 points over Arias Cardenas, who has the support of the middle
and upper classes.
</P>
<P>
   l
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
