<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kosovo OK Colombia Emergency Bill  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Leading lawmakers agreed Tuesday to the
outlines of an emergency bill financing Colombia's battle against
drug traffickers, U.S. peacekeepers in Kosovo and recovery from
storms, fires and other domestic disasters, one participant said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Young, R-Fla., chairman of the House Appropriations
Committee, declined to provide an exact figure but said it would be
between $9 billion and the $12 billion limit that House and Senate
leaders set for the measure last week. That would make the package
double the $5.2 billion President Clinton requested at the
beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders hope to work out final details on Wednesday and push the
entire bill through Congress by week's end, when lawmakers are due
to begin a one-week July 4 recess. Republicans want to finish the
bill quickly to avoid blame for any problems the Pentagon might
face as it juggles money to pay for U.S. peacekeepers in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it would be a bill that would be acceptable to House
and Senate'' leaders and the White House, Young said after he and
other lawmakers ended a closed-door bargaining session.
</P>
<P>
   Young said the measure would include $1.3 billion to help
Colombia's embattled government fight drug traffickers who control
broad swaths of the country, along with their leftist guerrilla and
right-wing paramilitary allies. Included is money for purchasing
helicopters and other supplies and training Colombian troops.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a victory for Clinton and House Speaker Dennis
Hastert, R-Ill., who have pushed for the aid as a way to combat
drug use in the United States. Colombia supplies most of the
cocaine used in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Still unresolved is whether to include compromise language
struck Tuesday that would lift the four-decade-old U.S. food
embargo against Cuba. There is strong opposition to that deal among
some senators, and Young indicated it might be left for inclusion
in some later bill.
</P>
<P>
   Aides and lawmakers had said earlier that to keep the bill
acceptable to Clinton, they would avoid including controversial
provisions changing laws.
</P>
<P>
   They said they would therefore omit a provision pushed by
Schering-Plough Corp. to win an extension of its patent for
Claritin, the popular and profitable allergy drug. Also left off
the bill was language by Sen. Judd Gregg, R-N.H., aimed at
extending a lucrative patent his alma mater, Columbia University,
has on a process its scientists invented for making some widely
sold biotechnology drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Both of those measures could end up on other bills.
</P>
<P>
   ''We do not want a veto of the bill,'' said Senate
Appropriations Committee Chairman Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, when
bargainers held a brief public session.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Hastert and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss.,
had discussed a tentative compromise of about $5.5 billion, said
participants speaking on condition of anonymity. That was abandoned
as unrealistically low.
</P>
<P>
   Lott had criticized earlier, larger versions of the package for
being too costly and containing unnecessary items, and Senate work
on the measure virtually halted for two months. The House approved
$13 billion in March, mostly by adding extra money for the
Pentagon, while the Senate approved roughly $9 billion last month.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, participants said that as part of the final package,
the House and Senate would each get a $100 million kitty for
various lawmakers' home-district projects.
</P>
<P>
   Young would reveal few details of the bill. But earlier,
participants said that besides money for Colombia, the compromise
would include $2.05 billion to repay the Pentagon for the costs of
5,700 American troops serving with the NATO peacekeeping team in
Kosovo; at least $660 million for rebuilding from the
government-set fires that ravaged Los Alamos, N.M.; and $250
million to help North Carolina and other states recover from last
September's Hurricane Floyd and other agricultural problems.
</P>
<P>
   Aides have said that Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., chairman of
the Senate Appropriations Committee's subcommittee that oversees
foreign aid, had been trying to keep the Colombia money out of the
emergency package.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving it in the regular foreign aid bill could increase
pressure on Clinton to sign it. Lott nevertheless indicated that in
the name of completing the emergency bill quickly, McConnell seemed
ready to let the Colombia money be included.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-27-00 2323 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000627.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indians 12, Royals 1  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Jim Thome homered twice, went 4-for-4
and drove in four runs and Richie Sexson also had four RBIs as the
Cleveland Indians defeated the Kansas City Royals 12-1 Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Sexson and Sandy Alomar also homered for the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Finley (6-5) allowed one run through five innings, but
threw 111 pitches. He allowed runners in four of his five innings,
stranding six.
</P>
<P>
   Mac Suzuki (3-2) allowed four runs in 5 1-3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The game capsulized the trouble the Royals have had all season.
Kansas City has allowed 128 home runs, the most in the majors this
season. The Royals also lead the American League with 329 walks --
issuing five Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians' 120 home runs are third best in the American League
and fourth most in the majors. Cleveland has received 302 walks,
the third most in the AL.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians took the lead in the second when Thome hit his 22nd
home run of the season, a 435-foot blast to right-center. Sexson
then added a two-run homer in the fourth to make it 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg Zaun cut it to 3-1 in the fifth with a leadoff home run
that just cleared the fence in left-center.
</P>
<P>
   Sexson got his third RBI in the sixth, driving home David
Justice with a sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   That marked the end for Suzuki, who was relieved by Brett
Laxton. Laxton gave up four earned runs on one hit, two walks and a
hit batter in just one inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians got three more in the eighth to take an 11-1 lead on
Alomar's two-run home run and an RBI single Omar Vizquel. Thome's
second homer in the ninth closed the scoring.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Thome has hit 17 of his 23 home runs with the bases empty.
It was his 13th career multihomer game. ... Finley improved his
career mark to 15-10 against the Royals, including 9-4 in Kansas
City. ... Rey Sanchez played in his 50th consecutive game without
an error, two shy of the club record for a shortstop, set by Greg
Gagne in 1993. ... Kenny Lofton was hit below the right knee by a
pitch with one out in the seventh. Lofton, who has a bruised shin,
was taken to the hospital for precautionary X-rays. Roberto Alomar
left the game with a sore left ankle. ... The Royals have allowed
43 percent of their runs on home runs (198 of 462).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
