<DOCNO> APW20000627.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dodgers Waive Hershiser  </HEADLINE>
By BETH HARRIS
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Orel Hershiser wanted to be the link between
the Dodgers' last World Series title in 1988 and their next one.
</P>
<P>
   But the team's pitching hero during much of the 1980s was waived
Tuesday, a day after he gave up eight runs in the second inning of
a 9-5 loss to San Diego. The inning was one of the worst of his
18-year career.
</P>
<P>
   ''I understand and support the club's decision of giving me my
release after the way I performed,'' Hershiser said in a statement.
''I am grateful that I was given the opportunity to play for the
Dodgers this season.''
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser, the 1988 NL Cy Young winner and World Series MVP,
struggled after rejoining the club as a free agent last winter. His
ERA was 13.14 in 10 appearances that included six starts but just
24 2-3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was totally committed to baseball and the Dodgers and
helping us win, and to have it end this way ...'' said manager
Davey Johnson, his voice trailing off.
</P>
<P>
   ''Even though he struggled, I loved having him out there,''
Johnson said. ''It's probably one of the toughest things I've been
associated with, and I've been associated with a bunch of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Dodgers manager Tommy Lasorda, now the team's senior vice
president, had an emotional visit with Hershiser after Monday
night's debacle.
</P>
<P>
   ''We both cried, and he was really broken-hearted,'' Lasorda
said. ''I told him, 'You're the same with the Dodger fans in this
city as (Sandy) Koufax and (Don) Drysdale.' They were role models
to a lot of youngsters.''
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser, 41, had voluntarily gone to the minors last month
before rejoining the team. He said he plans to take a few days to
think about his future, but his major league pitching career could
be finished.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's sad to see him go down like this,'' said bullpen coach
Rick Dempsey, who caught Hershiser during the Dodgers' championship
season in '88. ''I hope it's over with, that he doesn't have to go
back out there. He's got nothing to prove to anybody anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser pitched a major league record 59 consecutive scoreless
innings in 1988 and had a 23-8 record.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think it'll ever be matched in my lifetime,'' Dempsey
said of the 59 scoreless innings. ''He did things I've never seen a
pitcher able to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser was given the nickname ''Bulldog'' by then-manager
Lasorda during his first stint with the Dodgers from 1983-94,
because Lasorda said no batters would be intimidated by a pitcher
named Orel.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Daly, the team's managing partner, and general manager Kevin
Malone both realized while watching Hershiser on Monday night that
a change was necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can't be in a situation where you're eight runs behind in
the second inning of a game. We have to have the best 25 men on the
roster. It was a tough call,'' Daly said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was frustrating and disappointing for me and Bob when we
were sitting together watching the game,'' Malone said. ''I felt
bad for Orel but I also understand the predicament that Davey's in
with our bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are shorthanded in the bullpen because of injuries,
and aches and pains have plagued others on the active roster.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie right-hander Eric Gagne was recalled from Triple-A
Albuquerque to start Wednesday night's game against San Diego. He
was optioned to Albuquerque when Hershiser was recalled from his
self-imposed minor-league stint.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser, who pitched 353 career games in Los Angeles, briefly
recaptured some of his former glory when he won the Dodgers' home
opener this season, beating Cincinnati 8-1. But he went into a
severe tailspin and lost his last five decisions.
</P>
<P>
   He developed control problems and hasn't won since the home
opener. He matched a modern major league record, hitting four
batters in a 10-3 loss to Houston on April 19. Hershiser did it in
just 1 1-3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   After throwing one pitch five feet over the catcher's head
Monday night, Hershiser hit the next batter, Ryan Klesko, with a
pitch that bounced and hit his left big toe.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know that he doesn't in his heart believe that it's over
with, and he won't for a long time,'' Dempsey said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right now he's wondering to myself whether it's really over
with, he doesn't know. He thinks he can come back from this and
maybe pitch for a couple more years. Under certain circumstances, I
wouldn't bet against him,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A three-time All-Star, Hershiser has a career record of 204-150
with a 3.48 ERA. He was with Cleveland, San Francisco and the New
York Mets before returning to the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are responsible for paying Hershiser's entire $2
million salary this year and a $500,000 buyout of next year's $2
million option. The buyout is deferred at 5 percent interest,
payable on July 1 each starting in 2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-27-00 2324 </TRAILER>
