<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 23:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
Arnold Black
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLEMONT, Mass. (AP) -- Arnold Black, a composer and violinist
who started a beloved classical music program in the rural
Berkshires, died Sunday. He was 77.
</P>
<P>
   Black died two days after the Mohawk Trails Concert series
opened its 31st year.
</P>
<P>
   Black moved to the Berkshires in 1970 to escape his hectic life
in New York. Born in Philadelphia, he attended the Julliard School
of Music and wrote music for theater, film, television and concert
halls.
</P>
<P>
   Black engaged world-renowned artists for the concert series,
which could satisfy the most discriminating classical music fan.
</P>
<P>
   Black was composer-in-residence at The Circle in the Square in
New York City in the 1950s. He wrote the score for the production
of James Joyce's ''Ulysses in Nighttown,'' starring Zero Mostel.
</P>
<P>
   He also wrote music for the National Shakespeare Company and for
films including ''River Song,'' ''Black Harvest,'' ''Memorial
Day,'' ''Empire of Reason,'' and ''Peace for Our Time,'' which he
co-composed with Eric Clapton.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, his opera ''The Phantom Tollbooth,'' based on the
children's classic, premiered with Opera Delaware.
</P>
<P>
Diane Divers Blair
</P>
<P>
   FAYETTEVILLE, Ark. (AP) -- Diane Divers Blair, a University of
Arkansas political science professor who was a longtime friend and
adviser to President Clinton, died Monday. She was 61 and had
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Blair's friendship with the president and first lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton dated to the early 1970s when both Clintons taught
at the University of Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, she was a member of the national Democratic Platform
Committee in the convention that nominated Clinton to run against
President Bush, and she served as senior researcher during the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   When he took office the following year, Clinton appointed her to
the board of the Corporation for Public Broadcasting. She was
elected chairman of the panel in 1997, serving the maximum two
years as leader.
</P>
<P>
   She was noted for her 1988 book ''Arkansas Politics and
Government: Do the People Rule'' that is still in use in courses at
the university.
</P>
<P>
   When she married James B. Blair in 1979, then-Gov. Clinton
performed the ceremony. The Blairs' relationship with the Clintons
drew scrutiny after it was reported that in the late '70s James
Blair, a lawyer for Tyson Foods, led Hillary Rodham Clinton to
profit greatly from a small commodities investment.
</P>
<P>
Larry Kelley
</P>
<P>
   HIGHTSTOWN, N.J. (AP) -- Larry Kelley, the second winner of the
Heisman Trophy, died Tuesday. He was 85.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley won the Heisman, college football's highest individual
honor, in 1936 after an All-America season as a receiver at Yale.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 13, 1934, Yale recorded one of its greatest upset wins
when Kelley made a one-handed grab of a 49-yard pass from
quarterback Jerry Roscoe, scoring the only touchdown in a 7-0
victory that snapped Princeton's 15-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Kelley became the second Heisman Trophy winner to
auction his prize to the public. The trophy sold for $328,110 --
$100,000 more than the price paid for O.J. Simpson's Heisman in
February 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley had suffered a stroke six months earlier and said he
wanted to raise money for his 18 nieces and nephews.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley was elected to the National Football Hall of Fame in
1969.
</P>
<P>
Pierre Pflimlin
</P>
<P>
   STRASBOURG, France (AP) -- Pierre Pflimlin, former president of
the European Parliament and the European Council and longtime mayor
of Strasbourg, died Tuesday. He was 93.
</P>
<P>
   Pflimlin, a lawyer whose political career spanned four decades,
had vast experience in government and believed strongly in a
unified Europe. He was Strasbourg's centrist mayor from 1959 to
1983, was active in regional politics and represented the Bas-Rhin
region in the French National Assembly from 1946 to 1971.
</P>
<P>
   He became European Council president in 1955, and went on to
become finance minister and cooperation minister. A member of the
European Parliament from 1979-89, Pflimlin was vice president of
the assembly until 1984 before becoming president until 1987.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, he published his memoirs, ''Memoirs of a European under
the Fourth and Fifth Republic.''
</P>
<P>
Gerald Whitrow
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Gerald Whitrow, an influential astrophysicist
whose books studied the mathematical, cosmological, historical,
biological and psychological implications of time, died June 2. He
was 87.
</P>
<P>
   One of his most important works was the 1960's ''The Natural
Philosophy of Time.'' His 1972 book ''What is Time?'' and 1988's
''Time in History,'' explored such concepts as how time originated;
biological clocks; the relations between time, gravitation and the
universe; and whether time can be said to have a beginning and an
end.
</P>
<P>
   He felt time was unfairly eclipsed as a subject in modern
science.
</P>
<P>
   Whitrow graduated from Oxford University, and served as an
applied maths lecturer at London's Imperial College for 50 years.
He retired with the title of emeritus professor in 1979, though he
remained actively involved as a senior research fellow almost up
until his death.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-27-00 2325 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
