<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-27 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAS To Resolve Peru Crisis  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- Police used tear gas to disperse about 300
female protesters -- dressed in black and carrying cardboard coffins
-- late Tuesday who were awaiting the arrival of an Organization of
American States delegation.
</P>
<P>
   The OAS mission, led by OAS General Secretary Cesar Gaviria and
Canadian Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy, was due to arrive in Lima
shortly before midnight for a three-day round of meetings with
government and opposition officials to help improve Peru's
democracy in the wake of President Alberto Fujimori's tainted
re-election victory.
</P>
<P>
   The OAS refused to monitor last month's runoff, saying the
election was ''far from what could be considered free or fair.''
</P>
<P>
   But the 34-member body later rejected calls from the United
States to question the legitimacy of Fujimori's win or consider
collective sanctions. Instead it decided to send Gaviria and
Axworthy to help resolve Peru's political crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The women had planned a vigil outside the luxury hotel where the
delegation is scheduled to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ''I came to protest against the dictatorship. We are tired of
Fujimori after 10 years,'' said Maria Arela Melo, a 53-year-old
grandmother of two. ''There is no freedom of expression.''
</P>
<P>
   They were forced to disband by hundreds of riot police who
blocked side streets in a six-block radius around the hotel.
Throughout the evening the police fired tear gas at any protesters
who tried to reassemble.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori has promised to revamp Peru's democratic institutions
after claiming an unprecedented third five-year term in a May 28,
presidential runoff, which followed a campaign riddled with
irregularities and allegations of government fraud.
</P>
<P>
   His challenger, Alejandro Toledo, who boycotted the election, is
demanding a new ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori's foes contend that the autocratic leader plans
cosmetic changes to appease the international community.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori's National Intelligence Service is accused of waging a
campaign of dirty tricks and intimidation against his opposition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
