<HEADLINE> Orioles 6, Red Sox 3, 10 Innings  </HEADLINE>
By HOWARD ULMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Charles Johnson hit a two-run homer in a five-run
10th inning as the Baltimore Orioles ended a nine-game losing
streak Tuesday night with a come-from-behind 6-3 win over the
Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Pinch-hitter Harold Baines started the inning by lining a single
off the right arm of Derek Lowe (2-3). Johnson jumped on a 3-2
pitch and drove his 16th homer of the season high over the
left-field wall, his 10th in his last 27 games.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore loaded the bases on an error, a walk and a single,
scored two runs on Jeff Conine's single and another when Cal Ripken
reached on a fielder's choice when third baseman Manny Alexander's
throw to second to get Conine was late.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe, who entered with a 1-0 lead in the ninth, blew a save for
the third time in 20 chances as Boston lost for the eighth time in
10 games. Baltimore is only 2-14 in its last 16 road games.
</P>
<P>
   Nomar Garciaparra hit his eighth homer, a two-run shot off Alan
Mills in the bottom of the 10th. After Mike Stanley's single, Buddy
Groom relieved for his third save in nine chances.
</P>
<P>
   Boston wasted a chance to in the bottom of the ninth after
loading the bases with two outs on a single by Morgan Burkhart, an
intentional walk to Scott Hatteberg and a walk to Darren Lewis.
Mike Trombley (3-2) retired Jose Offerman on a groundout.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe started the ninth by striking out Mike Bordick before
Delino DeShields doubled, Albert Belle then singled to center for
his 31st RBI in his last 27 games.
</P>
<P>
   Offerman, who entered with a .233 batting average, had broken up
a scoreless game between Mike Mussina and Pete Schourek with a
run-scoring single in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Hatteberg opened the inning with a single and took second
on Alexander's sacrifice bunt. Curtis Pride struck out before
Offerman came through.
</P>
<P>
   He hit a liner to right in front of Belle, and Hatteberg scored
as Conine cut off the throw. After Hatteberg crossed the plate,
Offerman was tagged out by Conine in a rundown.
</P>
<P>
   Mussina, 3-1 in his previous four games, struck out a
season-high 10 batters. Schourek, 0-3 in seven starts since his
last win on May 15, allowed four hits, struck out four and walked
two. Each pitched seven innings.
</P>
<P>
Notes: RF Trot Nixon was placed on Boston's 15-day disabled list,
retroactive to Saturday, with a strained right hamstring. ...
Burkhart, who had 17 homers and 54 RBIs for Pawtucket of the
International League, was called up Tuesday to replace Nixon on the
roster. He singled in his first major-league at bat and went
2-for-4 with a walk. ... B.J. Surhoff extended his hitting streak
to 20 games, one short of his career high, with a single in the
seventh. ... The Orioles' 11-31 road record is the worst in
baseball. ... Baltimore sent only three batters to the plate in the
third, fourth, sixth and eighth innings despite putting runners on
base in each inning. Two runners were erased on double plays and
Conine and DeShields were caught stealing.
</P>
</TEXT>
